[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction to the Harry Attack"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Introduction to the Harry Attack@@HeaderEnd@@ } 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 g6
{ This is, of course, a common position for the d4 and c4 player to reach, as Black lines up to play the King's Indian or the Grünfeld. Now White usually develops a knight or sometimes reaches for the g- or f-pawn, but there is another pawn that can be pushed – in a way you may never have considered before! }
3. h4
{ Harry's History  This is it. Dare we call this advance of Simon's favourite pawn the Harry Attack? Simon was the first grandmaster to play this bold advance, so we think you can safely think of the opening as the Harry Attack! That debut game was back in the Swiss Open Championship of 2008 against FM Patrick Hugentobler.  Simon's games and decent results with 3.h4!? unsurprisingly soon led to others following suit, beginning with those ever-creative grandmasters Ivan Ivanisevic, Richard Rapport and Veselin Topalov. It wasn't until 2019 though, when Alexander Grischuk sprung 3.h4!? on Maxime Vachier-Lagrave at the Riga Grand Prix, that the interest level went up another notch.  Grischuk repeated the move four times in the subsequent Paris Rapid & Blitz. The elite were quick to take note and at blitz even Magnus Carlsen and Ding Liren have wheeled out 3.h4!?, while MVL has even been tempted over to the white side, as we'll see shortly.  Harry's Purpose  So what are White's aims with this bold advance of Harry? In short, he aims to take Black out of his comfort zone and away from his comfortable blanket of Grünfeld or King's Indian theory as early as move three. Already, Black must decide: is 4.h5 an issue? That advance is certainly high on White's agenda, if not always as early as move four.  Sometimes White will get in h4-h5, then exchange on g6, opening up the h-file and launching a strong attack, especially if Black has already castled. Other times Harry may even press on to h6, suffocating Black and causing problems for his dark-squared bishop and king.  It's also important to be aware that Grünfeld players will find it no easy task to break with ...d5 without allowing White a pleasant early initiative. We'll appreciate why a little more in the upcoming illustrative games, but first we should mention that 3.h4!? still very much packs a punch at all levels – it was, after all, only seen in 91 games that made The Week in Chess in the course of 2021!  Good luck with 3.h4 and especially enjoy your early adventures with Harry!  Chessable Note  There is no separate chapter for model games since some of the games are annotated as an introduction to the opening, while others are intended as model games for specific variations. Therefore you will find some games in the introduction chapter and some at the end of the theory chapter to which they belong. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "1A | Simon Williams – Alexandre Platel | Dieppe 2009"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Simon Williams – Alexandre Platel@@HeaderEnd@@Dieppe Open 2009 }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 { Here we go...! } 3... d5
{ Simon's early non-GM opponents did show a remarkable desire to insist on an immediate reaction in the centre and Grünfeld-like play. So too may many club players when surprised by 3.h4. }
4. cxd5 Qxd5
{ 4...Nxd5  5.h5  is very nice for White, but bringing the queen out so early can hardly be warranted. }
5. Nc3
{ Of course. White develops with tempo and will now follow up with e2-e4 unless Black tries a Scandinavian-style pin. }
5... Qa5 6. Bd2
{ Another example of simple and strong play. Simon simply breaks the pin and creates future discoveries against the black queen.  He can well recall to also be tempted by  6.h5!?  Nxh5  7.e4  , which would offer fantastic play for a pawn, but there's no need to sacrifice one... just yet! }
6... Qb6
{ A rather greedy choice, eyeing the b2- and d-pawns.  The Scandinavianesque  6...c6  would have been safer, although after  7.e4  White has pretty much everything you could want from the opening: ideal central control and ideas of quickly prising open the h-file with h4-h5.  For example,  7...Bg7  8.e5!  Nd5  9.h5  when it would take a brave man to castle as Black, but otherwise h5-h6 may well jam up his development and White also has swift and easy development, not least with Bc4. }
7. h5
{ Inspired play. Rather than defend d4 or b2, Simon dangles a third pawn before Black and, of course, he can only take the pawns one at a time. }
7... gxh5
{ Rather ugly, if engine-approved. Simon had been hoping for:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pp1p/1q3np1/7P/3P4/2N5/PP1BPPP1/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nxh5?  when his big idea was  8.Rxh5!  gxh5  9.Nd5  Qd6  @@StartBracket@@  9...Qc6?  10.e4  is even worse for Black with Bb5 now a threat@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pp1p/3q4/3N3p/3P4/8/PP1BPPP1/R2QKBN1 w Qkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.e4  . White simply threatens Bf4 and Nxc7+,  a threat that is extremely hard to prevent, as  10...e5?  11.dxe5  Qxe5  loses to  12.Bc3  Qxe4+  13.Ne2  when there are just far too many threats.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pp1p/1q3np1/7P/3P4/2N5/PP1BPPP1/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qxb2?  would have been cleaned up by  8.Rb1  Qa3  9.Nb5  .  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pp1p/1q3np1/7P/3P4/2N5/PP1BPPP1/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qxd4  8.Nf3  Qb6  @@StartBracket@@or  8...Qd8  9.hxg6  fxg6  10.Qb3  when Ne5 is all set to highlight Black's rather vulnerable light squares and kingside.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pp1p/1q3np1/7P/8/2N2N2/PP1BPPP1/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9.hxg6  fxg6  10.e4  or even  10.Rh4!?  just leaves White with a powerful initiative and excellent play for the pawn. Indeed, he might well quickly overwhelm Black with some combination of Rc1,  e4-e5,  Ng5 and Na4. }
8. e4
{ Offering a second pawn to further White's initiative while also threatening to dislodge Black's only developed minor piece with 9.e5. }
8... Qxd4 9. Nf3 { With tempo. } 9... Qb6 10. Be3
{ Another improving move with tempo and now Platel elects to grab a third pawn for his suffering. }
10... Qxb2
{ Easy to criticise, but Black was set to suffer in any case, not least as  10...Qa5  11.e5  Ne4?  is pretty much impossible on account of the neat  12.Qd5!  Qxd5  13.Nxd5  Kd8  14.O-O-O  with a ginormous initiative for White. }
11. Bd4
{ A fine square for the bishop, eyeing not just the black queen @@StartBracket@@Nd5 is a huge threat@@EndBracket@@, but also the rook on h8 after e4-e5-e6. }
11... c5
{ This pretty much loses by force, but even after  11...Qa3  12.e5  Ng4  13.e6!  f6  @@StartBracket@@  13...Nf6  14.exf7+  Kxf7  15.Bc4+  Ke8  16.Ng5  fast becomes a massacre@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1p2p/4Pp2/7p/3B2n1/q1N2N2/P4PP1/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Bc4  White would have enjoyed superb compensation, with Nd5 one idea, Rb1 and Nb5 another and there's always Rxh5 too to strike on the other flank. }
12. Rb1 Qa3 13. Nb5
{ Everything continues to come with tempo. Black's queen will make it back to base, but she only returns there to find her realm in ruins. }
13... Qa5+ 14. Bc3 Qd8 15. e5
{ Naturally, White does not object to an exchange of queens and potential snap mate on c7. }
15... Ng4 16. e6
{ Simon continues to roll forwards as the word 'massacre' rather springs to mind. Do observe though just how much of a fish bone this pawn quickly proves to be in the black king's throat. }
16... f6
{ 16...Qxd1+?  17.Rxd1  Na6  does cover c7,  but there's another rook hanging too:  18.exf7+  Kxf7  19.Bxh8  . }
17. Qa4
{ Threatening discovered check and mate while also freeing d1 for the rook.  17.Qxd8+  Kxd8  18.Rd1+  would also have done the business. }
17... Nc6 18. Rd1 Qb6 19. Ba5
{ A neat finish, as if  19.Ba5  Qxa5+  20.Qxa5  Nxa5  21.Nc7  . } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "1B | Michael Basman – Nir Grinberg | Ramat Hasharon 1980"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Michael Basman – Nir Grinberg@@HeaderEnd@@Ramat Hasharon 1980 }
1. c4
{ This was the first game with the double-advance of Harry on move 3, albeit via a typically unusual Basman move order. Our route into the game would, of course, be:  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.h4!?  . }
1... g6 2. h4 Nf6 3. d4 { And so play transposes. } 3... Bg7
{ Black refuses to be intimidated and sees no reason to respond by blockading with his own h-pawn. Note how an immediate Grünfeld isn't really possible:  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5?!  5.h5  .  White already threatens to mess up Black's kingside structure with an exchange on g6 and is also ready to take over the centre with e2-e4. He already enjoys a very pleasant advantage, as we'll appreciate a little more in Line 1A of our opening theory chapter. }
4. Nc3
{ An important move. Content with having shocked Black and likely gained an early lead on the clock, White holds back on the further advance of Harry, ensuring that he won't be outgunned in the centre as he competes for the key e4- and d5-squares.  Objectively, the immediate advance of Harry should be labelled as dubious, although we still like  4.h5!?  as the advance might well scare Black at fast time controls. We'll take a quick look at this option here at the start of Chapter Four. }
4... d5
{ This is likely to be the reaction of a lifelong Grünfeld player. Yes, there is a white knight on c3 which will help Black in the event of  5.cxd5  Nxd5  , but White can do even better than exchange on d5. }
5. h5
{ Excellent use of Harry and a very powerful advance. Suddenly Black finds that if he grabs on h5 with the knight, he'll lose d5.  Meanwhile White threatens to gain a serious lead in development and a superb version of a main-line Grünfeld with  5...--  6.h6  Bf8  7.cxd5  Nxd5  8.e4  . }
5... Nxh5
{ The 1976 World Under-16 Champion decides that there's nothing better than to take. Let's have a rapid look at the alternatives to fully appreciate Black's early difficulties:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p3P/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...gxh5?  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.Rxh5  leaves White with a serious early initiative, not to mention h7 looking rather unhappy as well as the black king.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p3P/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4?  6.h6!  Bf8  7.e4  badly gums up Black's development while leaving White with a perfect centre.  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p3P/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c6?!  6.h6!  Bf8  7.Nf3  gives White a very pleasant version of a Schlecter Slav @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  and 4...g6 @@EndBracket@@. White can calmly complete development with Bf4,  Ne5,  e2-e3 and it might also be possible to be more aggressive, combining ideas of Ne5 with Qb3 and possibly Bg5.  All the while note the cramping effect of Harry. Even if the black king does manage to escape to g8,  it will always be vulnerable to mating attacks on both g7 and the back rank.  D@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p3P/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O !?  is a brave choice, but also Black's best move along with 5...Nxh5 :  D.1@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p3P/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.cxd5  Nxd5  and only then exchanging on g6 is decent too, but here  7.e4?!  Nxc3  8.bxc3  c5  would offer Black sufficient counterplay against White's centre in typical Grünfeld fashion.  D.2@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p3P/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.hxg6  hxg6  7.cxd5  Nxd5  8.Bh6!  . It's not every day that you can develop a bishop straight to rook-six @@StartBracket@@a6 or h6@@EndBracket@@ in one move! Here a rapid attack is very much top of White's agenda, as we'll see more in Line 1B.  E@@EndBracket@@ Finally, Black can't even fight for the initiative in typical Grünfeld fashion: @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p3P/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5?  6.h6!  Bf8  7.cxd5  .  Exchanging on d4 would now simply leave Black a pawn down and neither is the other central capture completely ideal:  7...Nxd5  8.e4  Nxc3  9.bxc3  . Once again, we find White bossing the position with his big centre and cramping pawn on h6. }
6. cxd5
{ Bagging an extra central pawn while simply intending to further dominate the centre with e2-e4. }
6... c6
{ Black tries to chip away at the powerful white centre, eyeing d4 for some counterplay, but White can now do much better than grab on c6. }
7. e4 cxd5 8. e5
{ A most powerful pawn sacrifice from the English chess legend that is IM Mike Basman. Black is now a pawn ahead, but just look at his dire kingside situation! The immediate threat is g2-g4, which rather discombobulates the defence. }
8... Bf8
{ Freeing a retreat square for the knight, but now White is able to develop in an unhurried and straightforward fashion. }
9. Nf3 Nc6
{ Likewise,  9...Bg4  would have been well met by  10.Qb3  , refusing to fear doubled pawns while seizing the initiative on the queenside. }
10. Qb3
{ A powerful spot for the queen and without a knight on f6, Black doesn't find it at all easy to cover his key pawn on d5. }
10... e6
{ Now the light-squared bishop becomes rather passive, but  10...Bg4?  would have been even worse:  11.Qxb7  and suddenly Black discovers there's no time to take on f3,  as well as that  11...Bd7  12.Nxd5  Rc8  13.Bb5  simply leaves White dominating the board.  For example,  13...Bg7  14.O-O  @@StartBracket@@Simple chess is rarely bad chess! Lacking an immediate knockout blow, White simply completes development while maintaining his firm grip on the position.@@EndBracket@@  14...O-O  15.Bxc6!  Rxc6  @@StartBracket@@  15...Bxc6?  16.Nxe7+  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@3q1rk1/pQ1bppbp/2r3p1/3NP2n/3P4/5N2/PP3PP1/R1B2RK1 w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Be3  when White's centre is secure, he's a clear pawn to the good and a7 is rather vulnerable. }
11. g4
{ Played with a cry of 'Forwards!'. Not only does this drive the knight backwards, but it also prevents it from re-emerging on f5. }
11... Ng7 12. Bh6
{ Another strong move from Basman, making maximum use of his dark-squared bishop. Now Black's bishop is tied to f8 and he also can't break with ...h5. Factor in the miserable bishop on c8 and his cause is already a pretty grim one. }
12... f5
{ A desperate bid for freedom, compared with, for example,  12...Qb6  13.Qxb6  axb6  14.a3  @@StartBracket@@keeping Black's knight out of b4@@EndBracket@@  14...Bd7  15.Rc1  .  Talk about being in full control! White might even follow up by increasing the pressure with Nb5 and Ng5. Alternatively, Bd3,  Kd2 and doubling rooks on the h-file is a pretty tempting plan. }
13. Bh3
{ Retaining full control.  13.exf6!?  Qxf6  14.Be2  was also good, intending to seize a strong initiative after O-O-O and probably a timely Bg5 and Ne5. }
13... Qb6
{ This leads to a miserable queenless middlegame, but even, say,  13...fxg4  14.Bxg4  Bd7  15.O-O-O !  would have been excellent for White. His king will be quite happy on c1 or b1,  while Ng5 will begin to turn up the heat against the black king. }
14. Qxb6
{ Inflicting further damage to Black's hideous structure and also making it even harder for Black to ward off Nb5 ideas. }
14... axb6 15. Ke2
{ Basman is understandably in no rush, although the engines do make a good case for upping the tempo with  15.gxf5!?  Nxf5  16.Bxf5  gxf5  17.Nb5  .  The main point is to secure a very powerful initiative, with Nc7+ the immediate threat and Ke2 followed by Rdg1 set to quickly target the black king wherever it runs, as will Ng5. }
15... fxg4
{ Grinberg grimaces and digs in for a long defence... or so he hopes. } 16.
Bxg4 Bd7 17. Nb5
{ A powerful leap and one which has been on White's agenda for a while now. That said, a good case could also be made for the unhurried  17.a3!?  , intending Kd3,  Rag1 and Ng5,  thereby keeping Black under heavy pressure. }
17... Nxe5
{ A decent defensive try from Grinberg, sacrificing the exchange for some freedom.  Instead,  17...Kf7  18.Nc7  would have threatened both the rook and Nxd5,  and even after  18...Ra4  @@StartBracket@@  18...Rd8?  19.Ng5+  Ke7  20.Nxh7!  is a useful tactic@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@5b1r/1pNb1knp/1pn1p1pB/3pP3/r2P2B1/5N2/PP2KP2/R6R w - - 5 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Ke3  Nxd4!?  20.Nxd4  Bc5  21.Rad1  White retains a large advantage. }
18. Nc7+ Kd8 19. Nxe5
{ A decent practical choice, declining the rook on a8 to go after the one on h8.  Instead,  19.Nxa8  Bb5+  20.Ke1  Nxg4  would have been a bit messy, although White does appear to still be clearly better after  21.a4  Bc6  22.Bd2!  and b2-b4,  which should enable him to extricate the cornered knight. }
19... Kxc7 20. Nf7 Rg8
{ Collapsing. Black needed to be happy to continue offering the exchange here with  20...Bb5+  21.Ke3  Nh5!  , although after  22.Bg5!  @@StartBracket@@and not  22.Nxh8??  Bxh6+  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r4b1r/1pk2N1p/1p2p1p1/1b1p2Bn/3P2B1/4K3/PP3P2/R6R b - - 5 22@@EndFEN@@  22...Rg8  23.Bxh5  gxh5  24.Bf4+  White would have retained a significant advantage with the safer king, the initiative and h5-pawn about to fall.  And even @@StartFEN@@r4b1r/1pkb1Nnp/1p2p1pB/3p4/3P2B1/8/PP2KP2/R6R b - - 1 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Nh5!  21.Bg5!?  @@StartBracket@@  21.Nxh8  Bxh6  22.Nf7  Bb5+  23.Ke1  Bg7  gives Black full compensation for the exchange with his bishop pair working well@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r4b1r/1pkb1N1p/1p2p1p1/3p2Bn/3P2B1/8/PP2KP2/R6R b - - 3 21@@EndFEN@@  21...Rg8  22.Bxh5  gxh5  23.Bf4+  @@StartBracket@@Preventing Black's king from running away and too much mess breaking out with  23.Rxh5  Kb8  24.Rxh7  e5!  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r4br1/1pkb1N1p/1p2p3/3p3p/3P1B2/8/PP2KP2/R6R b - - 1 23@@EndFEN@@  23...Kc8  24.Rxh5  would have offered White more than enough for the pawn, with Black's king and queen's rook still concerns and the white knight always able to return to occupy a fine outpost on e5. }
21. Bf4+ Kc8 22. Rxh7
{ Black might have saved the exchange, but suddenly Rc1+ is a mighty threat. }
22... Nf5 23. Bxf5
{ Simple chess. The bishop was no longer doing much on g4, so White exchanges it ahead of bringing his knight back to a dominant outpost. }
23... gxf5 24. Ne5 Bc6 25. Rc1
{ More simple chess: pin and if not win, at least retain full control. } 25...
Bd6 26. a3
{ Preventing any counterplay from Black, which  26.Nxc6?  Bxf4  would not have done. }
26... Ra4 27. Ke3
{ Continuing to deny Black any counterplay while introducing the rather deadly threat of Nxc6. }
27... Rg4
{ Easy to criticise, but without this slightly desperate try it would still have been a massacre: for example,  27...Rd8  28.Nxc6  Bxf4+  29.Kxf4  bxc6  when White can harvest and even deploy his king yet further forwards:  30.Rxc6+  Kb8  31.Rxb6+  Ka8  32.Ke5!  .  Also winning would be @@StartFEN@@2k3r1/1p5R/1pbbp3/3pNp2/r2P1B2/P3K3/1P3P2/2R5 b - - 2 27@@EndFEN@@  27...Bxe5  28.Bxe5  when the slow motion threat is Rc7+ Kd8; Rh1-h7 or if  28...Kd8  29.Rch1  b5  30.Rc7  b4  31.Rhh7  Rf8  32.Bd6  Rg8  33.axb4  when the superiority of White's pieces over their counterparts will be summed up as the king strolls in via f4 and e5,  or with  33...Ra1  34.b5!  Bxb5  35.Rxb7  . }
28. Nxg4
{ Yet more simple chess and an easier path to calculate than the also winning  28.f3!?  . }
28... Bxf4+ 29. Kxf4 Rxd4+ 30. Ke5
{ Never forget to make full use of the most powerful piece in most endgames, the king! }
30... Rxg4 31. Kxe6 Rf4
{ This is quickly shown to be hopeless, but even  31...Re4+!?  32.Kxf5  Re2  wouldn't save the day after  33.f4  Rxb2  34.Ke6  when White's active king allied to his powerful rooks and passed f-pawn should prove decisive. }
32. Rc2 Kb8 33. Ke5 Rf3 34. Rf7
{ White is about to acquire a passed f-pawn after all. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "1C | Victor Mikhalevski – Nisim Iliaguev | Safed 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Victor Mikhalevski – Nisim Iliaguev@@HeaderEnd@@Israeli Open, Safed 2021 }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 h5
{ The young Israeli FM playing Black here is by no means the only opponent whose reaction to h2-h4 is to think: Best stop h4-h5 as soon as I can.  Blocking so cannot be a terrible choice, but the inclusion of h4 and ...h5 does allow White some handy extra options compared to normal lines. }
4. Nc3 d5
{ Opting for Grünfeld play after all and in a situation where Black won't lose a pawn in the centre or be overrun by h4-h5.  The alternative is  4...Bg7  5.e4  d6  , which is likely to be the choice of a King's Indian player. White now has a few tempting options, of which angling for an improved version of a Petrosian variation might be best:   6.Be2  @@StartBracket@@Keeping Black out of g4. Those who prefer something more immediately aggressive should consider both  6.Bg5!?  followed by Qd2 and the Sämisch style  6.f3  .@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppb1/3p1np1/7p/2PPP2P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...O-O  7.Nf3  .  This is, of course, a main line King's Indian with h4 and ...h5 inserted and the difference can quickly be felt, not least in the event of  7...e5  8.d5  a5  @@StartBracket@@Black's main move in the position without the h-pawns advanced@@EndBracket@@  9.Ng5!  .  A fine spot for the knight, not least as Black may find himself rather vulnerable on e6 should he break with ...f5. White can continue simply with O-O,  but he can also, of course, angle for more aggressive play with Be3 and f2-f3,  looking to Qd2 and O-O-O or even g2-g4. }
5. Bg5
{ Forcing the pace. White simply prepares to shatter Black's structure and pick off d5.  Depending on what experience you have against the Grünfeld, you may also wish to consider  5.cxd5  Nxd5  and then either  6.e4  or  6.Bd2!?  . In both cases, White will hope to eventually exploit the slight weakening of the black kingside with ...h5. }
5... Bg7
{ The most natural reply.  In contrast,  5...dxc4?!  6.e4  does not look at all advisable for Black: for instance,  6...c5  7.d5  @@StartBracket@@or even 7.dxc5!?@@EndBracket@@  7...Bg7  8.Bxc4  a6  9.a4  .  White retains control, most certainly has ideas of e4-e5 followed by d5-d6,  and all the while Black is badly hampered by his inability to kick the bishop away from g5 with ...h6.  Just as without the h-pawns having been pushed, Black might consider other more independent options and we'll examine both @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp2/5np1/3p2Bp/2PP3P/2N5/PP2PPP1/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne4  6.cxd5  @@StartBracket@@see here @@EndBracket@@ and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp2/5np1/3p2Bp/2PP3P/2N5/PP2PPP1/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5!?  @@StartBracket@@see here @@EndBracket@@ in Line 1C. }
6. Nf3
{ Straightforward development as White clamps down further on the e5- and g5-squares, while asking Black: just how will you free your position with ...h6 not being possible? }
6... O-O
{ A pawn sacrifice. We'll explore the alternatives in Line 1C: ...Ne4?!, ...dxc4!?, ...c6. }
7. Bxf6
{ By no means forced, but obtaining an extra central pawn is rarely a terrible deal. }
7... Bxf6 8. cxd5
{ And so we find Black with an unopposed dark-squared bishop, but also a pawn down and slightly cramped by that extra pawn on d5. In short, it's hard to believe that he should have sufficient compensation. }
8... c5
{ Hitting back on the dark squares.   8...c6  had previously been seen in Solomon-Aizenberg, Petah Tikva 2020, when White should have accepted:  9.dxc6  Nxc6  10.e3  . This shores up the extra pawn on d4 and looks pretty solid for White, who may simply complete development with Be2 and O-O.  A timely Qb3 may also prove useful @@StartBracket@@not only is an eye kept on b7,  but also f7,  meaning that Ng5 and even Bd3 could be a bit awkward for Black@@EndBracket@@, and even if he can get in ...e5,  it doesn't seem that Black can come close to equality, for example:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2pp2/2n2bp1/7p/3P3P/2N1PN2/PP3PP1/R2QKB1R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qa5  11.Qb3  e5?!  12.d5  Ne7  13.Nd2!  when Black's dark-squared bishop is shut out and White will begin to take over the board after Nc4.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2pp2/2n2bp1/7p/3P3P/2N1PN2/PP3PP1/R2QKB1R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bg4  11.Be2  Bxf3?!  12.Bxf3  e5  13.d5!  when Delroy the d-pawn looks like a rather useful asset indeed. }
9. dxc5
{ This works out well, but once again  9.dxc6!  was the route to a clear plus, as in our previous note. }
9... Qa5
{ 9...Nd7!  leaves Black two pawns down, but White can't hold on to both the extra units and...  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1npp2/5bp1/2PP3p/7P/2N2N2/PP2PPP1/R2QKB1R w KQ - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.g3!  Nxc5  11.Bg2  might yet retain a pull; Black's pieces are quite well coordinated, but a pawn is a pawn as they say.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1npp2/5bp1/2PP3p/7P/2N2N2/PP2PPP1/R2QKB1R w KQ - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.e4  Nxc5  11.e5  Bg7  should leave Black with sufficient compensation, with both ...Qb6 and ...Bg4 on their way. }
10. Qd2
{ Breaking the pin and so simply intending e2-e4, as well as ideas of just Rc1 or even Rd1. }
10... Rd8 11. e3
{ Keeping things tight at the back, although there was no especially good reason to reject the more ambitious  11.e4  . }
11... Qxc5
{ White quickly takes over after this.  Once again,  11...Nd7!  was indicated, although after  12.a3!  @@StartBracket@@slyly preparing a certain potential fork with b2-b4@@EndBracket@@  12...Bxc3  13.Qxc3  Qxc3+  14.bxc3  Nxc5  15.c4  Black's lead in development may not give him quite enough for a pawn, in part because both Rd1 and Nd4 will help White to retain control. }
12. Ng5
{ A powerful leap. Just because White has exchanged his early activity for an extra pawn doesn't mean that he can't still play actively. Just as the bishop earlier made good use of g5, so now does the knight.  White avoids any issues with ...Bg4, threatens Nge4 and all the while Black would be ill-advised to exchange on g5 and so weaken his king position. }
12... Qa5 { Scurrying away from Nge4 hits, not to mention ideas of Rc1. } 13.
Be2
{ Simple chess. Mikhalevski prepares to complete development and then make good use of his knight being on g5 to advance in the centre. }
13... Nc6
{ Note that while  13...Bxc3  14.Qxc3  Qxc3+  15.bxc3  Rxd5  would see Black regaining his pawn, after  16.Bc4  Rf5  17.e4  his rook isn't especially happy and it's also White who now leads in development.  Indeed, after, say, Rd1,  O-O,  e4-e5 and f2-f4 Black might well find his pieces in a bit of a logjam. }
14. Rd1 { And why not overprotect d5 before housing the king? } 14... Ne5
{ The point of Black's play, but while he can eye the c4- and g4-squares, his minor pieces are about to become targets for the white pawns to begin their gradual roll down the board. }
15. O-O Bf5 16. Kh1
{ Prudently avoiding any checks on the g1-a7 diagonal, although even after  16.e4  Bd7  17.f4!?  Ng4  18.e5  White would have been doing well on account of the fork-avoiding  18...Qb6+  19.Qd4!  . }
16... Rac8
{ Arguably a bit too slow, but even after the engines' preference of  16...Qb6!?  17.e4  Bd7  White appears to be doing well:  18.f4  Ng4  19.Bxg4  Bxg4  20.Nf3!  .  This keeps Black's bishops under control, prepares to roll forwards with e4-e5 and  20...Bxf3?  21.Rxf3  Bxh4  22.e5  would merely leave Black's remaining bishop in some trouble, not to mention his king. }
17. e4
{ Here we go... White's play may not have appeared super-aggressive between moves five and here, but with such an outpost on g5, not to mention an extra central pawn, he was always going to be looking for ways to first expand in the centre and then use that extra space to begin a direct attack after all. }
17... Bd7 18. f4 Nc4 19. Bxc4 Rxc4
{ There goes White's second bishop, but the pawn tsunami is really building up force by this point. }
20. e5
{ Logical and tempting, but it appears that  20.f5!  would have been even stronger, preparing to crash through with d5-d6 or if  20...Rd4  21.Qf4  Rxd1  22.Rxd1  .  Now e4-e5 is very much a threat, as is d5-d6 and  22...Qb4  23.Qc7!  would see some neat work by the white queen to retain a clear advantage after  23...Qb6  24.Qxb6  axb6  25.fxg6  fxg6  26.Kg1  on account of the still powerful centre. }
20... Bxg5
{ Good defence from Iliaguev and not  20...Bg7?  21.e6!  fxe6  22.Qd3  when White would have crashed through. }
21. hxg5 Bg4
{ Discombobulating, but even with his rook driven off the d-file, White is able to retain control and a clear plus. }
22. Rde1 { 22.Rc1!  was likely more exact, as we'll see shortly. } 22... Be6
23. d6
{ A big decision. It turns out well, but objectively White should have preferred  23.Rd1  , and if  23...Bg4  24.Rc1!  b5  25.a3  , thereby keeping Black's counterplay under control and hoping to only now edge forwards with d5-d6. }
23... exd6 24. exd6 Rc6
{ And there goes the d-pawn, but in return White is hoping to whip up a nasty attack. }
25. Rd1
{ White might like to go  25.Qe3  Rcxd6  26.Ne4  , but after  26...Rd4!  he doesn't seem to have more than a draw with  27.Nf6+  Kg7  28.f5!  Bxf5  29.Ne8+  Kg8  30.Nf6+  , unless Black now falls for  30...Kh8??  31.Qxd4!  . }
25... Rcxd6 26. Qxd6 Rxd6 27. Rxd6
{ Talk about a transformation of the position! The engines even now fractionally prefer Black, but White's position is arguably the easier to play, in part because if he can establish his knight on f6, mating nets will always be in the air. Moreover, two rooks for just a queen cannot be such a bad deal. }
27... Kg7 28. a3
{ Ruling out any notion of ...Qb4 or even ...b5-b4 as Mikhalevski refuses to rush. }
28... h4
{ Black's decision to try and expose the white king must be a good one, although we must not lose sight of the fact that his king too can easily become a target. }
29. Rd2
{ Avoiding any issues on the second rank and also preparing his line-closing next move. }
29... h3 30. g3
{ And so Black has a certain fish bone of his own on h3, but White should never get mated so long as his rook covers g2. }
30... Qa6 31. Re1 Qc6+
{ This only forces White's king on to a square where it can't easily be checked.  Instead,  31...Bg4!  is how the engines want to defend and after  32.Kh2  go  32...Bf3  . }
32. Kh2 b5
{ And just like that, Black's position veers from worse to lost as Mikhalevski's judgement pays off. Good judgement we should add, since at least from a practical perspective White's chances with the two rooks against the queen and with potential mating nets were always decent ones.  Here  32...Bc4!  was apparently required, preparing to throw a spanner in the works with ...Bd3 or if  33.Ne4  Qe6!  and the defence is just about holding, as with  34.Rd8  34...Qc6!  . }
33. Ne4
{ Suddenly there's nothing preventing White from installing his knight in all its glory on f6 and then calmly invading along the back rank with a rook. }
33... Qb6 34. Nf6 b4
{ 34...Kf8  would try to run away, but also runs into  35.Rxe6!  Qxe6  36.Rd8+  followed by mate or winning the queen. }
35. axb4 Qxb4 36. Ree2 { Calmly does it. Suddenly Rd8 is a very large threat. }
36... Qb6
{ Missing a tactic, but  36...Qe7  37.Re4  would have been followed by Red4 and Rd8,   @@StartFEN@@8/p4pk1/4bNp1/6P1/1q3P2/6Pp/1P1RR2K/8 b - - 1 36@@EndFEN@@  36...Qf8  37.Rd4  and Red2 is also all over, and so is @@StartFEN@@8/p4pk1/4bNp1/6P1/1q3P2/6Pp/1P1RR2K/8 b - - 1 36@@EndFEN@@  36...Qa5  37.b4!  . }
37. Rd6
{ Very pretty. The rook is clearly taboo in view of the check on e8, but declining it simply allows White to double up on the d-file. }
37... Qb5 38. Red2
{ There's simply nothing to be done about Rd8 and the mating net, as  38.Red2  Kf8  39.Rd8+  Ke7  merely walks into a different one:  40.Ng8  . }
