{ @@HeaderStart@@Kirill Alekseenko – Markus Ragger@@HeaderEnd@@European Club Cub, Struga 2021 }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7
{ Sometimes the immediate  3...c5  is seen, but after  4.d5  Black usually just goes  4...Bg7  with play transposing after  5.Nc3  . }
4. Nc3 c5
{ Striking out on the dark squares and played to assist the prospects of the fianchettoed bishop on g7. This is likely to be the choice of those with some experience of the Benoni. }
5. d5
{ Naturally, White seizes space and pushes on. He is now ready to expand with e2-e4 and may even have ideas of h4-h5 on the agenda. }
5... e6
{ Modern Benoni style. Now White can simply go  6.e4  , but there is a very tempting alternative: }
6. h5
{ The exclamation mark is partly for courage and shock value, but the advance is also a strong one. Indeed, we'll see that White quickly obtains full compensation and more than that for the pawn. }
6... Nxh5
{ To avoid being somewhat worse, Black must accept the pawn. For instance:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1pbp/4pnp1/2pP3P/2P5/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...a6?  would be far too slow and after  7.h6  Bf8  8.d6!  White dominates the board, and continues to do so in the event of  8...Qb6  9.Bf4  Qxb2?  10.Rh3  when Rb1 is one threat, Be5 an even bigger one.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1pbp/4pnp1/2pP3P/2P5/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d6?!  is a bit better, but  7.h6!  Bf8  8.e4  still leaves Black under the cosh, in part because there will always be mating ideas in the middlegame on g7.  C@@EndBracket@@ We should also mention that @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1pbp/4pnp1/2pP3P/2P5/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...O-O ?!  7.hxg6  @@StartBracket@@  7.h6  achieves less when Black can simply retreat and stay on the key diagonal:  7...Bh8  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp1p1pbp/4pnP1/2pP4/2P5/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQ - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...fxg6  prepares to meet  8.d6  with  8...b5!  , which is suddenly all rather unclear.  White can do much better, though, with simply @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp1p2bp/4pnp1/2pP4/2P5/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nf3  , heading for g5 and also intending to meet any capture on d5 with Nxd5. }
7. g4
{ Maximum aggression as White kicks the knight backwards before looking to jam up Black's development. }
7... Nf6 8. d6
{ The aforementioned jamming up. White is all now set to expand with e2-e4 and f2-f4,  with g4-g5 followed by Bg2 and Bf3 also very much an idea.   8.g5!?  Nh5  9.Bg2  tempts us too, we must admit, threatening Ne4 even more than the immediate Bf3. Black should probably react with  9...d6!  10.dxe6!  @@StartBracket@@trying to make maximum use of the fianchettoed bishop on g2@@EndBracket@@:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3pbp/3pP1p1/2p3Pn/2P5/2N5/PP2PPB1/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...fxe6?  11.Ne4!  might easily claim some victims. Either d6 is falling or Black set to fall into a trap:  11...d5  12.cxd5  exd5?  13.Nxc5!  Qa5+?!  14.Bd2  , and if  14...Qxc5  15.Rc1  .  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3pbp/3pP1p1/2p3Pn/2P5/2N5/PP2PPB1/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bxc3+!  11.bxc3  fxe6  . Here White might simply develop with  12.Be3!?  and Qd2,  or be more direct with  12.Bf3  when Black doesn't have to return the pawn, but  12...Ng7  13.Be4  Nf5  14.Nf3  would leave him behind in development and under ongoing pressure with Bf4 set to target d6 and aim to force a rather weakening ...e5. }
8... O-O
{ The Austrian Grandmaster is both an excellent theoretician and very strong player, but now finds himself clearly worse after just eight moves. Such is the strength of 3.h4! Instead:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1pbp/3Ppnp1/2p5/2P3P1/2N5/PP2PP2/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nxg4!?  would have been critical when:  A.1@@EndBracket@@ You may also wish to explore @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1pbp/3Pp1p1/2p5/2P3n1/2N5/PP2PP2/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.e4!?  when Black might well be tempted into a forcing and critical line,  9...Bxc3+  10.bxc3  Qf6  and now it's time for White to have some fun:  11.f3!  Qxc3+  12.Bd2  Qd4  13.fxg4!  Qxe4+  14.Qe2  Qxh1  15.Nf3  .  White is the exchange and four pawns down, but Black's dark squares are shot and his queen far from happy. The immediate threat is O-O-O and Bg2,  with  15...f6!  16.O-O-O  g5  the only defence according to the engines.  Here White can sacrifice on g5 then invade on e5 with the queen or even calmly go  17.Bg2!?  Qh6  and only then  18.Nxg5!  fxg5  19.Bc3  with full compensation for a rook and a possible repetition - but only if Black is able to walk such a defensive tightrope – after  19...Rg8  20.Rh1  Qf8  21.Rf1  Qxd6  22.Be5  Qe7  23.Bf6  Qf8  24.Be5  Qe7  25.Bf6  Qd6  26.Be5  , etc. Definite food for thought.  A.2@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1pbp/3Pp1p1/2p5/2P3n1/2N5/PP2PP2/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nb5  Na6  10.e4  retains full compensation. White always has Be2 if needed and simply wants to continue annexing space with f2-f4,  all the while as the monster pawn on d6 continues to badly interfere with Black's coordination.  Note too how well placed that fine knight on b5 is, eyeing c7,  overprotecting d6 and keeping Black's bishop out of d4.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1pbp/3Ppnp1/2p5/2P3P1/2N5/PP2PP2/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...b6!?  would perhaps have been the most sensible defence, when  9.Bg2  Nc6  10.e4  simply intends to steamroller Black with f2-f4 and e4-e5,  thereby retaining good compensation.  The critical line is probably  10...e5!  when  11.g5  Nh5  12.Rxh5  gxh5  is by no means ridiculous and White can also hit back in the centre:  11.f4  Bb7  @@StartBracket@@and not  11...exf4?  12.e5  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pb1p1pbp/1pnP1np1/2p1p3/2P1PPP1/2N5/PP4B1/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.g5!  Nh5  13.f5  .  Yes, Black does have a firm grip on d4 and can even go  13...Nd4!  , but  14.Bf3!  Ng3  @@StartBracket@@  14...Nxf3+?  15.Qxf3  is almost positionally winning for White; Be3 and O-O-O may simply follow, if not Nb5 or just Rxh5 and f5-f6,  thereby completely messing up Black's development and coordination.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pb1p1pbp/1p1P2p1/2p1pPP1/2PnP3/2N2Bn1/PP6/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 3 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Rh3  Nxf3+  16.Nxf3  Nxe4  17.Nxe4  Bxe4  18.f6  forces Black to sacrifice a piece @@StartBracket@@otherwise, Nxe5 will just clean him up@@EndBracket@@  18...Bxf6!  19.gxf6  Qxf6  .  Even here matters are rather unclear but after  20.Bh6  we'd be quite happy as White. Black does have four pawns for the piece, but Qe2 and O-O-O are on their way, that superbly cramping d6-pawn still lives and Black's dark squares are likely to remain shut for the rest of the game. }
9. e4
{ Thematic expansion and now e4-e5 is an actual threat, followed by the cheeky yet very strong Qd3 @@StartBracket@@or Qf3@@EndBracket@@ and Qh3. }
9... Nc6 10. Qf3
{ Route one stuff, but very dangerous route one stuff at that. } 10... h5
{ This looks like a reasonable defensive try, but actually seems to lose pretty much by force. So would have:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1p1pbp/2nPpnp1/2p5/2P1P1P1/2N2Q2/PP3P2/R1B1KBNR b KQ - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nd4  11.Qh3  Nc2+?  12.Kd1  Nxa1  13.e5  when, for example,  13...h5  14.exf6  Qxf6  15.Nf3  is just a massacre, with Bg5 but one huge threat.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1p1pbp/2nPpnp1/2p5/2P1P1P1/2N2Q2/PP3P2/R1B1KBNR b KQ - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...b5!   B.1@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p2p1pbp/2nPpnp1/1pp5/2P1P1P1/2N2Q2/PP3P2/R1B1KBNR w KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.e5?  Nxe5!  is the clever point when  12.Qxa8  Qb6  13.Qg2  Bb7  14.f3  bxc4  gives Black a huge amount of activity for a rook – we want to be having such fun, not finding ourselves on the receiving end of such a powerful initiative!  B.2@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p2p1pbp/2nPpnp1/1pp5/2P1P1P1/2N2Q2/PP3P2/R1B1KBNR w KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Qh3!  Bb7  is how the engines want to try and defend, although even here with  12.cxb5!?  Nd4  13.Bg5!  Re8  14.Rc1  White is able to retain control and a large advantage. He might simply complete development with Bc4 and Nge2,  and there's also a certain threat of e4-e5. }
11. gxh5 { Ripping open lines. } 11... Nxh5
{ After  11...Nd4?  White can do even better than go to h3,  with  12.Qg2!  :  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1p1pb1/3Ppnp1/2p4P/2PnP3/2N5/PP3PQ1/R1B1KBNR b KQ - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nc2+  13.Kd1  Nxa1  14.h6!  , which is a killer in view of  14...Bh8  15.h7+!  Nxh7  16.Qh3  and mates.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1p1pb1/3Ppnp1/2p4P/2PnP3/2N5/PP3PQ1/R1B1KBNR b KQ - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nxh5  13.Be2!  simply overwhelming:  B.1@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1p1pb1/3Pp1p1/2p4n/2PnP3/2N5/PP2BPQ1/R1B1K1NR b KQ - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nxe2  14.Ngxe2  doesn't exactly help the defence, with all of e4-e5 @@StartBracket@@so if ...Bxe5; Rxh5@@EndBracket@@, Bg5 and Ng3 sizeable threats.  B.2@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1p1pb1/3Pp1p1/2p4n/2PnP3/2N5/PP2BPQ1/R1B1K1NR b KQ - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nc2+  14.Kf1  Nxa1  15.Bxh5  gxh5  16.e5!  and there just isn't a defence. Black can ward off immediate mate after Bh6 with  16...f6  , but after  17.Ne4  fxe5  18.Bh6  Rf7  19.Nf3!  the armada is simply overwhelming.  White may be a rook and two pawns down, but he has five pieces in the attack and Nxe5 followed by Rg1 is about to wipe Black out. }
12. Be2
{ Simply intending to move the queen, then swipe the knight on the rim. } 12...
Nd4 13. Qh3
{ Once again,  13.Qg2!?  might have been even stronger:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1p1pb1/3Pp1p1/2p4n/2PnP3/2N5/PP2BPQ1/R1B1K1NR b KQ - 3 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nc2+  14.Kd1  Nxa1  15.Bxh5  is pretty much crushing, and if  15...Qf6  16.Be2  Qd4+  17.Bd2  Qxd6  18.Qh3  Rd8  19.Nf3  when it would be amazing if Black could survive with e4-e5 followed by Bg5 or Qh7+ and Bh6 but one threat.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1p1pb1/3Pp1p1/2p4n/2PnP3/2N5/PP2BPQ1/R1B1K1NR b KQ - 3 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nxe2  14.Ngxe2  b5  15.Bg5!  . All of a sudden Black lacks a single good move, since he doesn't want to be cleaned up by e4-e5 or Rxh5,  but  15...f6  16.Bh6!  is a lovely silent sacrifice, and if  16...Bxh6  17.Qxg6+  Bg7  18.Qxh5  followed by O-O-O and Rdg1. }
13... Qf6 14. f4
{ Highly thematic as White angles to suffocate Black with his pawn chain after e4-e5 and, yes, yet again, White is quite happy to sacrifice the rook on a1 to speed up his attack. }
14... Nc2+
{ Black decides that he might as well have a rook for his suffering, but now that suffering won't last for long.  The engines prefer  14...Nxe2!?  15.Ngxe2  Re8  , but even here  16.Qf3  simply looks extremely strong, with White all set to castle long and invite his remaining pieces to the party:  For instance  16...a6  17.Be3  Rb8  18.O-O-O  b5  19.Rxh5!  gxh5  20.Ng3  and there's just no real defence for Black to the upcoming threats down the open g-file. }
15. Kf1 Nxa1 16. Bxh5 gxh5 17. f5
{ The star follow-up and the main point behind Alekseenko's rook sacrifice. Black's queen is denied the use of g6, he can't really capture on f5 due to the resulting hole on d5, and, as such, is about to be cleaned up on the kingside. }
17... Re8
{ A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp1p1pb1/3Ppq2/2p2P1p/2P1P3/2N4Q/PP6/n1B2KNR b - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...exf5  18.Nd5  Qxd6  19.Bf4  Qe6  20.exf5  overloads the black queen and wins.  B@@EndBracket@@ As does @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp1p1pb1/3Ppq2/2p2P1p/2P1P3/2N4Q/PP6/n1B2KNR b - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...b5  18.Qxh5  Re8  19.Bg5  Qd4  20.f6!  Bxf6  21.Qh7+  Kf8  22.Bh6+  Bg7  23.Qh8  . }
18. Qxh5
{ Once again, Bg5 followed by f6+ is a deadly threat and there's simply no defence. Very rarely can such a strong player as Ragger have lost so brutally and with their queenside still largely untouched. }
18... exf5 19. Nd5 Qd4
{ A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1r1k1/pp1p1pb1/3P1q2/2pN1p1Q/2P1P3/8/PP6/n1B2KNR b - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Qxd6  20.Qh7+  @@StartBracket@@or even 20.exf5@@EndBracket@@  20...Kf8  21.Bh6  is absolutely devastating.  B@@EndBracket@@ As is @@StartFEN@@r1b1r1k1/pp1p1pb1/3P1q2/2pN1p1Q/2P1P3/8/PP6/n1B2KNR b - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Qg6  20.Ne7+  Rxe7  21.dxe7  . }
20. Ne2
{ A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1r1k1/pp1p1pb1/3P4/2pN1p1Q/2PqP3/8/PP2N3/n1B2K1R b - - 3 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Qxe4  21.Nf6+!  Bxf6  22.Qh7+  Kf8  23.Bh6+   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1r1k1/pp1p1pb1/3P4/2pN1p1Q/2PqP3/8/PP2N3/n1B2K1R b - - 3 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Qd1+  21.Kg2  Qxh1+  22.Kxh1  is absolutely hopeless for Black, so badly exposed is his king and so great White's threats. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "5A | Maxime Vachier-Lagrave – Peter Svidler | Saint Louis 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@M. Vachier-Lagrave – Peter Svidler@@HeaderEnd@@Sinquefield Cup, Saint Louis 2021 }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4
{ Talk about a statement of intent in the opening round, and from the man who would go on to win the tournament! }
3... Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O
{ The main line. Svidler normally plays the Grünfeld, of course, but that just isn't really possible after the crafty 3.h4, as we've already seen and will again shortly in our opening theory chapter. }
5. e4
{ Thematically taking over the centre, since Black is yet to make any sort of challenge there. }
5... d6 6. Be2
{ The best spot for this piece, as well as a move that definitely puts h4-h5 high on the agenda. }
6... c5
{ Black opts for a Benoni and quickly Benko-type play, rather than the more normal King's Indian counter of  6...e5  . That is largely because after  7.d5  White's set-up is simply an attractive one, with the dark-squared bishop able to come to e3 and both a quick h4-h5 and even g2-g4 imminent.  A club player, though, could easily stumble into such an inferior version of a King's Indian as Black, and we'll take a good look at this line in Chapter Four. }
7. d5
{ Naturally, White keeps his centre intact and retains his space advantage. }
7... b5
{ Black offers a pawn for counterplay.  Another important line is  7...e6  8.h5  , as we'll also consider in Chapter Five @@StartBracket@@see 5B @@EndBracket@@. }
8. cxb5
{ With ...b4 something of an issue, White should simply accept the gambit... }
8... a6 9. a4
{ ...but not this second pawn! The text is a well-known method for countering delayed forms of the Benko. White refuses to develop Black's queenside pieces for him, and angles for a queenside clamp with his bishop on b5.  Instead,  9.bxa6  Qa5  10.Bd2  Bxa6  gives Black easy play and  11.h5!?  Nbd7  @@StartBracket@@calm and consistent, although  11...Bxe2  12.Ngxe2  Nxh5  was also possible.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/3nppbp/b2p1np1/q1pP3P/4P3/2N5/PP1BBPP1/R2QK1NR w KQ - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.hxg6  hxg6!  @@StartBracket@@  12...fxg6  13.Nh3!  would quickly eye that rather large hole on e6.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/3nppb1/b2p1np1/q1pP4/4P3/2N5/PP1BBPP1/R2QK1NR w KQ - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Kf1  Rfb8  gave Black promising Benko counterplay in Jobava-Atalik, Burgas 2012.  You might though wish to consider @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/4ppbp/p2p1np1/1PpP4/4P2P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR w KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.b6!?  Qxb6  10.h5  , returning the pawn to keep the queenside situation under control, as in Bartel-Sapeta, Katowice @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@ 2019. }
9... axb5
{ Black begins to free his queenside.  Suat Atalik wondered about the ambitious  9...Qa5?!  10.Bd2!  Qb4  in his notes to his encounter with Jobava, but after  11.Qc2  White would appear to be doing quite well. Not only is h4-h5 still on the agenda, but Black's queen can quickly run into trouble with the unpinning Ra3 one powerful way for White to neutralise all the potential pressure on the queenside.  Atalik's idea was  11...Nbd7?!  12.Nf3  axb5  13.Bxb5  Ng4?!  , but after  14.Nd1!  Qxb5  15.axb5  Rxa1  16.O-O  it's very hard to believe that Black should have anything like enough for the queen. }
10. Bxb5
{ Clearly the point of White's play and he now arranges things to be left with a pawn on b5. }
10... Ba6 11. Bd2 Bxb5 12. axb5
{ Black has managed to open the a-file, but not also the b-file and it will take him some time with ...Ne8-c7 to round up the extra pawn on b5, time which White will use to try and mate the black king or at least crash through in the centre. }
12... Nbd7 13. Nf3
{ It's high time to catch up in development. The h-pawn still has a useful role to play, but for now White must make sensible moves, content to have won a pawn on the queenside. }
13... Rxa1 14. Qxa1 Qb6 15. O-O
{ Very logical play from White who may now consider ideas of a timely Qa6,  in contrast to which  15.Qa6?  Qxa6  16.bxa6  Ra8  would not have been wise. }
15... Rb8
{ Svidler too proceeds thematically and this move improves over  15...Ne8?  16.Bg5!  Nc7!?  @@StartBracket@@C@@EndBracket@@. The pawn didn't have to be sacrificed, but:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@4nrk1/3nppbp/1q1p2p1/1PpP2B1/4P2P/2N2N2/1P3PP1/Q4RK1 b - - 4 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Ndf6?  17.Qa6!  Qxa6  18.bxa6  Nc7  19.Ra1  Ra8  20.a7  would just be very bad news for Black@@EndBracket@@  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@4nrk1/3nppbp/1q1p2p1/1PpP2B1/4P2P/2N2N2/1P3PP1/Q4RK1 b - - 4 16@@EndFEN@@  16...f6  17.Be3  Nc7  18.b4!  sees lines opening to White's advantage, with  18...f5  nothing to fear:  19.bxc5  dxc5  20.d6!  Qxd6  21.Rd1!  Bxc3!  @@StartBracket@@pretty much forced as otherwise the black queen finds herself overloaded.   22.Qb1  Qe6  23.Ng5  Qc4  24.Rxd7  Nxb5  25.exf5  and at the end of the forcing line we find the weakness of Black's king and his sub-optimal coordination the key features of the position.  C@@EndBracket@@ Therefore @@StartFEN@@4nrk1/3nppbp/1q1p2p1/1PpP2B1/4P2P/2N2N2/1P3PP1/Q4RK1 b - - 4 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Nc7!?  17.Bxe7  Ra8  18.Qd1  @@StartBracket@@if in doubt centralise is rarely a bad policy@@EndBracket@@  18...Nxb5  19.Nxb5  Qxb5  20.Bxd6  Bxb2  21.Qc2  , which left White doing pretty well with his powerful centre and safer king position in Maatman-Kokje, Groningen 2019. }
16. Qa6
{ Invading and consistent with the plan begun with 9.a4,  but the unstereotyped  16.Qe1!?  was also worth a thought, hinting at e4-e5 and especially preparing to press on with h4-h5 once the black knight vacates f6. }
16... Ne8
{ The knight comes round to regain the pawn on b5, in return for which White ensures that he will retain control of the open a-file. }
17. Ra1 Kf8
{ A slightly mysterious move, but Svidler simply wants to keep e7.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@1r2n1k1/3nppbp/Qq1p2p1/1PpP4/4P2P/2N2N2/1P1B1PP1/R5K1 b - - 6 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Nc7?  18.Qxb6  Nxb6  @@StartBracket@@  18...Rxb6?  19.Ra7  wins a piece@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@1r4k1/2n1ppbp/1n1p2p1/1PpP4/4P2P/2N2N2/1P1B1PP1/R5K1 w - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Ra7  would have been excellent for White, even after  19...Bxc3!  20.Rxc7!  Bxb2  21.Rxe7  , but...  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@1r2n1k1/3nppbp/Qq1p2p1/1PpP4/4P2P/2N2N2/1P1B1PP1/R5K1 b - - 6 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Bxc3!  18.Bxc3!  @@StartBracket@@  18.bxc3  Nc7  19.Qa7  Rb7  is fine for Black, and if  20.Qxb6  Nxb6  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@1r2n1k1/3npp1p/Qq1p2p1/1PpP4/4P2P/2B2N2/1P3PP1/R5K1 b - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Nc7  19.Qxb6  Nxb6  20.Ra7  Nba8  would have seen Black regaining his pawn and only slightly worse after  21.b6  Rxb6  22.Nd2  when White might hope to make something of a knight on c4 and that fine unopposed dark-squared bishop. }
18. h5
{ Some 15 moves after arriving on h4,  Harry is finally able to press ahead and do keep an eye on his future career!  That said,  18.Bg5!?  might have been a better try, when...  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@1r2nk2/3nppbp/Qq1p2p1/1PpP2B1/4P2P/2N2N2/1P3PP1/R5K1 b - - 8 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Bxc3  19.bxc3  Nc7  is the critical line, but at least here White can retain pieces with  20.Qa3  Nxb5  21.Qc1  , with an unclear middlegame ahead, albeit one where he will have some chances on the dark squares and kingside.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@1r2nk2/3nppbp/Qq1p2p1/1PpP2B1/4P2P/2N2N2/1P3PP1/R5K1 b - - 8 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Nc7?  19.Qxb6  Nxb6  20.Ra7  would again see White causing major problems along the seventh rank. }
18... Nc7 19. Qa4
{ Keeping pieces on retains a bit of pressure, which  19.Qxb6  Nxb6  wouldn't have done. }
19... Ra8
{ Allowing White some chances, in contrast to which the simple  19...Nxb5!  20.Nxb5  @@StartBracket@@  20.Qd1?  Nd4  is not what White wants to be doing@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@1r3k2/3nppbp/1q1p2p1/1NpP3P/Q3P3/5N2/1P1B1PP1/R5K1 b - - 0 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Qxb5  21.Qxb5  Rxb5  would most likely have led to a draw as after  22.Ra8+  Rb8  @@StartBracket@@and not  22...Nb8?  23.Ba5!  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@Rr3k2/3nppbp/3p2p1/2pP3P/4P3/5N2/1P1B1PP1/6K1 w - - 2 23@@EndFEN@@  23.Rxb8+  Nxb8  24.hxg6  hxg6  25.b3  . }
20. Qd1 Rxa1 21. Qxa1 Ne5
{ Svidler is in no rush to regain his pawn, but now White is able to make good use of Harry and remind Black that there will always be tactics on the back rank. }
22. h6
{ Forcing the upcoming exchanges and also denying the black king its obvious escape square. }
22... Nxf3+ 23. gxf3 Bxc3
{ This feels like a concession, even if it does regain the pawn.  Instead,  23...Be5!?  , as proposed by Yermolinsky in his notes to this encounter for Chess.com,  would given Black enough time to go ...f6 and ...Kf7,  and he should be OK after, say,  24.Be3  f6  25.b4  Qb8!  . }
24. Bxc3 Qxb5 25. b4
{ Vachier-Lagrave had no doubt spotted this powerful and neat advance a few moves in advance. Suddenly, Black must be wary of the white queen invading down the long diagonal and the defence isn't an easy one. }
25... Ne8
{ The pressure Black has been under all game finally takes its toll. Svidler was no doubt rather worried by  25...cxb4  26.Bxb4  Ke8  27.Qh8+  Kd7  28.Qxh7!  , but it transpires that Black is somehow able to save the day, despite Harry being about to queen:  28...Nxd5!  29.exd5  Qxd5!  and White isn't able to avoid perpetual check.  However, there was no need for such heroics when @@StartFEN@@5k2/2n1pp1p/3p2pP/1qpP4/1P2P3/2B2P2/5P2/Q5K1 b - - 0 25@@EndFEN@@  25...Ke8!  was available and after  26.Qa7  Kd7  27.bxc5  Qxc5  Black would have had everything under control, with a draw again looking likely. }
26. bxc5 dxc5 27. Bg7+
{ This must have been an enjoyable move to make. The bishop is untouchable and now the white queen is set to invade on the back rank. }
27... Kg8
{ 27...Nxg7?  28.Qxg7+  Ke8  29.Kg2!  @@StartBracket@@avoiding  29.Qxh7?  Qb2!  when Black escapes with a draw after all, as with  30.Qg7  Qc1+  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@4k3/4ppQp/6pP/1qpP4/4P3/5P2/5PK1/8 b - - 2 29@@EndFEN@@  29...Qb1  30.Qg8+  Kd7  31.Qxf7!  Qc1  32.f4  is now a killer with h7 followed by g6 set to fall and Black too slow after  32...c4  33.Qxh7  Qxf4  34.Qxg6  , in view of  34...c3  35.h7  c2  36.h8=Q  c1=Q  37.Qe6+  Kc7  38.Qhc8  . }
28. Qa8 c4
{ White's queen wriggles her way in after this, but  28...Qd7  29.e5  would also have been decisive, and if  29...c4  30.e6!  fxe6  31.dxe6  Qb5  32.f4!  , eliminating any perpetuals and leaving Black unable to find a single good move after  32...Qb1+  @@StartBracket@@or  32...g5  33.f5!  g4  34.Qd8  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@Q3n1k1/4p1Bp/4P1pP/8/2p2P2/8/5P2/1q4K1 w - - 1 33@@EndFEN@@  33.Kg2  Qb5  34.Qd8  . }
29. Qd8 Qa4 30. Kg2
{ Cruel and precise as White avoids any checks and leaves Black almost in zugzwang. }
30... Qb5 31. Bb2
{ After  31.Bb2  Kf8  @@StartBracket@@or  31...Qa4  32.Qxe7  Qb5  33.Ba3  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@3Qnk2/4pp1p/6pP/1q1P4/2p1P3/5P2/1B3PK1/8 w - - 6 32@@EndFEN@@  32.Ba3!  Qb7  Black might appear to have everything defended, but  33.d6!  quickly shatters that illusion and leads to mate. }
