[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "QS | 1A | Grünfeld with 3...d5 | Black plays 4...Qxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4
{ This is likely to come as a nasty shock to opponents at all levels. As early as move three, White intimidates Black with Harry.  The option of h4-h5 makes it hard for Black to obtain a satisfactory version of a Grünfeld, although White won't always rush with that advance, often preferring to keep it in reserve while first competing for the centre with Nc3 and e2-e4. }
3... d5
{ This might well be the choice of a Grünfeldeer at club level, but is also a move that White should relish appearing on the board. }
4. cxd5
{ There is absolutely no reason not to capture, especially when after  4...Nxd5  and a subsequent  5.e4  Black won't find a knight on c3 to exchange off and will be forced to retreat from d5. }
4... Qxd5 { Black prevents e2-e4, but not White developing with tempo: } 5. Nc3
{ Of course. White develops with tempo and will now follow up with e2-e4 unless Black tries a Scandinavian-style pin. }
5... Qa5
{ 5...Qd8  6.e4  dominates the centre unless Black elects to react there:  6...e5!?  7.Bg5!  is a powerful pin and one which pretty much prevents Black from capturing on d4.   7...h6  8.Bxf6  Qxf6  was Gershenov-Christensen, Helsingor 2011, where White should have continued aggressively to gain tempi:  9.Nd5  Qd8  10.dxe5  . Black does have an unopposed dark-squared bishop, but not only is he a clear pawn in arrears, but both Nf6+ and f2-f4 are also imminent, with an excellent game for White. }
6. Bd2
{ Always a good response to a pinning ...Qa5 in the repertoire. Here White simply intends to boss the centre after e2-e4 and has a powerful triple@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ pawn sacrifice in mind: }
6... Qb6
{ 6...c6  is a solid Scandinavian sort of move, but not one which challenges White in any way, shape or form. After  7.e4  White is already doing very well with simply e4-e5 followed by h4-h5 being top of the agenda. }
7. h5
{ A powerful pawn sacrifice and, don't forget, Black can only take one of the three en prise pawns at a time. }
7... gxh5
{ A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pp1p/1q3np1/7P/3P4/2N5/PP1BPPP1/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nxh5?  when his big idea was  8.Rxh5!  gxh5  9.Nd5  Qd6  @@StartBracket@@  9...Qc6?  10.e4  is even worse for Black with Bb5 now a threat@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pp1p/3q4/3N3p/3P4/8/PP1BPPP1/R2QKBN1 w Qkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.e4  . White simply threatens Bf4 and Nxc7+,  a threat that is extremely hard to prevent, as  10...e5?  11.dxe5  Qxe5  loses to  12.Bc3  Qxe4+  13.Ne2  when there are just far too many threats.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pp1p/1q3np1/7P/3P4/2N5/PP1BPPP1/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qxb2?  would have been cleaned up by  8.Rb1  Qa3  9.Nb5  .  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pp1p/1q3np1/7P/3P4/2N5/PP1BPPP1/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qxd4  8.Nf3  Qb6  @@StartBracket@@or  8...Qd8  9.hxg6  fxg6  10.Qb3  when Ne5 is all set to highlight Black's rather vulnerable light squares and kingside.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1pp1p/1q3np1/7P/8/2N2N2/PP1BPPP1/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9.hxg6  fxg6  10.e4  or even  10.Rh4!?  just leaves White with a powerful initiative and excellent play for the pawn. Indeed, he might well quickly overwhelm Black with some combination of Rc1,  e4-e5,  Ng5 and Na4. }
8. e4 { Threatening 9.e5 while offering a second pawn. } 8... Qxd4 9. Nf3
{ With tempo. } 9... Qb6 10. Be3
{ A third pawn is gambited and already White is just doing extremely well. His bishop is all set to take up a powerful role on d4 should Black get greedy and capture on b2, as we saw him doing in Williams-Platel, and in any case, yet again, e4-e5 is set to cause serious headaches for the defence. }
10... Qxb2
{ Easy to criticise, but Black was set to suffer in any case, not least as  10...Qa5  11.e5  Ne4?  is pretty much impossible on account of the neat  12.Qd5!  Qxd5  13.Nxd5  Kd8  14.O-O-O  with a ginormous initiative for White. }
11. Bd4
{ A fine square for the bishop, eyeing not just the black queen @@StartBracket@@Nd5 is a huge threat@@EndBracket@@, but also the rook on h8 after e4-e5-e6. White already enjoyed an extremely strong initiative in Williams-Platel.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    Chapter 1: Grünfeldesque Lines  Variation: 1A | Black plays 4...Qxd5, 7...gxh5  Model Game: Simon Williams – Alexandre Platel }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "QS | 1A | Grünfeld with 3...d5 | Black plays 4...Nxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4
{ This is likely to come as a nasty shock to opponents at all levels. As early as move three, White intimidates Black with Harry.  The option of h4-h5 makes it hard for Black to obtain a satisfactory version of a Grünfeld, although White won't always rush with that advance, often preferring to keep it in reserve while first competing for the centre with Nc3 and e2-e4. }
3... d5
{ This might well be the choice of a Grünfeldeer at club level, but is also a move that White should relish appearing on the board. }
4. cxd5
{ There is absolutely no reason not to capture, especially when after  4...Nxd5  and a subsequent  5.e4  Black won't find a knight on c3 to exchange off and will be forced to retreat from d5. }
4... Nxd5 5. h5
{ White may now break up Black's kingside with hxg6 or make a powerful cramping advance with h5-h6, while e2-e4 is also high on the agenda, taking over the centre. }
5... Bg7
{ Black attempts to hold his kingside together and prepares to meet hxg6 with ...hxg6.   5...h6?!  6.hxg6  fxg6  was seen in Pavalachandran-Wickramasinghe, Colombo 2020, where White went  7.Qd3  , but expansion in the centre would appear even stronger:  7.e4  Nb6  8.Nc3  Bg7  9.e5  . White blunts the bishop on g7 and simply prepares to target the rather vulnerable g6-pawn with Bd3 and also Nge2 and Nf4 if needed. }
6. h6
{ Not for the first time we see White happy to close the h-file to badly mess up Black's development. Now, of course, the bishop must retreat, otherwise White would simply win a piece with 7.e4 and 8.e5. }
6... Bf8 { Forced, unless Black wishes to lose a piece after  7.e4  . } 7. e4
Nf6 8. Nc3
{ White enjoys a powerful centre, a long-term rather useful cramping asset on h6 and Black won't find it at all easy to complete development, as we'll see in Line 1A.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    Chapter 1: Grünfeldesque Lines  Variation: 1A | Black plays 4...Nxd5, 5...Bg7 }
