[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "QS | 2A | Harry Obstruction with 3...h5 | Black plays 7...e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4
{ This is likely to come as a nasty shock to opponents at all levels. As early as move three, White intimidates Black with Harry.  The option of h4-h5 makes it hard for Black to obtain a satisfactory version of a Grünfeld, although White won't always rush with that advance, often preferring to keep it in reserve while first competing for the centre with Nc3 and e2-e4. }
3... h5
{ Black elects to keep the h-file closed ahead of instigating a Grünfeld-type counter in the centre. }
4. Nc3
{ Once again, we find White quite content to prepare e2-e4 in classic fashion. Now a Grünfeldesque response with  4...d5  is quite common when we will analyse  5.Bg5  in Line 1C, but plenty of opponents will prefer King's Indian-like waters. }
4... Bg7
{ 4...c5  A Benoni-like advance and one we'll see much more of, albeit a move earlier, in Chapter Three. White should respond by seizing space, with a very likely transposition to our lines with 4...Bg7 here:   5.d5  Bg7  6.e4  O-O  7.Be2  . Now  7...d6  8.Nf3  transposes to our main line after 4...Bg7,  and alternatives which do not dissuade e4-e5 are unsurprisingly rather risky:  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp1pppb1/5np1/2pP3p/2P1P2P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e6?!  8.e5!  Nh7  9.Bf4  , simply defending d5,  although a good case might also be made for 9.g4!?.  9...exd5  10.Qxd5!  . This strong recapture denied Black in Sychev-Savchenko, Skolkovo 2019, the counterplay he was likely hoping for with  10.cxd5  d6!  11.exd6  Re8  .  However, after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp1p1pbn/6p1/2ppP2p/2P2B1P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R2QK1NR w KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Qxd5!  White clamps down on the d6-square, attacks c5 and may simply continue with Nf3 and O-O or O-O-O. Do observe too that a timely Nb5 or even g2-g4 may very much be an idea as well. }
5. e4
{ Against a King's Indian, not Grünfeld, approach, White simply takes over the centre. }
5... d6 6. Be2
{ Always a useful little move. Here it doesn't support h4-h5, but does keep Black out of g4. }
6... O-O
{ Black is extremely likely to castle, thereby meaning that he can recapture on d8 with his rook in the event of any ...e5; dxe5 dxe5 exchange. }
7. Nf3
{ The knight eyes a fine home on an important square Black has already weakened: g5. }
7... e5 8. d5
{ Once again, White pushes straight past and will install his knight on g5 when it will be hard for Black to classically break with ...f5 without significantly weakening his light squares.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    Chapter 2: Black Obstructs Harry  Variation: 2A | Black plays 7...e5 }
