{ Black is extremely likely to castle, thereby meaning that he can recapture on d8 with his rook in the event of any ...e5; dxe5 dxe5 exchange. }
7. Nf3
{ The knight eyes a fine home on an important square Black has already weakened: g5. }
7... c5
{ Black's most common move, seeking Benoni-like play to exploit the fianchettoed bishop on g7,  rather than a more conventional closed centre King's Indian approach with  7...e5  8.d5  .  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppb1/3p1np1/7p/2PPP2P/2N2N2/PP2BPP1/R1BQK2R b KQ - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6  8.d5  is once again a powerful advance, one which simply increases White's control of the position:   8...Ne5  9.Nxe5  dxe5  10.f3  and with Bg5 on its way @@StartBracket@@possibly followed by Qd2 and O-O-O@@EndBracket@@, Black was already struggling for acceptable counterplay in Mica-Sikorova, Pardubice 2020. }
8. d5
{ Our approved method: push on by and avoid any early central pawn exchanges.  Those who recall the course of Vachier-Lagrave-Svidler or who have already looked forward in the course will be aware that we are now in a main line @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP3P/8/PP2PPP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bg7  4.Nc3  O-O  5.e4  d6  6.Be2  c5  7.d5  @@EndBracket@@ where Black has weakened himself with  7...h5  8.Nf3  .  The advance of the h-pawns is an insertion that slightly favours White as any bishop or knight on g5 can no longer be easily dislodged by ...h6. In contrast, and in part because White hasn't yet gone O-O,  it will be possible to arrange f2-f3 after ...Bg4 or ...Ng4 much more easily than Black can even make a rather ugly and further weakening ...f6 push.  Already White might just expand with Ng5 or simply Bf4 @@StartBracket@@not Be3 when ...Ng4 may supply some counterplay@@EndBracket@@ and Qd2. }
8... e6
{ Reacting in the centre is principled and likely best.   8...Bg4  9.Bf4!?  looks even stronger than the 9.Be3 of Dimitrijevic-A.L'Ami, Doha 2014. White makes it that little bit harder for Black to bring a knight to e5,  while reminding her that e4-e5 is an important pawn break.  After  9...Nbd7  10.O-O  , White's king is safe and the plan now is to meet any ...a6 with a counterplay-denying a2-a4,  as well as to edge forwards with Qd2 and Bh6 or even Ng5 Bxe2; Qxe2,  thereby continuing to leave Black a little low on counterplay. }
9. Bf4
{ White eyes the weakness on d6, aims to provoke ...e5, which would restrict the bishop on g7, will find safety for his king on g1 and still intends to exert some pressure on its counterpart after Ng5, as we'll see in Line 2A.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    Chapter 2: Black Obstructs Harry  Variation: 2A | Black plays 7...c5, 8...e6, 9...e5  Variation: 2A | Black plays 7...c5, 8...e6, 9...exd5  Variation: 2A | Black plays 7...c5, 8...e6, 9...Re8 }
