{ This is likely to come as a nasty shock to opponents at all levels. As early as move three, White intimidates Black with Harry.  The option of h4-h5 makes it hard for Black to obtain a satisfactory version of a Grünfeld, although White won't always rush with that advance, often preferring to keep it in reserve while first competing for the centre with Nc3 and e2-e4. }
3... h5
{ Black elects to keep the h-file closed ahead of instigating a Grünfeld-type counter in the centre. }
4. Nc3
{ Once again, we find White quite content to prepare e2-e4 in classic fashion. Now a Grünfeldesque response with  4...d5  is quite common when we will analyse  5.Bg5  in Line 1C, but plenty of opponents will prefer King's Indian-like waters. }
4... d5
{ Opting for Grünfeld play after all and in a situation where Black won't lose a pawn in the centre or be overrun by h4-h5. }
5. Bg5
{ A slight change of approach, but now  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.e4  runs into a typical Grünfeld exchange on c3,  so White instead creates a definite threat. }
5... Bg7 { Black's most straightforward and typically Grünfeld-like response. }
6. Nf3
{ Development, while ignoring any early pawn snatches – for now. All the while White aims to provoke ...dxc4 when e2-e4 would take over the centre. }
