[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "QS | 3A | Other 3rd Moves | Black plays 3...c5, 7...O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4
{ This is likely to come as a nasty shock to opponents at all levels. As early as move three, White intimidates Black with Harry.  The option of h4-h5 makes it hard for Black to obtain a satisfactory version of a Grünfeld, although White won't always rush with that advance, often preferring to keep it in reserve while first competing for the centre with Nc3 and e2-e4. }
3... c5
{ This Benoni and Benko counter-thrust was Anish Giri's choice when surprised by Veselin Topalov at the Moscow Candidates of 2016, a game which appeared to put the elite off 3.h4 until three years later Alexander Grischuk realised that matters were by no means bad for White. }
4. d5
{ Once again, seizing space and keeping lines closed. Now  4...Bg7  5.Nc3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP3P/8/PP2PPP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bg7  4.Nc3  c5  5.d5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppp1p/5np1/2pP4/2P4P/8/PP2PPP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  usually also leads to a transposition after a subsequent ...Bg7. }
4... b5 { Benko style. } 5. cxb5
{ Accepting the pawn, in part because here after  5.h5!?  Nxh5  6.e4  d6  there isn't an amazingly great continuation for White. }
5... a6 6. e3
{ A restrained but effective advance, refusing to develop Black's queenside for him, while facilitating both Bxb5 and Nc3 followed only then by e3-e4. }
6... Bg7 7. Nc3
{ Once again White prepares e3-e4, with the counterplay-reducing a2-a4 also likely to prove a useful advance. }
7... O-O 8. a4
{ Always a useful advance in such structures, increasing White's stranglehold over b5 and the queenside. }
8... Bb7 9. Nf3
{ With Black not enjoying his usual Benko free queenside play, White is now ready to expand with e3-e4. }
9... e6 10. dxe6
{ Giving up the central bastion, but also forcing Black into a major decision over how to recapture and an exchange which gives him a harder position than  10.e4  exd5  11.exd5  Re8+  12.Be2  axb5  would. }
10... fxe6
{ 10...dxe6  11.Qxd8  Rxd8  12.Bd2  gave White a pleasant edge in Leimgruber-Laghetti, correspondence 2017.  Black is a little low on counterplay, will find any move of the knight from f6 met by h4-h5 and must also watch out that White can't get in a well-timed a4-a5 and/or b5-b6 to make significant inroads on the queenside. }
11. Qd6
{ A powerful invasion, preventing ...d5 and leaving Black a little cramped, as we'll see in Rapport-Svidler.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    Chapter 3: Other 3rd Moves Bar 3...Bg7  Variation: 3A | Black plays 4...b5, 6...Bg7, 7...O-O, 8...Bb7  Model Game: Richard Rapport – Peter Svidler }
