{ This is likely to come as a nasty shock to opponents at all levels. As early as move three, White intimidates Black with Harry.  The option of h4-h5 makes it hard for Black to obtain a satisfactory version of a Grünfeld, although White won't always rush with that advance, often preferring to keep it in reserve while first competing for the centre with Nc3 and e2-e4. }
3... d6
{ Black keeps his options open: he may transpose to King's Indian @@StartBracket@@3...Bg7@@EndBracket@@ lines or try something independent. The latter was thrice Maxime Vachier-Lagrave's choice when confronted by Magnus Carlsen's 3.h4!? during their December 2020 Chess.com Speed Championship match. }
4. Nc3
{ White continues in standard fashion, preparing e2-e4,  and now Black's main move is  4...Bg7  , transposing after all into the realm of chapters 4 and 5. }
4... Nc6
{ Vachier-Lagrave's choice in his second and third games with Carlsen in their speed match, having first tried to develop the knight to d7. }
5. e4 { White refuses to fear the upcoming attack on d4. } 5... e5 6. d5
{ Our usual policy and there's no need to worry about an invasion on d4, as Black won't be able to maintain his knight there. }
6... Nd4 7. Nge2
{ And this is why. Black must now meekly exchange or roll the dice with the positionally committal ...c5, as we'll see in Line 3B.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    Chapter 3: Other 3rd Moves Bar 3...Bg7  Variation: 3B | Black plays 4...Nc6 }
