1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4
{ This is likely to come as a nasty shock to opponents at all levels. As early as move three, White intimidates Black with Harry.  The option of h4-h5 makes it hard for Black to obtain a satisfactory version of a Grünfeld, although White won't always rush with that advance, often preferring to keep it in reserve while first competing for the centre with Nc3 and e2-e4. }
3... Bg7
{ Black's most common response, keeping play within King's Indian waters.  Sometimes the immediate  3...c5  is seen, but after  4.d5  Black usually just goes  4...Bg7  with play transposing after  5.Nc3  . }
4. Nc3
{ Development first to prepare e2-e4 and now Black might decide that it's a better time for  4...d5  , since there will be a knight on c3 to exchange off in the event of  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.e4  . }
4... d5 5. h5
{ Once again, White scotches the notion that Black can obtain a decent version of a Grünfeld. Already  5...--  6.h6  Bf8  7.cxd5  Nxd5  8.e4  is a sizeable threat. }
5... Nxh5
{ Black decides to exchange d5 for h5, which is probably his best choice. } 6.
cxd5
{ No, an exchange sacrifice is not the plan when we can simply pocket an extra central pawn and push e2-e4 next move. }
6... e6
{ Nepomniachtchi's attempt to breathe life into the line as Black.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3P3n/3P4/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5?  7.dxc5  O-O  8.e4  was just an extra pawn and large advantage for White in Budisavljevic-Milosevic, Novi Sad 2020, with Be2 and Be3 set to leave Black suffering somewhat.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3P3n/3P4/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  7.e4  c6  8.dxc6  is a simple retort to Black's bid for counterplay. White can now simply continue development with Nf3 and Bc4 or Be2,  while d4-d5 may well be a handy advance:   8...O-O  9.Nf3  Nxc6  10.d5  Nb8  11.Bg5  . This left White menacing both e4-e5 and Qd2 followed by Bh6,  with a clear advantage in Wichmann-Hahn, Schwaebisch Gmuend 2018. }
7. g4
{ And why not be provoked? Yet again, White has a promising pawn sacrifice in mind. }
7... Nf6
{ The knight must scurry back, but White isn't now going to allow Black to take on d5. }
8. dxe6 Bxe6 9. e4
{ This is it, as seen in a battle between the two leading Grünfeld exponents, Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and Ian Nepomniachtchi, which we'll follow for a while in Line 1B. }
9... Bxg4 10. f3
{ Forcing the bishop back and keeping the proud centre intact. } 10... Be6
{ Of course, @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp2pbp/4bnp1/8/3PP1P1/2N5/PP3P2/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nxg4  10.f3  Nf6  would also lead to this position. }
11. Bg5
{ Not only is e4-e5 a threat, but White enjoys excellent long-term compensation. The bishop will tuck back in on e3 if prodded, the centre is mobile and after Qc2 or Qd2 White will be able to consider going long, with Nge2 and then Nf4 or d4-d5 and Nd4 being other useful ideas.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    Chapter 1: Grünfeldesque Lines  Variation: 1B | Black plays 5...Nxh5, 6...e6 }
