1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4
{ This is likely to come as a nasty shock to opponents at all levels. As early as move three, White intimidates Black with Harry.  The option of h4-h5 makes it hard for Black to obtain a satisfactory version of a Grünfeld, although White won't always rush with that advance, often preferring to keep it in reserve while first competing for the centre with Nc3 and e2-e4. }
3... Bg7
{ Black's most common response, keeping play within King's Indian waters.  Sometimes the immediate  3...c5  is seen, but after  4.d5  Black usually just goes  4...Bg7  with play transposing after  5.Nc3  . }
4. Nc3
{ Development first to prepare e2-e4 and now Black might decide that it's a better time for  4...d5  , since there will be a knight on c3 to exchange off in the event of  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.e4  . }
4... d6 5. e4
{ Now play is extremely likely to transpose after  5...O-O  to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2PP3P/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...O-O  5.e4  d6  . There's just the one important sideline for Black: }
5... Nc6
{ Not a move you're likely to see much of at club level, but an important alternative to  5...O-O  and one which Magnus Carlsen gave his seal of approval to when hit by Vladimir Fedoseev's 3.h4 at the 2021 FIDE World Cup.  Black prepares to strike back against d4 to obtain some counterplay while aiming to lure White forwards in the centre. We should also note that this move has been recommended by Peter Svidler and then in Gawain Jones's excellent Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian course. }
6. d5
{ White allows himself to be provoked.  Note that  6.Be2  no longer cuts the mustard on account of  6...e5  , and if  7.d5?!  Nd4  , one of the main points behind this line for Black. }
6... Ne5 { Black continues to provoke. } 7. Be2
{ Keeping Black out of g4 and so facilitating a later f2-f4 @@StartBracket@@in the short term White is more likely to prefer to challenge Black's best piece with Nf3@@EndBracket@@, as well as h4-h5. }
7... h5 8. Nf3
{ White wastes no time in challenging the strong knight on e5 and may now be able to bring his dark-squared bishop to e3.  Instead,  8.Bf4  O-O  9.Nf3  Nxf3+  10.gxf3  c6  gave Black sufficient counterplay in Fedoseev-Carlsen, FIDE World Cup, Krasnaya Polyana 2021. }
8... Nxf3+ 9. gxf3
{ A dynamic recapture, opening the g-file since the black king is bound for g8. Be3 and Qd2 will follow, and then quite possibly Rg1 when one onwards plan is Rg5 and f3-f4-f5.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    Chapter 4: King's Indian Style  Variation: 4A | Black plays 7...h5 }
