1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4
{ This is likely to come as a nasty shock to opponents at all levels. As early as move three, White intimidates Black with Harry.  The option of h4-h5 makes it hard for Black to obtain a satisfactory version of a Grünfeld, although White won't always rush with that advance, often preferring to keep it in reserve while first competing for the centre with Nc3 and e2-e4. }
3... Bg7
{ Black's most common response, keeping play within King's Indian waters.  Sometimes the immediate  3...c5  is seen, but after  4.d5  Black usually just goes  4...Bg7  with play transposing after  5.Nc3  . }
4. Nc3
{ Development first to prepare e2-e4 and now Black might decide that it's a better time for  4...d5  , since there will be a knight on c3 to exchange off in the event of  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.e4  . }
4... O-O 5. e4
{ Already e4-e5 followed by h4-h5 is an issue, hence Black's next move. } 5...
d6 6. Be2
{ Once again, the best follow-up to e2-e4 as White supports the onward advance of Harry.  In Line 4B we reach this position via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2PP3P/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  5.e4  O-O  6.Be2  . }
6... e5 7. d5
{ This is what you might perceive to be normal King's Indian fare. The problem for Black is that he lacks some of his normal counterplay, with  7...h5  8.Nf3  followed by 9.Ng5 being quite pleasant for White, as we've already noted via the 3...h5 move order. }
7... c6
{ 7...h6?!  8.g4!  . Just as in Line 2B, this is an extremely strong advance, threatening to open lines with g4-g5 and also simply intending to limber up with menace through Be3,  Qd2 and O-O-O. }
8. h5
{ Needless to say, White presses straight ahead with Harry once allowed. } 8...
cxd5 9. cxd5
{ Maintaining the symmetry, as well as control. Now it's by no means impossible to imagine White playing on the queenside with Be3, Nf3-d2 and Rac1, as well as on the kingside. }
9... Nbd7 10. Be3
{ White already enjoys a very pleasant edge, with an AlphaZero style h5-h6 to entomb Black's bishop high on the agenda, as we'll see in Praggnanandhaa-Yip.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    Chapter 4: King's Indian Style @@StartBracket@@5...d6 transposes@@EndBracket@@  Variation: 4B | Black plays 6...e5, 7...c6  Model Game: Rameshbabu Praggnanandhaa – Carissa Yip }
