{ Already e4-e5 followed by h4-h5 is an issue, hence Black's next move. } 5...
d6 6. Be2
{ Once again, the best follow-up to e2-e4 as White supports the onward advance of Harry.  In Line 4B we reach this position via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2PP3P/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  5.e4  O-O  6.Be2  . }
6... c5 { Benoni style and the main line. } 7. d5
{ Retaining the space advantage and renewing the threat of h4-h5. } 7... b5
{ Black sacrifices a pawn and heads for Benko Gambit-like waters. } 8. cxb5
{ The best way to deal with Black's Benko-like play is to take the first pawn, thereby putting a little something in the bank. }
8... a6
{ Invariably played. We dare say  8...Qa5  is also possible, but after  9.Bd2  play is likely to transpose with  9...a6  10.a4  . }
9. a4
{ White does, however, decline the second offer, not wishing to speed up Black's queenside development and counterplay. }
9... axb5
{ 9...Nbd7  10.Nf3  . Simple development, although 10.h5!? must also be an option.  10...Qa5  11.Bd2  is a straightforward alternative to the also promising  11.O-O  axb5  12.Bxb5  of Badelka-Injac, Women's World Blitz Championship, Warsaw 2021.  Continuing the line @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/3nppbp/p2p1np1/qPpP4/P3P2P/2N2N2/1P2BPP1/R1BQK2R w KQ - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bd2  Qb4  12.Qc2  . Once again, White is just doing very well, as we saw in the notes to Black's 9th move in Vachier-Lagrave-Svidler. }
10. Bxb5 { Needless to say, White wants to remain a pawn ahead. } 10... Ba6
{ Consistent and very Benkoesque, although on the odd occasion Black prefers something else when White should just continue to develop:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/4ppbp/3p1np1/1BpP4/P3P2P/2N5/1P3PP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bd7  11.Bd2  is likely to transpose to our main line after  11...Bxb5  12.axb5  . If Black declines to exchange, the white bishop will be happy to tuck back in on c4: @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/3bppbp/3p1np1/1BpP4/P3P2P/2N5/1P1B1PP1/R2QK1NR b KQ - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qb6  12.Bc4!  Qxb2?  13.Rb1  and Black is losing material.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/4ppbp/3p1np1/1BpP4/P3P2P/2N5/1P3PP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Na6  11.Nf3  Nc7  12.Bc4  . White avoids an annoying exchange and maintains control, being all set to castle.  12...Ba6  13.Bxa6  . This straightforward approach seems even better than 13.Nd2.  13...Rxa6  14.O-O  .  Black shouldn't have enough for his pawn and White may now find Rb1 a useful move, overprotecting b2 and also enabling him to consider defensive ideas of b2-b3 or even of fighting back on the queenside, if allowed, with b2-b4.  Meanwhile, Re1 will support the key pawn break, e4-e5,  and if the black knight leaves f6,  of course, h4-h5 may well get in on the show. }
11. Bd2
{ An important move, directed not so much against ...Qa5 ideas as to defend the rook on a1. That means that White can now meet ...Bxb5 with axb5, continuing to deny Black easy counterplay while even allowing White to probe down the a-file, as in Vachier-Lagrave-Svidler.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    Chapter 5: KID Style Main Line @@StartBracket@@5...d6 transposes@@EndBracket@@  Variation: 5A | Black plays 9...axb5, 11...Qc8  Variation: 5A | Black plays 9...axb5, 11...Bxb5, 15...Rb8  Variation: 5A | Black plays 9...axb5, 11...Bxb5, 15...Ne8  Model Game: M. Vachier-Lagrave – Peter Svidler }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "QS | 5B | KID Style with 6...c5 + ...e6 | Black plays ...a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4
{ This is likely to come as a nasty shock to opponents at all levels. As early as move three, White intimidates Black with Harry.  The option of h4-h5 makes it hard for Black to obtain a satisfactory version of a Grünfeld, although White won't always rush with that advance, often preferring to keep it in reserve while first competing for the centre with Nc3 and e2-e4. }
3... Bg7
{ Black's most common response, keeping play within King's Indian waters.  Sometimes the immediate  3...c5  is seen, but after  4.d5  Black usually just goes  4...Bg7  with play transposing after  5.Nc3  . }
4. Nc3
{ Development first to prepare e2-e4 and now Black might decide that it's a better time for  4...d5  , since there will be a knight on c3 to exchange off in the event of  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.e4  . }
4... O-O 5. e4
{ Already e4-e5 followed by h4-h5 is an issue, hence Black's next move. } 5...
d6 6. Be2
{ Once again, the best follow-up to e2-e4 as White supports the onward advance of Harry.  In Line 4B we reach this position via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2PP3P/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  5.e4  O-O  6.Be2  . }
6... c5 { Benoni style and the main line. } 7. d5
{ Retaining the space advantage and renewing the threat of h4-h5. } 7... a6
{ Black's most critical continuation, challenging in the centre without delay. }
8. a4
{ Always a good response to Black's pawn-to-queen's-rook-three nudge, ruling out any ...b5 break for some considerable time. }
8... e6 9. h5 exd5 10. exd5
{ Just as in our main @@StartBracket@@7...e6@@EndBracket@@ line, retaining the symmetry of the pawn structure also retains control and an edge for White, which is an even better choice than the  10.hxg6!?  of Williams-Palliser.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    Chapter 5: KID Style Main Line @@StartBracket@@5...d6 transposes@@EndBracket@@  Variation: 5B | Black plays 9...a6 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "QS | 5B | KID Style with 6...c5 + 7...e6 | Black plays 15...f6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4
{ This is likely to come as a nasty shock to opponents at all levels. As early as move three, White intimidates Black with Harry.  The option of h4-h5 makes it hard for Black to obtain a satisfactory version of a Grünfeld, although White won't always rush with that advance, often preferring to keep it in reserve while first competing for the centre with Nc3 and e2-e4. }
3... Bg7
{ Black's most common response, keeping play within King's Indian waters.  Sometimes the immediate  3...c5  is seen, but after  4.d5  Black usually just goes  4...Bg7  with play transposing after  5.Nc3  . }
4. Nc3
{ Development first to prepare e2-e4 and now Black might decide that it's a better time for  4...d5  , since there will be a knight on c3 to exchange off in the event of  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.e4  . }
4... O-O 5. e4
{ Already e4-e5 followed by h4-h5 is an issue, hence Black's next move. } 5...
d6 6. Be2
{ Once again, the best follow-up to e2-e4 as White supports the onward advance of Harry.  In Line 4B we reach this position via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2PP3P/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  5.e4  O-O  6.Be2  . }
6... c5 { Benoni style and the main line. } 7. d5
{ Retaining the space advantage and renewing the threat of h4-h5. } 7... e6
{ Black's most critical continuation, once again deploying Modern Benoni motifs. }
8. h5
{ There's no reason whatsoever not to press ahead so and now White may even be able to restrict Black's counterplay with a cramping h5-h6 and Bg5. }
8... exd5
{ The typical Modern Benoni follow-up and invariably played. Otherwise, White should simply continue with h6 Bh8; Bg5,  cramping Black, and we'll see  8...a6  9.a4  by transposition in Williams-Palliser. }
9. exd5
{ Once again, the best recapture, denying Black the counterplay  9.cxd5  Re8  and  9.hxg6  fxg6  would grant him, not least with the king's rook. }
9... Re8
{ Black's main move by quite some margin, pinning and so threatening ...Nxh5. It has also been the choice of David Vigorito and Gawain Jones in their respective King's Indian repertoires.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3pbp/3p1np1/2pP3P/2P5/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qb6?!  10.h6  Bh8  11.g4!  when Black is already running out of good moves, with f2-f3 set to keep him out of g4 and do note that problem bishop on c8. Meanwhile White might go Qc2 and Bg5 or Bf4,  or untangle his kingside pieces with Nh3-g5 followed by O-O or Kf1.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3pbp/3p1np1/2pP3P/2P5/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qe7?!  10.h6!  White has often preferred 10.Kf1 and 10.hxg6 here, but why not cramp à la AlphaZero and then pin?  10...Bh8  11.Bg5  Pinning and, of course, ...Qe5 can just be met by Nf3.   11...Re8  12.Nf3  . White simply intends O-O followed by Re1 with a pleasant space advantage right across the board, although we should admit that  12.Rh4!?  Qf8  13.Kf1  is also quite tempting and strong. }
10. h6
{ This advance does mean that White won't be playing for mate in a hurry, but is still a good use of Harry. Black will now always have long-term concerns over his king. White's short-term goal: to pin the knight on f6, then maintain control. }
10... Bh8
{ 10...Bf8?!  11.Bg5  Be7  12.Qd2  only leaves Black a little cramped and low on counterplay while White can go Nf3,  O-O @@StartBracket@@or even O-O-O@@EndBracket@@, and Rae1 to maintain control.  12...Nbd7!?  13.O-O-O!  @@StartBracket@@here  13...Ng4?  would lose a piece, whereas @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/pp1nbp1p/3p1npP/2pP2B1/2P5/2N5/PP1QBPP1/R3K1NR w KQ - 5 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Nf3  Ng4  isn't so clear@@EndBracket@@ and now:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/pp1nbp1p/3p1npP/2pP2B1/2P5/2N5/PP1QBPP1/2KR2NR b - - 6 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nxd5?  14.Bxe7  Nxe7  15.Qxd6  . Black might have deployed a tactic, but finds himself badly suffering, being pinned down the d-file and rather vulnerable on the dark squares.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/pp1nbp1p/3p1npP/2pP2B1/2P5/2N5/PP1QBPP1/2KR2NR b - - 6 13@@EndFEN@@  13...a6  14.Re1!?  . White simply prepares to land his bishop with some force on b5 and in the event of a break and exchanges there, will now continue with Nf3 and Qf4 if unpestered, while continuing to provoke a certain tactic:  14...Nxd5  15.Bxe7  Nxe7  16.Qxd6  .  Now Black surely doesn't have anything better than forcing the queen backwards:  16...Nf5  17.Qf4!  Nd4  18.Nf3  wasting no time challenging Black's control of d4. White is simply doing pretty well, with his queen still in touch with the kingside, where Black's king is a definite target, and it can easily slip back to d2 or g3 if needed. }
11. Bg5
{ Now White has a few useful ideas, and not just the routine Nf3 and O-O. His king may prefer to step off the e-file to f1, possibly in conjunction with activating the rook via h4, thereby preparing to swing across to f4 while keeping Black out of e4.  Even Kf1 or f2-f3 then g2-g4 can prove a useful advance, denying Black's light-squared bishop too much scope. }
11... Qb6
{ Gawain Jones's recommendation, unpinning.   11...b5  12.cxb5  a6  13.a4!  is, of course, our standard method of dealing with any Benko-type play and was seen in Urazayev-Schmakel, Internet  (blitz)  2021:   13...Qa5  14.Bd2  unpinning and preparing to recapture with the knight on b5,  after which Bc3,  as well as Nf3 and O-O may well follow. }
12. b3
{ A brave advance, but a better choice than allowing Black to liberate his position with  12.Qd2  Ne4  . White always has Bd2 and/or Rc1 if needed and is itching to sacrifice the exchange. }
12... Ne4
{ Black wastes no time forcing matters on the dark squares and this choice of Gelfand and Jones is clearly a critical one. }
13. Nxe4 Rxe4 14. Kf1
{ Unpinning the bishop which may now head to d3. As we'll see in Line 5B, White is also all set to go Rc1 next and, of course, Black shouldn't get greedy. }
14... Bxa1 15. Qxa1 f6 16. Qxf6 Qc7 17. Bd3
{ This is crushing.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    Chapter 5: KID Style Main Line @@StartBracket@@5...d6 transposes@@EndBracket@@  Variation: 5B | Black plays 9...Re8, 12...Ne4, 14...Nd7  Variation: 5B | Black plays 9...Re8, 12...Ne4, 14...Re8 #1  Variation: 5B | Black plays 9...Re8, 12...Ne4, 14...Re8 #2 }
