[Round "?"]
[White "1. Grünfeldesque Lines (...d5)"]
[Black "Chapter One: Grünfeldesque Lines"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Chapter One: Grünfeldesque Lines@@HeaderEnd@@ } 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 g6 3. h4
{ We'll begin by seeing how a Grünfeld player might react to the early advance of Harry. White should be quite happy to see the black d-pawn quickly appearing on d5,  as we'll further appreciate in the following lines:  1A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP3P/8/PP2PPP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5   1B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP3P/8/PP2PPP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bg7  4.Nc3  d5   1C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP3P/8/PP2PPP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...h6  4.Nc3  d5  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP3P/8/PP2PPP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...h5  4.Nc3  d5 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Grünfeldesque Lines (...d5)"]
[Black "1A | Grünfeld with 3...d5 | Black plays 4...Qxd5, 7...Nxh5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 d5
{ This might well be the choice of a Grünfeldeer at club level, but is also a move that White should relish appearing on the board. }
4. cxd5
{ There is absolutely no reason not to capture, especially when after  4...Nxd5  and a subsequent  5.e4  Black won't find a knight on c3 to exchange off and will be forced to retreat from d5. }
4... Qxd5 { Black prevents e2-e4, but not White developing with tempo: } 5. Nc3
{ Of course. White develops with tempo and will now follow up with e2-e4 unless Black tries a Scandinavian-style pin. }
5... Qa5
{ 5...Qd8  6.e4  dominates the centre unless Black elects to react there:  6...e5!?  7.Bg5!  is a powerful pin and one that pretty much prevents Black from capturing on d4.   7...h6  8.Bxf6  Qxf6  was Gershenov-Christensen, Helsingor 2011, where White should have continued aggressively to gain tempi:  9.Nd5  Qd8  10.dxe5  . Black does have an unopposed dark-squared bishop, but not only is he a clear pawn in arrears, but both Nf6+ and f2-f4 are also imminent, with an excellent game for White. }
6. Bd2
{ White simply breaks the pin, thereby knocking any possible ideas of ...Ne4 on their head and should also be delighted if Black now elects to fork the pawns on d4 and b2. }
6... Qb6
{ 6...c6  is a solid Scandinavian sort of move, but not one which challenges White in any way, shape or form. After  7.e4  White is already doing very well with simply e4-e5 followed by h4-h5 being top of the agenda. }
7. h5
{ A powerful pawn sacrifice and, don't forget, Black can only take one of the three en prise pawns at a time. }
7... Nxh5
{ Along with the material-losing raid on b2, this is the capture White should most want to see, as now there's a very strong exchange sacrifice: }
8. Rxh5 gxh5 9. Nd5 { The point. Black's queen is about to be overloaded. }
9... Qd6 10. e4
{ Already there's just no good way to deal with the threat of Bf4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Grünfeldesque Lines (...d5)"]
[Black "1A | Grünfeld with 3...d5 | Black plays 4...Qxd5, 7...Qxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 d5
{ This might well be the choice of a Grünfeldeer at club level, but is also a move that White should relish appearing on the board. }
4. cxd5
{ There is absolutely no reason not to capture, especially when after  4...Nxd5  and a subsequent  5.e4  Black won't find a knight on c3 to exchange off and will be forced to retreat from d5. }
4... Qxd5 { Black prevents e2-e4, but not White developing with tempo: } 5. Nc3
{ Of course. White develops with tempo and will now follow up with e2-e4 unless Black tries a Scandinavian-style pin. }
5... Qa5
{ 5...Qd8  6.e4  dominates the centre unless Black elects to react there:  6...e5!?  7.Bg5!  is a powerful pin and one which pretty much prevents Black from capturing on d4.   7...h6  8.Bxf6  Qxf6  was Gershenov-Christensen, Helsingor 2011, where White should have continued aggressively to gain tempi:  9.Nd5  Qd8  10.dxe5  . Black does have an unopposed dark-squared bishop, but not only is he a clear pawn in arrears, but both Nf6+ and f2-f4 are also imminent, with an excellent game for White. }
6. Bd2
{ White simply breaks the pin, thereby knocking any possible ideas of ...Ne4 on their head and should also be delighted if Black now elects to fork the pawns on d4 and b2. }
6... Qb6
{ 6...c6  is a solid Scandinavian sort of move, but not one which challenges White in any way, shape or form. After  7.e4  White is already doing very well with simply e4-e5 followed by h4-h5 being top of the agenda. }
7. h5
{ A powerful pawn sacrifice and, don't forget, Black can only take one of the three en prise pawns at a time. }
7... Qxd4 8. Nf3
{ White continues to develop with tempo and enjoys excellent compensation for what is only one pawn. He will mess up Black's kingside with hxg6 and also swiftly continue development with e2-e4 and then e4-e5 or perhaps Bc4 and Qb3 depending on where the black queen goes. }
