{ Development first to prepare e2-e4 and now Black might decide that it's a better time for  4...d5  , since there will be a knight on c3 to exchange off in the event of  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.e4  . }
4... d5 5. h5
{ Despite Ian Nepomniachtchi no less having twice played this way as Black, it's not an especially impressive form of Grünfeld – and this is why! White makes immediate and good use of Harry and already threatens to pretty much take over the whole board with  5...--  6.h6  Bf8  7.cxd5  Nxd5  8.e4  . }
5... O-O 6. hxg6
{ Simple chess as White rips open the h-file at the earliest opportunity. }
6... hxg6 7. cxd5
{ White distracts the defender away from h6.  Of course, we wanted to recommend the immediate  7.Bh6  , but after  7...Bxh6!  8.Rxh6  Kg7  9.Rh1  c6  followed by 10...Rh8 Black is rather solidly placed. }
7... Nxd5 8. Bh6
{ 8.e4  Nxc3  9.bxc3  c5  10.d5!?  might well also tempt a natural attacker.  Back to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppb1/6p1/3n4/3P4/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bh6  . Only now does the bishop land here and we have to wonder when did you last get to develop your dark-squared bishop to h6 in one move? A swift attack with Qd2 is already set to quickly obliterate Black, hence his need to exchange pieces: }
8... Bxh6 9. Rxh6
{ White already has a sizeable threat: Qd2 followed by retreating the rook. Hence, Black must be careful. }
9... Kg7 10. Qd2
{ Keeping the rook in situ and now Black is likely to exchange knights so that his queen can recapture after ...Rh8 @@StartBracket@@a situation with ...Kxh8; Qh6+ Kg8; Nf3-g5 is unlikely to be great for him@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Rh8 { Forcing the rooks off after all. } 12. Rxh8 Qxh8 13.
e4
{ This natural advance could well be even stronger than the also logical  13.Qf4  of W.Chan-P.Chan, Thailand 2005. White's extra space should give him an edge and he will even be able to castle long.  Note that Qf4 followed by Bc4 is top of the attacking agenda to tie Black down, while any ...c5 break is likely to be well met by Qf4 or even Qg5. Do not lose sight of the fact that the black king is still not overly happy! }
