{ Only now does White expand and we much prefer such aggression to the  7.Bd2  of Budrewicz-Kantans, Szklarska Poreba 2021, a game in which a Latvian GM was Black. }
7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 c5
{ Just like in the main lines of the Grünfeld. Compared to  8...Bg7  @@StartBracket@@when  9.f4!  is extremely likely to transpose after  9...c5  @@EndBracket@@, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp2/7p/6pP/3PP3/2P5/P4PP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...c5  allows White some extra options, not least  9.Bb5+!?  , but he can also be bold and strike out on the kingside: }
9. f4
{ Now  9...Bg7  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp2/7p/6pP/3PP3/2P5/P4PP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bg7  9.f4  c5  and instead exchanging on d4 doesn't help Black due to a possibly surprising recapture: }
9... cxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. cxd4
{ White is still threatening to take on g5 and is also the boss of the centre. }
11... Nc6
{ A tempting move, but also a major error, underestimating White's immediate advance: }
12. d5 Nd4 13. Bb2
{ A strong pin. Now Black must allow White an extremely pleasant choice after  13...e5  between  14.Nf3  and the exchange-sacrificing  14.fxe5  , since contesting the long diagonal only loses material: }
13... Bg7 14. O-O-O { A piece must fall. } *

