[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Grünfeldesque Lines (...d5)"]
[Black "1C | Grünfeld with 3...h5 + 4...d5 | Black plays 5...dxc4, 6...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 h5
{ Black elects to keep the h-file closed ahead of instigating a Grünfeld-type counter in the centre. }
4. Nc3
{ White prepares to expand with e2-e4 and now Black doesn't have to head for King's Indian waters, as we'll consider in Chapter Two, but might strike out with arguably the best version of a Grünfeld that we'll see in this chapter. }
4... d5 5. Bg5
{ Not the most common move with the h-pawns at home, if far from a terrible move there, and one which certainly carries a positional threat in this case.  Don't forget, though, that depending on any anti-Grünfeld experience you may have, you might prefer  5.cxd5  Nxd5  and then either  6.e4  or  6.Bd2  . }
5... dxc4 6. e4
{ White already takes over the centre, leaving Black struggling. } 6... Nc6
{ After  6...c5  7.d5  Bg7  8.Bxc4  a6  9.a4  White enjoys a definite space advantage, Black lacks counterplay and once again badly wishes he could go ...h6,  as we noted briefly while examining Mikhalevski-Iliaguev. }
7. d5 { Taking up the challenge. } 7... Ne5
{ This ambitious try was seen in Boyer-De Ruiter, Guimaraes 2021, where  8.Qd4?!  might have been met by  8...Nfg4!  . }
8. Nf3
{ White simply develops and will now even recapture on f3 with the g-pawn, opening the g-file. Indeed, it's not hard to imagine the black king coming under pressure on g8 with Bxc4 and Rg1 played. White is also happy to sacrifice a pawn: }
8... Bg4 9. Qd4 Nxf3+ 10. gxf3 Bxf3 11. Rh3
{ The bishop only has one square, but even that won't prevent White from obtaining a powerful initiative: }
11... Bg4 12. e5
{ Suddenly exf6 followed by fxe7 is quite a threat and so the knight pretty much has to move. }
12... Nd7 13. e6
{ The main point of White's play and once again Black has only one move: }
13... Nf6 14. exf7+ Kxf7 15. Re3
{ White has sacrificed two pawns, but you have to like his compensation. He'll manage to castle after f3 and O-O-O, in contrast to which the king on f7 is pretty unhappy and will be even more so after Bxc4. }
*

