[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 h5
{ Black elects to keep the h-file closed ahead of instigating a Grünfeld-type counter in the centre. }
4. Nc3
{ White prepares to expand with e2-e4 and now Black doesn't have to head for King's Indian waters, as we'll consider in Chapter Two, but might strike out with arguably the best version of a Grünfeld that we'll see in this chapter. }
4... d5 5. Bg5
{ Not the most common move with the h-pawns at home, if far from a terrible move there, and one which certainly carries a positional threat in this case.  Don't forget, though, that depending on any anti-Grünfeld experience you may have, you might prefer  5.cxd5  Nxd5  and then either  6.e4  or  6.Bd2  . }
5... Ne4 6. cxd5
{ A simple response, as White forces the pace and ensures himself of a central pawn preponderance. }
6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 Qxd5 8. Nf3
{ This once again looks pretty pleasant for White. The bishop on g5 is especially well placed, ...f6 would, of course, be very weakening and meanwhile White will expand with Nd2 and e2-e4 or just e2-e3 and c3-c4. }
