[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Grünfeldesque Lines (...d5)"]
[Black "1C | Grünfeld with 3...h5 + 4...d5 | Black plays 5...c5, 9...Qxb2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 h5
{ Black elects to keep the h-file closed ahead of instigating a Grünfeld-type counter in the centre. }
4. Nc3
{ White prepares to expand with e2-e4 and now Black doesn't have to head for King's Indian waters, as we'll consider in Chapter Two, but might strike out with arguably the best version of a Grünfeld that we'll see in this chapter. }
4... d5 5. Bg5
{ Not the most common move with the h-pawns at home, if far from a terrible move there, and one which certainly carries a positional threat in this case.  Don't forget, though, that depending on any anti-Grünfeld experience you may have, you might prefer  5.cxd5  Nxd5  and then either  6.e4  or  6.Bd2  . }
5... c5
{ This is ever a valid move in the Grünfeld, if rare here, with or without the h-pawns having advanced. }
6. Bxf6 { White should probably be consistent and force matters so. } 6... exf6
7. cxd5
{ To avoid coming out a centre pawn in arrears for not very much, Black really needs to activate his queen. }
7... Qb6 8. e3
{ White calmly keeps everything under control and is happy to once again dangle b2 before Black. }
8... cxd4
{ 8...Qxb2  9.Bb5+  gives White a handy lead in development, with Nge2 and Rb1 high on the agenda. }
9. Qxd4
{ Denying Black any fun and we shouldn't lose sight of the fact that White is a pawn up. }
9... Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qa3 11. Bb5+
{ This is likely even stronger than picking off f6. White simply wants to complete development with Nge2 and O-O while retaining a strong initiative. }
*

