{ White prepares to expand with e2-e4 and now Black doesn't have to head for King's Indian waters, as we'll consider in Chapter Two, but might strike out with arguably the best version of a Grünfeld that we'll see in this chapter. }
4... d5 5. Bg5
{ Not the most common move with the h-pawns at home, if far from a terrible move there, and one which certainly carries a positional threat in this case.  Don't forget, though, that depending on any anti-Grünfeld experience you may have, you might prefer  5.cxd5  Nxd5  and then either  6.e4  or  6.Bd2  . }
5... Bg7 { Black's most straightforward and typically Grünfeld-like response. }
6. Nf3
{ Unable to shatter Black's structure on f6, White simply develops, taking control of e5 in the process. Now Black would quite like to go ...h6, but that is, of course, illegal. }
6... dxc4 7. e4
{ Just as a move earlier, White can be happy to have seen Black swipe on c4. His centre is dominant, he can push past after ...c5 @@StartBracket@@or even consider taking it@@EndBracket@@, and will simply go Bxc4 unless Black counters very dynamically: }
7... c5 8. d5 b5 9. e5
{ A fearless advance. The bishop can always drop back to f4 to help support the powerful centre and White must have good compensation with it. }
9... b4
{ This saw Black trying to pick off d5 in Gomez-Paveto, Caba 2018, a pawn White should be happy to sacrifice: }
10. Na4 Nxd5 11. Bxc4
{ Now Black is pretty much forced to retreat to b6, but that will mean his king remaining in the centre. }
11... Nb6 12. Qxd8+ Kxd8 13. Bb3
{ This appears even stronger than taking on b6 and then f7. The bishop will recapture on a4, after which the black king and c5 will be White's goals, not least with O-O-O+ and Rd5. }
