[Round "?"]
[White "1. Grünfeldesque Lines (...d5)"]
[Black "1C | Grünfeld with 3...h5 + 4...d5 | Black plays 5...Bg7, 6...c6, 8...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 h5
{ Black elects to keep the h-file closed ahead of instigating a Grünfeld-type counter in the centre. }
4. Nc3
{ White prepares to expand with e2-e4 and now Black doesn't have to head for King's Indian waters, as we'll consider in Chapter Two, but might strike out with arguably the best version of a Grünfeld that we'll see in this chapter. }
4... d5 5. Bg5
{ Not the most common move with the h-pawns at home, if far from a terrible move there, and one which certainly carries a positional threat in this case.  Don't forget, though, that depending on any anti-Grünfeld experience you may have, you might prefer  5.cxd5  Nxd5  and then either  6.e4  or  6.Bd2  . }
5... Bg7 { Black's most straightforward and typically Grünfeld-like response. }
6. Nf3
{ Unable to shatter Black's structure on f6, White simply develops, taking control of e5 in the process. Now Black would quite like to go ...h6, but that is, of course, illegal. }
6... c6 { A solid stance, and one which is unlikely to trouble White. } 7. e3
{ White continues his unhurried development, content to maintain control and see Black a little low on counterplay. }
7... O-O 8. Qb3
{ Not for the first time, a decent post for the queen. White keeps an eye on b7 and aims to entice Black into  8...dxc4  9.Bxc4  b5  when after  10.Be2  and a2-a4 Black may well find that he has merely overextended on the queenside. }
8... e6 9. Be2 Nbd7 10. O-O
{ This straightforward development left White with a very pleasant edge in Santiago-Goncalves, Ponta Grossa 2017. Note especially Black's lack of counterplay. White might follow up with Ne5 or simply centralise with Rfd1, Rac1, Qc2 and then break with e3-e4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Grünfeldesque Lines (...d5)"]
[Black "1B | Simon Williams – Sarah Hegarty | Sunningdale 2011"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Simon Williams – Sarah Hegarty@@HeaderEnd@@e2e4 Sunningdale Masters 2011 }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 5. h5
{ The semi-refutation of Black's Grünfeld-like last move and now White should be even happier if Black voluntarily elects to break up her own kingside. }
5... gxh5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Rxh5
{ Already the rook is more than pulling its weight and the early advance of Harry looks extremely justified. }
7... Nb6
{ Alternatively, if  7...Nf6  8.Rg5!  Bh6  9.Rg3  Bxc1  10.Rxc1  with the much safer king position for White, or  7...Nxc3  8.bxc3  when  8...c5?!  can simply be met by  9.Rxc5  . }
8. Nf3
{ Simple and strong development, as e2-e4 can wait. White is now ready to launch a lightning attack if Black castles, can meet ...Nc6 with d4-d5, and in any event, it's not so easy to undermine d4. }
8... Bg4
{ Attempting to do so, but now White can fork the two black bishops and, yes, as early as move 9! }
9. Rg5 Bxf3 10. Rxg7 Bh5 11. Rg5
{ Naturally the rook has no desire to be imprisoned by  11...Bg6  , although even then White would be doing well thanks to his central and dark-square control. }
11... Bg6 12. e4
{ It's high time to expand and now Be3, Qd2 @@StartBracket@@or Qb3@@EndBracket@@ and O-O-O may well just follow. }
12... f6 13. Rg3 Nc6
{ Easy to criticise, but finding a better approach in such a horrendous position for Black is no easy task. }
14. d5 Ne5 15. f4
{ With tempo as the term 'massacre' already begins to spring to mind. } 15...
Ned7 16. a4
{ Simon is determined not to let Black settle, now making good use of a second rook's pawn in the game. }
16... a6
{ 16...a5  was the only way to avoid a retreat to the back rank, but then  17.Qd4  followed by f4-f5 and Bf4 would simply leave Black getting badly squashed. }
17. a5 Nc8 18. Be2
{ There's no need to touch the queenside pieces just yet when there are targets aplenty on the kingside. }
18... Nd6 19. Bh5 Nf8
{ Horribly passive, but how else could Black have tried to unravel? } 20. e5
{ Boom! Simon decides that it's time to break through, although he might also have tormented Black with  20.Be3  and Bd4 first, or even  20.f5  Bxh5  21.Qxh5+  Kd7  22.Bf4  Qe8  23.Qh3  and only then e4-e5. }
20... Nf5 21. Rh3
{ The rook returns to the h-file, pinning the h7-pawn in the process. } 21...
Qd7
{ 21...Rg8!?  was possible when White might still exchange, or even switch the approach:  22.Bf3  Qd7  23.e6!  Qd6  24.Qa4+!  and Black is just in all sorts of trouble with Ne4 and g2-g4 set to follow. }
22. e6 { Wedging a certain fish bone deep into the black king's throat. } 22...
Qd6 23. Bxg6+ Nxg6 24. Qh5
{ Black had unsurprisingly seen enough. There's just no way to deal with the twin threats of Qxf5 and Qxg6+. }
