[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Black Obstructs Harry (...h6 or ...h5 without ...d5)"]
[Black "Chapter Two: Black Obstructs Harry"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Chapter Two: Black Obstructs Harry@@HeaderEnd@@ } 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 g6 3. h4
{ We now come to those lines, which we can easily imagine will be fairly common at club level, where Black is already rather afraid of Harry and so takes immediate steps to curtail his further advance.  2A@@EndBracket@@  3...h5   2B@@EndBracket@@  3...h6   In both cases, White should simply continue with  4.Nc3  and 5.e4 if allowed. In Lines 2A and 2B we'll examine Black's attempts to continue in King's Indian style. Instead,  4...d5  would take play back into the realm of Line 1C. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Black Obstructs Harry (...h6 or ...h5 without ...d5)"]
[Black "2A | Harry Obstruction with 3...h5 | Black plays 7...e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 h5 4. Nc3
{ Once again, we find White quite content to prepare e2-e4 in classic fashion. Now a Grünfeldesque response with  4...d5  is quite common when we analysed  5.Bg5  back in Line 1C, but plenty of opponents will prefer King's Indian-like waters. }
4... Bg7
{ 4...c5  A Benoni-like advance and one we'll see much more of, albeit a move earlier, in Chapter Three. White should respond by seizing space, with a very likely transposition to our lines with 4...Bg7 here:   5.d5  Bg7  6.e4  O-O  7.Be2  . Now  7...d6  8.Nf3  transposes to our main line after 4...Bg7,  and alternatives which do not dissuade e4-e5 are unsurprisingly rather risky:  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp1pppb1/5np1/2pP3p/2P1P2P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e6?!  8.e5!  Nh7  9.Bf4  , simply defending d5,  although a good case might also be made for 9.g4!?.  9...exd5  10.Qxd5!  . This strong recapture denied Black in Sychev-Savchenko, Skolkovo 2019, the counterplay he was likely hoping for with  10.cxd5  d6!  11.exd6  Re8  .  However, after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp1p1pbn/6p1/2ppP2p/2P2B1P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R2QK1NR w KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Qxd5!  White clamps down on the d6-square, attacks c5 and may simply continue with Nf3 and O-O or O-O-O. Do observe too that a timely Nb5 or even g2-g4 may very much be an idea as well. }
5. e4 { Naturally, White expands. } 5... d6 6. Be2
{ This classical development, avoiding any potential trouble on g4,  appears the simplest path here, as well as a fairly promising one. However, as we mentioned in the notes to Mikhalevski-Iliaguev, both  6.Bg5  and  6.f3  also very much come into the equation. }
6... O-O
{ Black is extremely likely to castle, thereby meaning that he can recapture on d8 with his rook in the event of any ...e5; dxe5 dxe5 exchange. }
7. Nf3
{ Continuing to follow the Classical main line of the King's Indian, but, worry not, White won't be castling short next move. }
7... e5 8. d5
{ White keeps the centre closed and just appears to have an improved version of a Petrosian System, in part because his knight is destined to take up a strong role on g5.  We should also point out that Bg5 and Qd2 can hardly be a bad policy, with Black unable to break the resulting pin with ...h6. }
8... a5
{ 8...Ng4?!  does nothing to deter White's plan:  9.Ng5!  f5!?  10.exf5!  , beginning to open lines towards the black king and preparing to expand immediately with 11.f3 and 12.g4 if Black recaptures with a piece.   10...gxf5  11.f3  Nf6  12.Qc2  Qe7  13.Be3  with O-O-O next up followed by Bd3 @@StartBracket@@a preparatory a2-a3 might first be required to prevent any ...Na6-b4@@EndBracket@@, White enjoyed control and decent attacking chances in E.Atalik-Schleining, Stary Smokovec 2018, with a timely Ne6 to weaken Black's light-squared control very much an idea. }
9. Ng5
{ A glorious leap and already a position we rather like for White. He will simply complete development with Be3 and Qd2, after which even O-O and the c4-c5 break may give White a good version of a King's Indian, although we'd be more looking to attack with O-O-O, f2-f3 and g2-g4, all the while as Black struggles to arrange ...f5 without Ne6 being too awkward. }
