5. e4 { Naturally, White expands. } 5... d6 6. Be2
{ This classical development, avoiding any potential trouble on g4,  appears the simplest path here, as well as a fairly promising one. However, as we mentioned in the notes to Mikhalevski-Iliaguev, both  6.Bg5  and  6.f3  also very much come into the equation. }
6... O-O
{ Black is extremely likely to castle, thereby meaning that he can recapture on d8 with his rook in the event of any ...e5; dxe5 dxe5 exchange. }
7. Nf3
{ Continuing to follow the Classical main line of the King's Indian, but, worry not, White won't be castling short next move. }
7... Bg4 8. Be3
{ Black's bishop development makes some sense with White no longer able to go h3, but the downside is that the dark-squared bishop can safely settle on e3.  White is now set to retain control and complete development with Qc2, O-O and Rad1, although ideas of Qd2 and O-O-O are by no means ridiculous either, and neither is a timely Ng5 leap. }
8... Nc6 9. d5
{ This is already something of an issue for Black who should probably retreat to b8 when White might simply castle then consider ideas of Qd2, Rad1 and a timely Nd4.  Black can also bring the knight to e5 without having to see his pawns doubled, but White should welcome such a policy: }
9... Bxf3 10. gxf3 Ne5 11. f4
{ This set in motion a powerful pawn roller in Matlakov-Starozhilov, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2020. If the knight leaps forward, White will just go Bd2 and f2-f3, and in any event Qc2, O-O-O, Rhg1 and f4-f5 is high on the agenda. }
