[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Black Obstructs Harry (...h6 or ...h5 without ...d5)"]
[Black "2A | Harry Obstruction with 3...h5 | Black plays 7...c5, 8...b5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 h5 4. Nc3
{ Once again, we find White quite content to prepare e2-e4 in classic fashion. Now a Grünfeldesque response with  4...d5  is quite common when we analysed  5.Bg5  back in Line 1C, but plenty of opponents will prefer King's Indian-like waters. }
4... Bg7
{ 4...c5  A Benoni-like advance and one we'll see much more of, albeit a move earlier, in Chapter Three. White should respond by seizing space, with a very likely transposition to our lines with 4...Bg7 here:   5.d5  Bg7  6.e4  O-O  7.Be2  . Now  7...d6  8.Nf3  transposes to our main line after 4...Bg7,  and alternatives which do not dissuade e4-e5 are unsurprisingly rather risky:  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp1pppb1/5np1/2pP3p/2P1P2P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...e6?!  8.e5!  Nh7  9.Bf4  , simply defending d5,  although a good case might also be made for 9.g4!?.  9...exd5  10.Qxd5!  . This strong recapture denied Black in Sychev-Savchenko, Skolkovo 2019, the counterplay he was likely hoping for with  10.cxd5  d6!  11.exd6  Re8  .  However, after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp1p1pbn/6p1/2ppP2p/2P2B1P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R2QK1NR w KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Qxd5!  White clamps down on the d6-square, attacks c5 and may simply continue with Nf3 and O-O or O-O-O. Do observe too that a timely Nb5 or even g2-g4 may very much be an idea as well. }
5. e4 { Naturally, White expands. } 5... d6 6. Be2
{ This classical development, avoiding any potential trouble on g4,  appears the simplest path here, as well as a fairly promising one. However, as we mentioned in the notes to Mikhalevski-Iliaguev, both  6.Bg5  and  6.f3  also very much come into the equation. }
6... O-O
{ Black is extremely likely to castle, thereby meaning that he can recapture on d8 with his rook in the event of any ...e5; dxe5 dxe5 exchange. }
7. Nf3
{ Continuing to follow the Classical main line of the King's Indian, but, worry not, White won't be castling short next move. }
7... c5
{ Black's most common move, seeking Benoni-like play to exploit the fianchettoed bishop on g7,  rather than a more conventional closed centre King's Indian approach with  7...e5  8.d5  .  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppb1/3p1np1/7p/2PPP2P/2N2N2/PP2BPP1/R1BQK2R b KQ - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6  8.d5  is once again a powerful advance, one which simply increases White's control of the position:   8...Ne5  9.Nxe5  dxe5  10.f3  and with Bg5 on its way @@StartBracket@@possibly followed by Qd2 and O-O-O@@EndBracket@@, Black was already struggling for acceptable counterplay in Mica-Sikorova, Pardubice 2020. }
8. d5
{ Those who recall the course of Vachier-Lagrave-Svidler or who have already looked forward in the course will be aware that we are now in a main line @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP3P/8/PP2PPP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bg7  4.Nc3  O-O  5.e4  d6  6.Be2  c5  7.d5  @@EndBracket@@ where Black has weakened himself with  7...h5  8.Nf3  .  The advance of the h-pawns is an insertion that slightly favours White as any bishop or knight on g5 can no longer be easily dislodged by ...h6. In contrast, and in part because White hasn't yet gone O-O,  it will be possible to arrange f2-f3 after ...Bg4 or ...Ng4 much more easily than Black can even make a rather ugly and further weakening ...f6 push.  Already White might just expand with Ng5 or simply Bf4 @@StartBracket@@not Be3 when ...Ng4 may supply some counterplay@@EndBracket@@ and Qd2. }
8... b5 9. cxb5
{ As so often, the best way to counter a Benko-type approach is to take the first pawn, if not then the second: }
9... a6 10. a4
{ This Vachier-Lagrave-like advance is stronger than taking on a6, as White did in Deuer-Tasev, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2021. The plan is again to keep Black's counterplay on the queenside under control. }
10... axb5 11. Bxb5 Ba6 12. Bd2
{ White makes it problematic for Black to deploy his queen to a5, simply wants to recapture on b5 with the a-pawn and then make use of the resulting open a-file, while the white king will find more than sufficient sanctuary on the kingside. }
