{ Those who recall the course of Vachier-Lagrave-Svidler or who have already looked forward in the course will be aware that we are now in a main line @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP3P/8/PP2PPP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bg7  4.Nc3  O-O  5.e4  d6  6.Be2  c5  7.d5  @@EndBracket@@ where Black has weakened himself with  7...h5  8.Nf3  .  The advance of the h-pawns is an insertion that slightly favours White as any bishop or knight on g5 can no longer be easily dislodged by ...h6. In contrast, and in part because White hasn't yet gone O-O,  it will be possible to arrange f2-f3 after ...Bg4 or ...Ng4 much more easily than Black can even make a rather ugly and further weakening ...f6 push.  Already White might just expand with Ng5 or simply Bf4 @@StartBracket@@not Be3 when ...Ng4 may supply some counterplay@@EndBracket@@ and Qd2. }
