[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Black Obstructs Harry (...h6 or ...h5 without ...d5)"]
[Black "2B | Harry Obstruction with 3...h6 | Black plays 5...O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 h6
{ A somewhat less impressive method of trying to keep lines closed, in part because Harry can still advance a square. }
4. Nc3
{ White readies the e2-e4 advance and in the very limited practice that there has been with this position, Black has always gone in for a Grünfeld and  4...d5  when we saw a good case for  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.h5  in Line 1C. }
4... Bg7 5. e4
{ Naturally White takes the space on offer while threatening e4-e5. } 5... O-O
6. h5
{ Black can usually castle before going ...d6 in the King's Indian, but not here! White's immediate use of Harry simply looks very promising and even stronger than first inserting  6.e5  .  Black's main problem is that after  6.h5  Nxh5?  7.Be2  @@StartBracket@@or  7.g4  @@EndBracket@@ he is going to lose h6,  and that's just for starters. }
6... g5 7. Bxg5
{ Boom! Talk about a put-that-in-your-pipe-and-smoke-it situation! Already White is just doing extremely well, and all thanks to the early and full inclusion of Harry: }
7... hxg5 8. h6
{ Now Black simply must return the piece on h6 and be left with a kingside containing rather large gashes on h5 and down the h-file, since retaining the bishop should lead to a swift demise: }
8... Bh8 9. h7+ Kg7 10. e5
{ White regains his piece for a start and only then will finally be able to land the queen on h5 – with quite some effect. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Black Obstructs Harry (...h6 or ...h5 without ...d5)"]
[Black "2B | Harry Obstruction with 3...h6 | Black plays 5...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 h6
{ A somewhat less impressive method of trying to keep lines closed, in part because Harry can still advance a square. }
4. Nc3
{ White readies the e2-e4 advance and in the very limited practice that there has been with this position, Black has always gone in for a Grünfeld and  4...d5  when we saw a good case for  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.h5  in Line 1C. }
4... Bg7 5. e4
{ Naturally White takes the space on offer while threatening e4-e5. } 5... d6
6. Be2
{ Just as in our main line, this appears the most sensible move, as White tees up both h4-h5 and f2-f4. It's also, of course, very possible to go Be3 and Qd2, not least if Black delays castling. }
6... O-O 7. g4
{ Yes, 6.Be2 also teed up a third pawn advance. Suddenly, White threatens to crash through with g4-g5 and this is much stronger than  7.h5  g5  8.f4  gxf4  9.Bxf4  Nc6!  , which is just very unclear after  10.Qd2  Nxd4!  11.Bxh6! }
7... Nfd7 { How else to get out of the way of the onrushing g-pawn? } 8. Be3
{ Simple chess as White prepares to tickle the weakness on h6 with Qd2. } 8...
e5 9. d5
{ White is already clearly better. After Qd2 Kh7; O-O-O he is in full control of the position and may even be able to consider sacrificial avenues on the kingside, not least with Nf3 then h5 g5; Bxg5 or Nxg5. }
9... f5
{ Black's only conceivable way to try and break out, and desperately obtain some counterplay. }
10. exf5 { Naturally, White is quite happy to open lines. } 10... gxf5 11. gxf5
{ Wherever Black moves his knight from d7, it's not hard to appreciate which king is the happier. White will simply go Qd2 and O-O-O, after which one pretty useful plan is Nf3, h4-h5 and Nh4, beginning to exploit the rather vulnerable black kingside, as will the more direct Rdg1. }
