1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4
{ Just like against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.f3  when both  3...Nc6!?  and  3...e5!?  have been tried, an overly creative opponent might perhaps try the double-advance of the e-pawn, but it just doesn't convince when White hasn't weakened the g3-square: }
3... e5 4. dxe5 Ne4 5. Qd5
{ Forcing the pace. White will now speedily develop with Bg5 and Nc3 should the knight drop back to c5.   5...f5  would just be quite weakening and neither should White fear a check: }
5... Bb4+ 6. Nd2
{ An even more forcing choice than  6.Bd2  with the knight on e4 hanging. }
6... Nxd2 7. Bxd2 Qe7 8. O-O-O
{ Talk about a good version of a Fajarowicz for White! He already exerts pressure down the d-file, the cramping e-pawn is extra @@StartBracket@@although it might be sacrificed to further White's initiative@@EndBracket@@, Black's dark squares and kingside are a little weak and h4-h5 is very much still on the way. }
