[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4
{ A better use of the e-pawn is just to prod it one square, but again, such an approach is unconvincing. It may work against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.f3  , but  3.h4  is a somewhat less weakening move than that one. }
3... e6 4. Nc3
{ Continuing the natural development path, as will both a subsequent e2-e4 and Bg5. }
4... Bb4 5. h5
{ It's not every day that you can play such a move in a Nimzo-Indian, but this is, of course, a most unusual version of that defence. }
5... Nxh5 6. e4
{ Already we rather like White's compensation. His centre is a very powerful one, Black's kingside is full of holes and already  6...--  7.g4  Nf6  8.Bg5  can pretty much count as a threat, and if  8...Be7  9.e5  , driving Black further backwards. }
