1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4
{ The best of the unusual third moves which Black might feel inspired to try by his knowledge of lines against 3.f3 is to develop the queen's knight: }
3... Nc6 4. Nc3
{ White keeps d4-d5 in reserve and simply asks Black: what next?  Now play is likely to go  4...d6  when we'll see  5.e4  in Line 3B or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppppp1p/2n2np1/8/2PP3P/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg7  5.e4  , taking play into the realm of Chapter Four. The only other option is for Black to break in the centre, but that is not at all advisable: }
4... e5 5. d5 { As per usual, White meets the break by pushing past. } 5... Ne7
6. Bg5
{ Forcing the pace is at least as good as simply claiming a good version of a King's Indian for White with  6.e4  Bg7  7.Be2  , as Black's knight is misplaced on e7 with White by no means in a rush to castle short – if ever. }
6... Bg7 7. d6
{ Breaking up Black's central formation and now  7...Nf5  8.e4!  Nxd6?  @@StartBracket@@even  8...Nd4  9.Nge2  is very good for White@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1pbp/3n1np1/4p1B1/2P1P2P/2N5/PP3PP1/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.c5  would be an unusual way to win a piece. }
7... cxd6 8. Qxd6
{ White's queen radiates power in all directions and already Black is forced into a rather miserable move: }
8... Qb6 9. Qxb6
{ Black was hoping for  9.Qxe5?  Qxf2+!  @@StartBracket@@intending ...Ng4@@EndBracket@@, but this is much simpler and far stronger. }
9... axb6 10. e4
{ White further clamps down on the position, leaving Black's position a mess and rather riddled with weaknesses. }
