[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Other 3rd Moves Bar 3...Bg7"]
[Black "3A | 3...c5 | Black plays 4...Bg7, 5...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 c5
{ This Benoni and Benko counter-thrust was Anish Giri's choice when surprised by Veselin Topalov at the Moscow Candidates of 2016, a game which appeared to put the elite off 3.h4 until three years later Alexander Grischuk realised that matters were by no means bad for White. }
4. d5
{ White has also been known to take, but we'll stick to the tried and tested formula of pushing on, with Nc3 and e2-e4 now set to follow. }
4... Bg7 5. Nc3
{ The usual, classical choice and now  5...O-O  6.e4  @@StartBracket@@6.h5!? is also quite tempting here@@EndBracket@@  6...d6  7.Be2  would be the main line, as we'll explore in Chapter Five. }
5... e6 6. h5
{ A strong gambit and one which Black should really accept lest he is overrun by h5-h6 then d5-d6 and/or e2-e4. }
6... Nxh5 7. g4 Nf6 8. d6
{ It's hard not to like White's compensation. He is ready to press ahead with e2-e4 and f2-f4, or even g4-g5 followed by Bg2 and Bf3, and the defence does not look an especially appetising one, as we saw in Alekseenko-Ragger. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Other 3rd Moves Bar 3...Bg7"]
[Black "3A | 3...c5 | Black plays 4...Bg7, 5...d6, 8...O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 c5
{ This Benoni and Benko counter-thrust was Anish Giri's choice when surprised by Veselin Topalov at the Moscow Candidates of 2016, a game which appeared to put the elite off 3.h4 until three years later Alexander Grischuk realised that matters were by no means bad for White. }
4. d5
{ White has also been known to take, but we'll stick to the tried and tested formula of pushing on, with Nc3 and e2-e4 now set to follow. }
4... Bg7 5. Nc3
{ The usual, classical choice and now  5...O-O  6.e4  @@StartBracket@@6.h5!? is also quite tempting here@@EndBracket@@  6...d6  7.Be2  would be the main line, as we'll explore in Chapter Five. }
5... d6 6. e4
{ Straightforward development from White and now play usually transposes to the main line and realm of Chapter Five with  6...O-O  7.Be2  . Black can, though, also react in the centre without delay: }
6... e6
{ 6...a6  7.a4  is denying Black any hope of ...b5 ahead of continuing central and kingside play.  7...e6  8.Be2  exd5  9.exd5  just as in Line 2A, White elects not to unbalance the pawn structure and so maintains control:  9...h5  10.Nf3  O-O  11.Bf4  .  This simple development reminds Black that d6 is a weakness and appears stronger than the immediate 11.Ng5 of Williams-Ostenstad, European Club Cup, Rhodes 2013. As you may have spotted, the position is the same as one in Line 2A, but with the a-pawns having advanced.  White intends to castle then go Ng5 or even Qc2,  a sneaky idea aiming to lure ...Bf5,  after which Bd3 Bxd3; Qxd3 is not so positionally misguided as it weakens Black's kingside, which an advance of the f-pawn to f5 could exploit. }
7. Be2
{ Preparing h4-h5,  although the more creative may wish to explore  7.h5!?  Nxh5  8.g4  Nf6  9.g5  Nh5  10.Be2  , with definite compensation. }
7... exd5 8. exd5
{ Yet again, the right recapture and now Black is unlikely to want to face  8...O-O  9.h5  . As such, he might again play in the style of Line 2A with the line-closing  8...h5  9.Nf3  or aim to disrupt down the e-file: }
8... O-O 9. h5
{ Consistent and now the spectre of a possible h5-h6 looms over Black, as well as the straightforward plan of opening the h-file. }
9... Re8 10. Kf1
{ A neat sidestep. White retains the option of h5-h6 and Bg5 and may also complete development with Bf3,  before or after Nf3-g5.   10.hxg6  hxg6  11.Bg5  is also logical, but after  11...Qb6!  Black had sufficient counterplay in Rapport-Grandelius, Malmo 2013. }
10... Nbd7 11. h6 Bh8 12. Bg5 Ne5 13. g3
{ Black's set-up might look active, but he is actually a little low on counterplay and suffering from a slightly cramped kingside. White might increase the pressure with Rh4-f4, although in Leimgruber-Conterno, correspondence 2017, he preferred to gradually creep forwards with a2-a4 and Ra3. }
