{ Straightforward development from White and now play usually transposes to the main line and realm of Chapter Five with  6...O-O  7.Be2  . Black can, though, also react in the centre without delay: }
6... e6
{ 6...a6  7.a4  is denying Black any hope of ...b5 ahead of continuing central and kingside play.  7...e6  8.Be2  exd5  9.exd5  just as in Line 2A, White elects not to unbalance the pawn structure and so maintains control:  9...h5  10.Nf3  O-O  11.Bf4  .  This simple development reminds Black that d6 is a weakness and appears stronger than the immediate 11.Ng5 of Williams-Ostenstad, European Club Cup, Rhodes 2013. As you may have spotted, the position is the same as one in Line 2A, but with the a-pawns having advanced.  White intends to castle then go Ng5 or even Qc2,  a sneaky idea aiming to lure ...Bf5,  after which Bd3 Bxd3; Qxd3 is not so positionally misguided as it weakens Black's kingside, which an advance of the f-pawn to f5 could exploit. }
7. Be2
{ Preparing h4-h5,  although the more creative may wish to explore  7.h5!?  Nxh5  8.g4  Nf6  9.g5  Nh5  10.Be2  , with definite compensation. }
7... exd5 8. exd5
{ Yet again, the right recapture and now Black is unlikely to want to face  8...O-O  9.h5  . As such, he might again play in the style of Line 2A with the line-closing  8...h5  9.Nf3  or aim to disrupt down the e-file: }
8... Nbd7 9. Nf3
{ Simple chess, introducing the idea of O-O and Bf4,  as played in a very high-level encounter, Ding Liren-Vachier-Lagrave, Yekaterinburg Candidates 2021 @@StartBracket@@  9.h5!?  is very much an option too@@EndBracket@@, where White soon obtained a grip on the position: }
9... Ng4 10. h5 { And why not? } 10... Qe7 11. Bg5
{ Forcing something of a concession out of Black. } 11... Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 f6 13.
Bd2
{ Matters weren't completely clear at this stage, but we quite like White's position with the unopposed dark-squared bishop and safer king.  And after  13...g5  14.O-O  Nge5?!  15.Nd4!!  cxd4  16.cxd4  O-O  @@StartBracket@@  16...Nf7  17.Re1  O-O  18.Bd3  Qd8  19.a4  is simply positionally disgusting for Black, extra piece or no extra piece@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp1nq2p/3p1p2/3Pn1pP/2PP4/8/P2BBPP1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17.dxe5  fxe5  18.Be3  Ding already enjoyed a large advantage. }
