[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Other 3rd Moves Bar 3...Bg7"]
[Black "3A | 3...c5 | Black plays 4...e6, 6...Bg7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 c5
{ This Benoni and Benko counter-thrust was Anish Giri's choice when surprised by Veselin Topalov at the Moscow Candidates of 2016, a game which appeared to put the elite off 3.h4 until three years later Alexander Grischuk realised that matters were by no means bad for White. }
4. d5
{ White has also been known to take, but we'll stick to the tried and tested formula of pushing on, with Nc3 and e2-e4 now set to follow. }
4... e6 5. Nc3
{ If you really don't like a Modern Benoni structure then  5.dxe6  is possible, but we really have to advise our favourite knight development  5.Nc3  , preparing e2-e4,  while also hoping for  5...Bg7  6.h5!  after all. }
5... exd5 6. cxd5 Bg7 7. h5
{ This pawn sacrifice appears even stronger than the immediate  7.d6  – there's a good reason why Black should have blocked with 6...d6. }
7... Nxh5 8. d6
{ White's position already looks rather appetising. There are ideas of Nd5, as well as expansion with e2-e4 or even g4 Nf6; g5 and castling is no panacea for Black: }
8... O-O 9. g4 Nf6 10. g5
{ White insists on obtaining full control of d5 and even has ideas of a rapid Qd3-h3. }
10... Nh5 11. Bg2
{ Already Black's position is bordering on critical, with both Bf3 and Nd5 on their way. }
