{ If you really don't like a Modern Benoni structure then  5.dxe6  is possible, but we really have to advise our favourite knight development  5.Nc3  , preparing e2-e4,  while also hoping for  5...Bg7  6.h5!  after all. }
5... exd5 6. cxd5 d6 7. e4
{ White has acquiesced to an unbalanced central structure and while it's not every day that you see @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  e6  4.Nc3  exd5  5.cxd5  d6  6.e4  g6  7.h4!?  , the cheeky advance is not such a bad one.  We also shouldn't lose sight of the fact that few King's Indian players also play the pure Modern Benoni and, indeed, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppp1p/5np1/2pP4/2P4P/8/PP2PPP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  has been a fairly rare choice here. }
7... Bg7 8. h5
{ A bold pawn sacrifice, making full use of Harry. In the limited practice with this position White has more usually preferred  8.Be2  , which is also a decent move, intending 9.h5 or if  8...h5  9.Bg5  . }
8... a6 9. h6
{ Not for the first time we see this strong advance badly interfering with Black's development. }
9... Bf8 10. a4
{ Simple chess, restraining ...b5,  but  10.e5!?  dxe5  11.Bg5  is a tempting alternative. }
10... Be7 11. Be2
{ White intends to expand with f2-f4 and g2-g4 and must have a promising version of a Four Pawns Attack, not least with Black cramped and low on counterplay. }
