[White "3. Other 3rd Moves Bar 3...Bg7"]
[Black "3A | 3...c5 | Black plays 4...b5, 6...axb5, 7...Ba6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 c5
{ This Benoni and Benko counter-thrust was Anish Giri's choice when surprised by Veselin Topalov at the Moscow Candidates of 2016, a game which appeared to put the elite off 3.h4 until three years later Alexander Grischuk realised that matters were by no means bad for White. }
4. d5
{ White has also been known to take, but we'll stick to the tried and tested formula of pushing on, with Nc3 and e2-e4 now set to follow. }
4... b5 { Giri's choice, as Black takes play into Benko waters. } 5. cxb5
{ Accepting the pawn, in part because here after  5.h5!?  Nxh5  6.e4  d6  there isn't an amazingly great continuation for White. }
5... a6 6. e3
{ A restrained, but important move, preparing to recapture on b5 with the bishop.  Instead,  6.bxa6  Bg7  7.Nc3  O-O  8.e4  d6  seems to be OK for Black and, indeed,  9.Nf3  Qa5  10.Bd2  Bxa6  gave Black a decent version of a Benko in the aforementioned Topalov-Giri encounter. }
6... axb5 7. Bxb5
{ Naturally, White recaptures and should now be pleased to see forcing play with Nc3 on its way. }
7... Ba6 8. Bxa6
{ White should exchange here, as  8.a4??  would most certainly not be wise. Now Nc3 and e2-e4 is the plan and there's always Nge2 if Black goes ...Qa5+ and ...Qxa6. }
8... Nxa6 9. Nc3 d6 10. e4
{ This does consume a tempo, but Black isn't yet up to anything and White is now ready to go Nf3, O-O, Bf4 and e4-e5, crashing through in the centre to exploit the black queen's knight being on a6, not d7. }
10... Bg7 11. Nf3 O-O 12. O-O
{ This calm move is sensible, whereas  12.h5?!  Nxh5  didn't achieve much in Bashylina-Ronka, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2021. It's important not to rush with Harry in such positions, h4-h5 will be all the stronger once Black regroups his knight from f6 to d7 or e8 in typical Benko fashion.  However, if the knight stays on f6,  White should look to arrange e4-e5. Two other important ideas to be aware of are Nf3-d2-c4,  which may especially prove useful in the event of ...Qa5 or ...Qb6,  and a2-a4 followed by Ra3,  keeping Black at bay on the queenside and even hinting at an eventual swing over to the e-file or into a kingside attack. }
