4. d5
{ White has also been known to take, but we'll stick to the tried and tested formula of pushing on, with Nc3 and e2-e4 now set to follow. }
4... b5 { Giri's choice, as Black takes play into Benko waters. } 5. cxb5
{ Accepting the pawn, in part because here after  5.h5!?  Nxh5  6.e4  d6  there isn't an amazingly great continuation for White. }
5... a6 6. e3
{ A restrained, but important move, preparing to recapture on b5 with the bishop.  Instead,  6.bxa6  Bg7  7.Nc3  O-O  8.e4  d6  seems to be OK for Black and, indeed,  9.Nf3  Qa5  10.Bd2  Bxa6  gave Black a decent version of a Benko in the aforementioned Topalov-Giri encounter. }
6... axb5 7. Bxb5
{ Naturally, White recaptures and should now be pleased to see forcing play with Nc3 on its way. }
7... Qa5+ 8. Nc3
{ Now  8...Ba6  can be met by  9.Bxa6  Qxa6  10.Nge2  when e3-e4 and a2-a4 are both likely to prove useful advances. }
8... Ne4 9. Ne2
{ Preparing to sacrifice a pawn and stronger than the bishop-losing  9.Bd2  of Hasseine-Kirk, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2021. }
9... Bg7 10. a4
{ Now it's Black who will have to part with an important bishop if he wants to regain his pawn: }
10... Nxc3 11. Nxc3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qxc3+ 13. Bd2 Qe5 14. Qc1
{ White eyes c5 and also threatens Bc3. } 14... Qxd5 15. O-O
{ This is superb compensation: White is leading in development, able to rip open further lines if needed with e3-e4 and h4-h5, and all set to dominate the a1-h8 diagonal. }
