{ White increases his grip on b5 and prepares to meet ...Qa5 with Bd2.  If this seems too sedate for you, then by all means explore  8.h5!?  Nxh5  9.g4  Nf6  10.g5  , fighting hard for the initiative and intending to launch a strong attack after  10...Nh5?!  11.Rxh5!  gxh5  12.Qxh5  . }
8... e6 9. Nf3
{ In the limited practice thus far, White has been tempted into 9.d6!? here, but there's no reason not to continue development and now  9...Bb7  would transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/3pppbp/p4np1/1PpP4/P6P/2N1P3/1P3PP1/R1BQKBNR b KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bb7  9.Nf3  e6  . }
9... exd5 10. Nxd5 Bb7 11. Nxf6+
{ A slightly unexpected exchange, but by no means a bad alternative to the attempt to maintain a grip on d5 with  11.Bc4  . }
11... Qxf6 12. Ra3
{ The point of White's play. While White might well still meet ...axb5 with Bxb5, he can now consider axb5 too and the rook is fairly well placed on the third rank, with the options of swinging across to d3 or just b3.  Next up will be Be2, after which White castle or prefer a more ambitious yet also tempting policy with h4-h5 and Kf1. }
