{ This Benoni and Benko counter-thrust was Anish Giri's choice when surprised by Veselin Topalov at the Moscow Candidates of 2016, a game which appeared to put the elite off 3.h4 until three years later Alexander Grischuk realised that matters were by no means bad for White. }
4. d5
{ White has also been known to take, but we'll stick to the tried and tested formula of pushing on, with Nc3 and e2-e4 now set to follow. }
4... b5 { Giri's choice, as Black takes play into Benko waters. } 5. cxb5
{ Accepting the pawn, in part because here after  5.h5!?  Nxh5  6.e4  d6  there isn't an amazingly great continuation for White. }
5... a6 6. e3
{ A restrained, but important move, preparing to recapture on b5 with the bishop.  Instead,  6.bxa6  Bg7  7.Nc3  O-O  8.e4  d6  seems to be OK for Black and, indeed,  9.Nf3  Qa5  10.Bd2  Bxa6  gave Black a decent version of a Benko in the aforementioned Topalov-Giri encounter. }
6... Bg7 { Black continues kingside development à la Giri. } 7. Nc3
{ Once again White prepares e3-e4, with the counterplay-reducing a2-a4 also likely to prove a useful advance. }
7... d6
{ 7...axb5  8.Bxb5  Qa5  9.a4!  This keeps the bishop in place, will be followed up by Bd2 or Nge2 and, just as after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/3ppp1p/p4np1/1PpP4/7P/4P3/PP3PP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...axb5  7.Bxb5  Qa5+  8.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@see this line @@EndBracket@@ White should be delighted if Black gives up the dark-squared bishop to regain his pawn on c3. }
8. Nf3
{ Once again, we see straightforward development from White, although you can also begin with  8.a4  if you prefer. }
8... O-O 9. a4 { Reinforcing White's grip on the key b5 point. } 9... Nbd7 10.
e4 { Logical expansion, although here too  10.Ra3!?  cannot be a bad move. }
10... axb5 11. Bxb5 Ba6 12. Bg5
{ Once again, we find White facilitating an axb5 recapture having protected the rook on a1. }
12... Bxb5 13. axb5 h6 14. Bd2
{ This modest retreat keeps an eye on the a5-square and left White slightly for choice in Caruana-Corrales Jimenez, World Blitz Championship, Warsaw 2021. It's worth seeing a few more moves of this instructive encounter:   14...Ng4  15.O-O  Qc7  16.Qe2  connecting the rooks and now White is ready to strike with Harry.  16...Qb7  17.h5  g5  is easy to criticise, but Nh4 was a definite threat.  18.Rxa8  Rxa8  19.Nxg5  and there went a second pawn, Caruana going on to convert in a further 30 moves. }
