[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 d6
{ Black keeps his options open: he may transpose to King's Indian @@StartBracket@@3...Bg7@@EndBracket@@ lines or try something independent. The latter was thrice Maxime Vachier-Lagrave's choice when confronted by Magnus Carlsen's 3.h4!? during their December 2020 Chess.com Speed Championship match. }
4. Nc3
{ White continues in standard fashion, preparing e2-e4,  and now Black's main move is  4...Bg7  , transposing after all into the realm of our next two chapters. }
4... Nbd7 5. e4 { White expands as per the usual plan. } 5... e5 6. d5
{ Another consistent response, pushing past the central challenge to retain a space advantage. }
6... Nc5 7. Qc2
{ White simply defends the en prise pawn. He will next go Be2, which both supports h4-h5 and helps to facilitate Be3. Black may also be worried about being pushed back on the queenside by b2-b4, hence his upcoming attempt to stabilise matters on the queenside. }
7... a5 8. Be2 Be7
{ A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pp2p1p/3p1np1/p1nPp3/2P1P2P/2N5/PPQ1BPP1/R1B1K1NR b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...h6?!  9.Be3  and White already enjoys a pleasant edge, in part because Black has weakened his kingside, although we'll see Simon preferring  9.h5  and going on to win a positional masterpiece in Williams-Poobalasingam.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pp2p1p/3p1np1/p1nPp3/2P1P2P/2N5/PPQ1BPP1/R1B1K1NR b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...h5  9.Nf3  . With ...h6 no longer possible, White heads straight for the g5 post.  9...Bg4  10.Ng5!  is improving over the  10.Be3  of Fedoseev-Giri, World Blitz Championship, Moscow 2019, after which  10...Bxf3  11.Bxf3  Bh6  allowed Black to make some positionally desirable exchanges.  However, after @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1pp2p2/3p1np1/p1nPp2p/2P1P1bP/2N2N2/PPQ1BPP1/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ng5!  Bxe2  11.Qxe2  White's well-placed knight prevents any exchange of dark-squared bishops, meaning that White can continue with Be3 and f2-f3 if needed. He may castle short then expand on the queenside in traditional slow but effective fashion with Rab1,  b2-b3,  a2-a3 and b3-b4,  or prefer a more aggressive set-up with O-O-O. }
9. Be3
{ Once again, this natural move appears best. White hints at a timely Bxc5,  but is more likely to retain this important bishop and go O-O-O and/or h4-h5. Note too that the king's knight will be fairly happy on h3,  after which it may leap forwards to g5 or drop back into f2.  Instead, Carlsen couldn't resist  9.h5  against Vachier-Lagrave, but then matters wouldn't have been so clear after  9...Nxh5!  10.Bxh5  gxh5  , and if  11.Rxh5  Bg4  . }
