[Round "?"]
[White "3. Other 3rd Moves Bar 3...Bg7"]
[Black "3B | 3...d6 | Black plays 4...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 d6
{ Black keeps his options open: he may transpose to King's Indian @@StartBracket@@3...Bg7@@EndBracket@@ lines or try something independent. The latter was thrice Maxime Vachier-Lagrave's choice when confronted by Magnus Carlsen's 3.h4!? during their December 2020 Chess.com Speed Championship match. }
4. Nc3
{ White continues in standard fashion, preparing e2-e4,  and now Black's main move is  4...Bg7  , transposing after all into the realm of our next two chapters. }
4... Nc6
{ Vachier-Lagrave's choice in his second and third games with Carlsen in that speed match, having first tried to develop the knight to d7. }
5. e4
{ The standard expansion as White dares Black to react in the centre rather than take play into the realm of 3...Bg7 and Chapter Four with  5...Bg7  . }
5... e5 6. d5
{ Our usual policy and there's no need to worry about an invasion on d4, as Black won't be able to maintain his knight there. }
6... Nd4 7. Nge2
{ The point. Now  7...Nxe2  8.Bxe2  would just be pleasant for White, with h4-h5 imminent and Black a little low on counterplay. }
7... c5 8. dxc6
{ A rather essential en passant capture to weaken Black's hold on d4. Now after  8...Nxc6  9.f3  White can complete development and retain control with Be3 and Qd2,  all the while as Black nurses long-term weaknesses down the d-file, so here Vachier-Lagrave preferred to sacrifice. }
8... bxc6 9. Nxd4
{ The proof of the pudding must lie in the eating. The queen will be slightly exposed on d4, but White still has his dark-squared bishop and is about to go a pawn ahead. }
9... exd4 10. Qxd4 Bg7 11. Bg5
{ A powerful pin and one which forces Black to weaken his kingside in order to create any discoveries against the queen on d4. }
11... h6 12. Be3
{ Calmly dropping back as  12...Nh5  13.Qd2  would hardly be an inconvenience. }
12... O-O 13. Qd2
{ White eyes h6,  is now set to go Be2 or f2-f3,  has options for his king on both flanks @@StartBracket@@even on c1 the king is fairly safe and we shouldn't forget that White still has attacking ideas of his own on the kingside@@EndBracket@@, and will be able to meet an immediate  13...Ng4  with  14.Bd4  .  In short, Black doesn't have enough for his pawn and Carlsen won both encounters from here in Carlsen-Vachier-Lagrave, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2020. }
