{ White keeps Rc1 in reserve and simply prepares to go Be2 and h4-h5, although Black may also be worried by ideas of a pinning Bb5 then Nf3-e5. }
7... Bg7
{ A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pp1p/2n2np1/3p4/3P1B1P/2N1P3/PP3PP1/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Ne4  This ambitious leap makes less sense than when White's bishop is on g5 and can be safely ignored:  8.Qb3  Nxc3  9.bxc3  Bg7  10.h5  when White enjoyed a bit of pressure on both flanks and an edge in Kapnisis-Teclaf, Prague 2020, with h6 a threat and also Nf3 on its way and then either Bd3 or Bb5,  fighting for a hold on e5.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pp1p/2n2np1/3p4/3P1B1P/2N1P3/PP3PP1/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...a6?!  8.Be2  . Black might have prevented a white bishop or knight from landing on b5,  but now h4-h5 is very much on its way:  8...h5  9.Nf3  Bg4  10.Ne5!?  . This is ever a tempting leap and a more aggressive choice than the  10.O-O  Bg7  11.Rc1  of Batsiashvili-Gvetadze, Georgian Women's Championship, Tbilisi 2021, pleasant for White though that was.  After our recommendation @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p2pp2/p1n2np1/3p3p/3P1BbP/2N1PN2/PP2BPP1/R2QK2R w KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ne5!?  Bxe2  11.Nxe2!  is a perhaps unexpected but strong recapture. White wants to obtain the initiative after any ...Nxe5; dxe5 exchange, threatens to weaken Black's queenside with a trade on c6 and most certainly does not fear a check:   11...Qa5+?!  12.Nc3  . Back again, but now Nxc6 bxc6; O-O followed by Be5,  Rc1 and Na4 in some order would give White a very nice position. After  12...Rc8?!  13.Qb3!  Black has kept his structure intact, but now finds the attack on b7 rather difficult to defend against:  B.1@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2r1kb1r/1p2pp2/p1n2np1/q2pN2p/3P1B1P/1QN1P3/PP3PP1/R3K2R b KQk - 4 13@@EndFEN@@  13...b5  14.O-O  would threaten Nxd5,  as well as just Rfc1 and a2-a4.  B.2@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2r1kb1r/1p2pp2/p1n2np1/q2pN2p/3P1B1P/1QN1P3/PP3PP1/R3K2R b KQk - 4 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Qb4  14.Qxb4  Nxb4  15.Ke2  . The queens are off, but White enjoys a large advantage, being set to take over the queenside after Rfc1 followed by Na4 then a2-a3. }
8. Be2
{ Simple chess, readying the h-pawn. Instead, Black seems to be OK after  8.Bb5  Bd7  or even  8...O-O!?  . }
8... h5 { Electing to block. } 9. Nf3
{ Completing minor piece development and guess where the queen is going? } 9...
O-O 10. Qb3
{ Tying down Black's bishop to b7, while simply intending to continue with Rc1 and O-O, after which White might begin to head forwards with Na4-c5 and/or Ne5. }
10... Na5
{ Probably the best defence, refusing to let the queen settle. It was seen in Paravyan-Matinian, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2021, where  11.Qb4  might have been met by  11...Nc6  , so White should probably step sideways. }
11. Qa3
{ White is now set to expand with Ne5 and castle, all the while as he aims to provoke an invasion on c4. }
11... Nc4 12. Qb4
{ Taking the knight is likely also an edge, but White continues to try and provoke weaknesses. }
12... a5 13. Qb5 Nd6 14. Qb3
{ White has made several queen moves in a row but retains a pleasant edge on account of the various weak spots in Black's queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Other 3rd Moves Bar 3...Bg7"]
[Black "3A | Richard Rapport – Peter Svidler | Paris 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Richard Rapport – Peter Svidler@@HeaderEnd@@Grand Chess Tour @@StartBracket@@Rapid@@EndBracket@@, Paris 2021 }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 c5 4. d5 b5 5. cxb5 a6 6. e3
{ A key little move, maintaining control and not rushing to create a target on e4 for Black to attack. White will only advance with e3-e4 once he has neutralised Black's immediate attempts at counterplay. }
6... Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. a4
{ Another important move, reinforcing White's grip on the all-important b5-square, a post he would like to maintain control of. }
8... Bb7 9. Nf3 e6
{ Black's main pawn break, but now he must allow White's queen to invade unless he prefers a slightly lifeless position with the d-file open and the queens off. }
10. dxe6 fxe6 11. Qd6
{ A star follow-up, preventing Black from expanding with ...d5 and, in short, denying him sufficient counterplay. }
11... axb5 12. Bxb5 Ne4
{ Trying to break out, as otherwise after, say,  12...Na6  13.O-O  Nc7  14.Be2!  White has sufficient control, having retained an important bishop, and c5 remains an issue for Black. }
13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. h5
{ It's certainly a handy rule of thumb in most Benko-type positions to be looking to go h4-h5 as soon as, or soon after, Black moves his knight from f6. }
14... Qf6
{ As remarkable as it may sound, this is already a decisive mistake.  Instead,  14...Nc6  15.hxg6  hxg6  and now:  A@@EndBracket@@ Not  16.Qxc5?  Bxf3  17.gxf3  Rf5  when White's queenside pieces are a little loose, not to mention f3,   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/3p2b1/2nQp1p1/1Bp5/P3b3/4PN2/1P3PP1/R1B1K2R w KQ - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Ra3!?  might have been stronger, indirectly offering support @@StartBracket@@the rook is now on a defended square@@EndBracket@@ to the bishop and thereby allowing White to consider Qxc5,  as well as even ideas of Bd2 Bxb2; Rc3!?,  sacrificing the exchange for attacking chances.  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/3p2b1/2nQp1p1/1Bp5/P3b3/4PN2/1P3PP1/R1B1K2R w KQ - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Qh2  Bxf3  17.gxf3  Ne5!  18.Qh7+  Kf7  19.Qh3  had just been all rather murky and unclear in Ilyin-Martin Gonzalez, correspondence 2013. }
15. h6
{ Harry gets in on the act, forcing the bishop into the corner and taking away the g7-square from the black king. }
15... Bh8 16. Rh4 { A lovely and deadly rook lift. } 16... Bxf3
{ This loses mundanely, but if...  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn3rkb/3p3p/3QpqpP/1Bp5/P3b2R/4PN2/1P3PP1/R1B1K3 b Q - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Bf5?  17.e4   B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn3rkb/3p3p/3QpqpP/1Bp5/P3b2R/4PN2/1P3PP1/R1B1K3 b Q - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Bc6  17.Rf4  Qd8  18.Bxc6  Nxc6  19.Rxf8+  Qxf8  20.Qxd7  when White is two pawns to the good and Black's position is collapsing. }
17. Rf4 Qd8 18. Bxd7
{ A deft tactic, overloading the defence. Svidler gave up in view of  18...Rxf4  @@StartBracket@@it's mate after  18...Nxd7  19.Qxe6+  or @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rkb/3B3p/3Qp1pP/2p5/P4R2/4Pb2/1P3PP1/R1B1K3 b Q - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Qxd7  19.Rxf8  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1q2kb/3B3p/3Qp1pP/2p5/P4r2/4Pb2/1P3PP1/R1B1K3 w Q - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Bxe6+  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Other 3rd Moves Bar 3...Bg7"]
[Black "3B | Simon Williams – Peter Poobalasingam | Hastings 2008"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@S. Williams – P. Poobalasingam@@HeaderEnd@@Hastings Masters 2008 }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 d6 4. Nc3 Nbd7
{ Slightly old-fashioned but by no means bad play from Black, against which White should classically seize space in the centre. }
5. e4 e5 6. d5 Nc5 7. Qc2
{ The simplest and best way to cover e4: Be2 then Be3 will follow. } 7... a5 8.
Be2 h6
{ Not for the first time this isn't an especially impressive way to deal with the notion of h4-h5. }
9. h5
{ This quickly works out well, although objectively White should probably first go  9.Be3  and O-O-O before looking to involve Harry. }
9... g5
{ A positionally horrible move, if one that is useful to know in general how to exploit.  Instead,  9...Nxh5!  10.Bxh5  gxh5  wouldn't have been so clear, with ...Rg8 and/or ...Bg4 on their way. }
10. Be3 b6 11. Bd1
{ You might have expected  11.O-O-O  from Simon, but this calm retreat is also very good for White, simply facilitating Ng1-e2-g3 to eye that huge hole on f5. }
11... Bd7 12. Nge2 c6
{ Black's only available pawn break, but it won't bring him any real counterplay. }
13. Bxc5 { 13.dxc6  Bxc6  14.Ng3  was also rather effective. } 13... bxc5 14.
Ng3 cxd5 15. cxd5
{ Simon has parted with his dark-squared bishop, but in this version of a Benoni or King's Indian, Black's normally favourite piece is a shadow of its ideal self, being badly blocked in by its own pawns. }
15... Be7 16. Be2
{ White would love to exchange bishops and obtain uncontested control of f5, hence Poobalasingam's next move. }
16... Kf8 17. Bb5 Bc8 18. Nd1
{ Simon is in no rush and calmly directs a second knight towards f5. And why should White rush? Black has absolutely zero counterplay. }
18... Ne8 19. Ne3 Ng7 20. Be2
{ Allowing White to consider a timely Bg4, although before that he first houses his king, which will be extremely safe on g1 with Black so passive. }
20... Rb8 21. O-O Kg8 22. b3
{ Simon continues to impress by making calm, small improving moves, here moving a pawn to a safer square while helping to eliminate any notion of ...a4. }
22... Kh7 23. Bg4 Ba6 24. Rfb1
{ Black might be devoid of any active ideas, but White isn't and he has a rather strong one in mind: a2-a3 and b3-b4, ripping open the queenside to favour his much more active forces. }
24... Rf8 25. Qc3 Bb5 26. a3 Be8
{ A very sad looking retreat, but so bad is Black's position it's hard to suggest anything that's all that much better and at least this hopes to break out with ...f5, on a very good day with a prevailing wind. }
27. b4 axb4 28. axb4 Rb5 29. Ra7 { The invasion begins in full earnest. } 29...
cxb4
{ This only helps White, but Be2 was set to force an exchange in any case. }
30. Rxb4 Qb8 31. Rxb5 { White is quite happy to exchange rooks... } 31... Qxa7
32. Rb1
{ ... and retain full control. Black's queen might be active enough, but the rest of his pieces find themselves in a very miserable huddle. }
32... f5
{ A final last-ditch attempt to salvage the game before White simply invaded with Qb4 and Qb7, after which material would have been quick to drop, with Black's dark-squared units so vulnerable. }
33. Nexf5 Bd7 34. Qe3 Qc7
{ 34...Qxe3  35.Nxe3  Bxg4  36.Nxg4  is the stuff of positional nightmares featuring bad bishops. }
35. Qb6 { Continuing to insist on the exchange of queens. } 35... Qxb6 36. Rxb6
Bxf5 37. Bxf5+
{ The right way to recapture as White wants to land up with an uncontested knight on f5. There are opposite-coloured bishops present, but also rooks and knights, and we shouldn't forget that opposite bishops favour the side attacking, which is obviously White. }
37... Kg8 38. Rb7 Bf6 39. Be6+
{ Once again, angling for an extremely good knight against a truly pitiful bishop. }
39... Kh8 40. Rd7 Ne8
{ Alternatively, if  40...Rd8  41.Rf7  Ne8  42.Bd7  when something major is about to give. }
41. Nf5 Bg7 42. Ne7
{ White can do much better than pocket d6. There's just no good way for Black to meet the threat of Ng6+. A real positional tour de force from Simon. }
