[White "4. King's Indian Style (...Bg7 + ...d6)"]
[Black "Chapter Four: King's Indian Style"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Chapter Four: King's Indian Style@@HeaderEnd@@ } 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7
{ Black's most popular choice, continuing in true King's Indian fashion. } 4.
Nc3
{ Once again, we see White keen not to fall too far behind in development while preparing e2-e4.   4.h5!?  is a slightly unnecessary and not wholly sound pawn sacrifice, if one which might well work at fast time controls or against any opponent looking especially timid once 3.h4 hits the board.  4...Nxh5  5.e4  and now:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/6p1/7n/2PPP3/8/PP3PP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5!?  6.d5  d6  saw White unable to resist the exchange sacrifice in Vestby-Ellingsen-Daianu, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2020, but it just doesn't threaten all that much with the black king still on e8 and White hardly leading in development. As such, White should prefer to develop:  7.Be2  Nf6  8.Nc3  . Objectively, there probably isn't quite enough for a pawn here, but at least f2-f4 and g2-g4 are on their way.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/6p1/7n/2PPP3/8/PP3PP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O ?!  6.g4!  forcing the pace is much stronger than  6.Rxh5?  gxh5  7.Qxh5  f5!?  . After @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppppppbp/6p1/7n/2PPP3/8/PP3PP1/RNBQKBNR w KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.g4!  Nf6  7.e5  Ne8  8.f4  this already looks extremely scary for Black with Qe2-h2 but one idea.  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/6p1/7n/2PPP3/8/PP3PP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  6.Be2  @@StartBracket@@once again, the exchange sacrifice led nowhere after  6.Rxh5?  gxh5  7.Qxh5  c5  in Mietkiewicz-Niekras, Poznan 2016@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p2p1/7n/2PPP3/8/PP2BPP1/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  7.Nc3  . Now g2-g4 is imminent if Black is too slow and he should probably react in the centre with his c- or e-pawns:  7...e5  8.Nf3  .  As  8.d5  h5!  would be a powerful closing of lines, White should probably retain the tension and look to drum up a bit of play with Bg5,  Qd2 and O-O-O. }
4... d6
{ We'll take this as our main line, in part just because it's been by far Black's most popular move. Instead:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2PP3P/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...O-O  5.e4  almost always leads to Line 4B after  5...d6  .  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2PP3P/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c5  5.d5  we saw back in Line 3A.  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2PP3P/2N5/PP2PPP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d5  5.h5!  we saw in Line 1B. }
5. e4
{ Needless to say, White expands without delay and now we'll focus our attention on:  4A@@EndBracket@@  5...Nc6   4B@@EndBracket@@  5...O-O   Instead,  5...c5  6.d5  would take play back into the realm of Line 3A.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP2P/2N5/PP3PP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...h5  6.Be2  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP2P/2N5/PP3PP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...h6  6.Be2  return to Lines 2A and 2B respectively, while on the odd occasion Black touches his queen's knight: }
5... Na6
{ 5...Nbd7  6.Be2  calmly preparing h4-h5 @@StartBracket@@although for the especially aggressive among you, the  6.g4!?  of Jacobson-Mishra, Charlotte 2019, may also be of interest@@EndBracket@@. After  6.Be2  e5  7.d5  Nc5  8.Qc2  is the smoothest way to cover e4 and the same method we used in Line 3B.  8...a5  9.h5!?  .  And why not push on so? Black may now worry about h5-h6,  although White might prefer to retain the tension rather than force ...Bf8-e7. That said, by analogy with Line 3B,  9.Be3  is also a good move, while in S.Ernst-Pruijssers, Amstelveen @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2019, White even preferred to provoke ...h6 with  9.Bg5  .  Back to  9.h5!?  when play might continue  9...Nxh5?  10.Bxh5  gxh5  11.Rxh5  . This recapture is a small issue with the bishop still on f8,  but here h7 is simply vulnerable, Be3,  Nge2 and O-O-O on their way and all because Black can't deploy his unopposed bishop straight to g4 on account of the forking Rg5. }
6. Be2
{ Sensibly not looking to punish the slightly unexpected arrival of the knight on the rim and now the logical  6...e5  7.d5  Nc5  8.Qc2  would transpose to our coverage of 5...Nbd7. }
6... h5 7. Bg5
{ Just as in Line 2A, White is happy to exploit without delay the weakening of g5 by Black.   7.Nf3  first would also be good. }
7... c6 8. Qd2
{ This retained a fair degree of flexibility while also preparing Bh6 in the event of Black castling in Fedoseev-Gordievsky, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2019.  White's king is likely to go long and he may even consider expanding with f2-f4 ahead of Nf3 or switch to an f2-f3 and g2-g4 approach if Black bravely doesn't delay castling. }
