1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7
{ Black's most popular choice, continuing in true King's Indian fashion. } 4.
Nc3
{ Once again, we see White keen not to fall too far behind in development while preparing e2-e4. }
4... d6
{ We'll take this as our main line, in part just because it's been by far Black's most popular move. }
5. e4 { Needless to say, White expands without delay. } 5... Nbd7 6. Be2
{ Calmly preparing h4-h5,  although for the especially aggressive among you, the  6.g4!?  of Jacobson-Mishra, Charlotte 2019, may also be of interest. }
6... e5 7. d5 Nc5 8. Qc2
{ The smoothest way to cover e4 and the same method we used in Line 3B. } 8...
a5 9. h5
{ And why not push on so? Black may now worry about h5-h6,  although White might prefer to retain the tension rather than force ...Bf8-e7.  That said, by analogy with Line 3B,  9.Be3  is also a good move, while in S.Ernst-Pruijssers, Amstelveen @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2019, White even preferred to provoke ...h6 with  9.Bg5  . }
9... Nxh5 10. Bxh5 gxh5 11. Rxh5
{ This recapture is a small issue with the bishop still on f8,  but here h7 is simply vulnerable, Be3,  Nge2 and O-O-O on their way and all because Black can't deploy his unopposed bishop straight to g4 on account of the forking  11...Bg4  12.Rg5  . }
