[Black "4A | KID Style with 5...Nc6 | Black plays 7...c6, 10...cxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Nc6
{ Not a move you're likely to see much of at club level, but an important alternative to  5...O-O  and one which Magnus Carlsen gave his seal of approval to when hit by Vladimir Fedoseev's 3.h4 at the 2021 FIDE World Cup.  Black prepares to strike back against d4 to obtain some counterplay while aiming to lure White forwards in the centre. We should also note that this move has been recommended by Peter Svidler and then in Gawain Jones's excellent Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian course. }
6. d5
{ White is provoked and opts for the most critical move.  Note that  6.Be2  no longer cuts the mustard on account of  6...e5  , and if  7.d5?!  Nd4  , one of the main points behind this line for Black.  However, if you have some experience of the Sämisch Panno you may prefer @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/2PPP2P/2N5/PP3PP1/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nge2  O-O  7.f3  @@StartBracket@@  7.h5?  Nxh5  8.Bg5  f6!  9.Be3  f5  unfortunately didn't give Simon much for the pawn in Williams-Mestel, British League 2010@@EndBracket@@.  We should also mention that one day @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/2PPP2P/2N5/PP3PP1/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nf3  will receive a test when  6...Bg4  7.d5!?  Ne5  8.Be2  Nxf3+  9.gxf3!?  Bh5  is Peter Svidler's line-closing idea, leading to a rich and unbalanced middlegame after  10.Be3  where White will want to get in f3-f4 at some point. }
6... Ne5 { Black continues to provoke. } 7. Be2
{ Our normal development, preparing h4-h5,  and a much stronger choice than  7.f4?  Neg4  . }
7... c6 8. Nf3
{ A more logical choice than the  8.Nh3  of Atakhan-Darini, Tehran 2021, as White challenges Black's centralised knight. }
8... Nxf3+ 9. Bxf3
{ Suddenly  9...--  10.dxc6  bxc6  11.e5  is a threat and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp2ppbp/2pp1np1/3P4/2P1P2P/2N2B2/PP3PP1/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...O-O  would be well met by  10.h5  . }
9... Bd7 10. Be3
{ Preventing ...Qb6,  which could have become an annoying idea in the event of  10.h5  Nxh5!  11.Bxh5  gxh5  .  This variation with 9...Bd7 is another as-yet-untested @@StartBracket@@at OTB@@EndBracket@@ recommendation from Peter Svidler's fine Grünfeld course, but we would not be unhappy here as White. With ...Qb6 off the agenda White is now ready to go h4-h5 and would be delighted if Black castled into the attack: }
10... cxd5 11. exd5
{ An unexpected recapture, but also a decent one, opening the e-file and preparing to deny Black counterplay. }
11... h5 12. O-O
{ White simply intends to take control of the position with Rfe1 and Bd4, while both Qb3 and Rac1 may also prove useful if White wishes to exert some pressure on the queenside and/or arrange to break with c4-c5. }
