[White "4. King's Indian Style (...Bg7 + ...d6)"]
[Black "4A | KID Style with 5...Nc6 | Black plays 7...h5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 Nc6
{ Not a move you're likely to see much of at club level, but an important alternative to  5...O-O  and one which Magnus Carlsen gave his seal of approval to when hit by Vladimir Fedoseev's 3.h4 at the 2021 FIDE World Cup.  Black prepares to strike back against d4 to obtain some counterplay while aiming to lure White forwards in the centre. We should also note that this move has been recommended by Peter Svidler and then in Gawain Jones's excellent Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian course. }
6. d5
{ White is provoked and opts for the most critical move.  Note that  6.Be2  no longer cuts the mustard on account of  6...e5  , and if  7.d5?!  Nd4  , one of the main points behind this line for Black.  However, if you have some experience of the Sämisch Panno you may prefer @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/2PPP2P/2N5/PP3PP1/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nge2  O-O  7.f3  @@StartBracket@@  7.h5?  Nxh5  8.Bg5  f6!  9.Be3  f5  unfortunately didn't give Simon much for the pawn in Williams-Mestel, British League 2010@@EndBracket@@.  We should also mention that one day @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/2PPP2P/2N5/PP3PP1/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nf3  will receive a test when  6...Bg4  7.d5!?  Ne5  8.Be2  Nxf3+  9.gxf3!?  Bh5  is Peter Svidler's line-closing idea, leading to a rich and unbalanced middlegame after  10.Be3  where White will want to get in f3-f4 at some point. }
6... Ne5 { Black continues to provoke. } 7. Be2
{ Our normal development, preparing h4-h5,  and a much stronger choice than  7.f4?  Neg4  . }
7... h5 8. Nf3
{ White wastes no time in challenging the strong knight on e5 and may now be able to bring his dark-squared bishop to e3.  Instead,  8.Bf4  O-O  9.Nf3  Nxf3+  10.gxf3  c6  gave Black sufficient counterplay in Fedoseev-Carlsen, FIDE World Cup, Krasnaya Polyana 2021. }
8... Nxf3+ 9. gxf3
{ A more dynamic recapture than  9.Bxf3  Bg4  would be.  After @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1ppb1/3p1np1/3P3p/2P1P2P/2N2n2/PP2BPP1/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.gxf3  , in contrast to the line we mentioned above after 6.Nf3,  Black has a pawn, not a bishop, on h5,  so his kingside should be slightly weaker. }
9... O-O 10. Be3
{ This should be a better square for the bishop than Fedoseev's choice of f4, in part because it prevents any ...Qb6 ideas. White will now continue with Qd2 and can be quite flexible with his king, which has all of f1, g1, staying on e1 and escaping to c1 available to it. }
10... c6 11. Qd2
{ White has ideas of Bh6 to weaken the black king's defences and may also meet a slow response from Black with f3-f4, beginning to roll forwards, with Rg1 and f4-f5 set to follow. }
11... Kh7
{ Gawain Jones's sensible recommendation on his course in this untested position. Black prevents Bh6 and also gets off the g-file, while now  12.f4  b5!  should give Black sufficient counterplay. }
12. Rg1
{ It's hard to believe that the rook will find a better post than the half-open g-file. Now White would quite like to attack with Bd3, Rg5 @@StartBracket@@preparing a strong exchange sacrifice in the event of ...Bh6 with Rxh5!@@EndBracket@@, O-O-O, Rdg1 and e4-e5. }
12... Bd7 13. f4
{ A change of approach after Black's sensible last move.  Instead,  13.Bd3  cxd5  14.cxd5  Rc8  should be OK for Black, as should @@StartFEN@@r2q1r2/pp1bppbk/2pp1np1/3P3p/2P1P2P/2N1BP2/PP1QBP2/R3K1R1 w Q - 4 13@@EndFEN@@  13.O-O-O  cxd5  14.cxd5  Qa5  15.Kb1  Rfc8  16.Bd3  Rc7  @@StartBracket@@Jones@@EndBracket@@ when White should probably try  17.Ne2  , looking to make something of his space advantage and a knight on d4 after the exchange of queens.  The more ambitious text move intends f2-f3 @@StartBracket@@to shore up e4 and take control of g4@@EndBracket@@, then Bd3 and crashing through with e4-e5. }
13... b5
{ Black should react so before he is steamrollered in the centre and on the kingside. }
14. cxb5
{ Electing to go a pawn up for now if Black takes on d5 @@StartBracket@@  14...cxb5  15.f3  prepares Bd3 and after  15...b4  16.Nb5  White should be slightly for choice, since his knight can easily drop back into d4@@EndBracket@@.  Lovers of wild positions may, though, also wish to consider the arguably even more gung-ho @@StartFEN@@r2q1r2/p2bppbk/2pp1np1/1p1P3p/2P1PP1P/2N1B3/PP1QBP2/R3K1R1 w Q - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.dxc6  Bxc6  15.f3  bxc4  16.f5!?  . }
14... cxd5 15. exd5
{ This fascinating position is extremely unclear and in need of tests. White's structure is shot, but he is a pawn up for now @@StartBracket@@you never know, that queenside majority could be very useful in an endgame@@EndBracket@@, and we'd be quite happy in his shoes.  One idea is to take control of the position with O-O-O and Bd4, another Bd3, followed by a possible f2-f3 and Rg5, looking to lever open the black king's defences with f4-f5.  Finally, we should point out that after Rg5 Bh6, White should be very happy to leave the rook on g5, sacrificing the exchange to the detriment of Black's king. }
