6... e5 7. d5
{ Pushing past in approved fashion, although curiously  7.dxe5?!  dxe5  8.Qxd8  Rxd8  was preferred in no less a clash than Vachier-Lagrave-Carlsen @@StartBracket@@note the colours!@@EndBracket@@, Magnus Carlsen Invitational 2020, played near the start of those sub-optimal lockdown days.  At this juncture Black often plays @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2pbp/3p1np1/3Pp3/2P1P2P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...h5  , obstructing Harry, but also allowing White a very pleasant game after  8.Nf3  and Ng5,  emphasising the light-square weaknesses in the black camp, as we saw back in Line 2A. }
7... c6
{ 7...h6?!  8.g4!  . Just as in Line 2B, this is an extremely strong advance, threatening to open lines with g4-g5 and also simply intending to limber up with menace through Be3,  Qd2 and O-O-O. }
8. h5 { If allowed, press ahead on the kingside is very much our mantra. } 8...
cxd5 9. cxd5
{ Maintaining the symmetry helps to make it harder for Black to obtain counterplay, although we should note that Richard Rapport preferred  9.exd5  in Rapport-Gallagher, Gibraltar 2014. }
9... Nbd7 10. Be3
{ A fine multi-purpose post for the bishop, although ambitious souls may also wish to consider  10.g4!?  . }
10... Nc5 11. h6
{ White gives up on any idea of mate in return for major positional gain. }
11... Bh8 12. Bxc5
{ By no means obligatory, but a good exchange with Black's now unopposed bishop currently rather sidelined in the corner. }
12... dxc5 13. Nf3 Ne8 14. Nd2
{ The knight is bound for c4 to challenge the blockader on d6. White will then keep up the pressure with Qb3 and potentially O-O-O.  Black enjoys an unopposed dark-squared bishop, but is also low on counterplay and clearly worse, as we'll see in Praggnanandhaa-Yip. }
