[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 O-O
{ Black's main move, housing his king without delay and continuing to play all the normal King's Indian moves. }
6. Be2
{ White tees up h4-h5 and reaches a position which can also come about via a @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Be2  O-O  6.h4!?  move order, one which has tempted a number of strong players over the years, including Gerald Abrahams twice in the late 1940s!  Now we'll examine ideas with  6...e5  and  6...Nc6  for Black. His two most popular moves in practice, though, have been  6...c5  , when  7.d5  is the subject of Chapter Five, and @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP2P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...h5  when  7.Nf3  takes play back into the sphere of Line 2A.  Gambit Alternative  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP2P/2N5/PP3PP1/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.h5!?  is a tempting alternative here and a much better gambit played now that Black has castled than on move four. Indeed, Gawain Jones admitted that he was 'a bit scared by 6.h5',  so let's take a quick look:   6...Nxh5  7.g4!  kicking the knight back and beginning to seize space so simply must be better than  7.Rxh5?!  gxh5  8.Qxh5  f5!  , even though this was seen in the fairly high-profile online rapid game Yoo-Liang, 2021.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p2p1/7n/2PPP1P1/2N5/PP3P2/R1BQKBNR b KQ - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.g4!  Nf6  8.g5  Nh5?  would be quickly cleaned up by  9.Be2  , so the knight must retreat to d7 or e8,  after which White can even continue to expand:   8...Ne8  9.f4  not only seizing more space, but also clearing the second rank and so a stronger continuation than the 9.Be3 of Zakaryan-Etingof, Sochi 2021. White already threatens the crude but strong Qd2-h2,  so the engines feel that Black must react with a double-central advance:   9...c5  @@StartBracket@@possible as  10.Qd2  Bxd4  11.Qh2  h5!  keeps lines relatively closed@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqnrk1/pp2ppbp/3p2p1/2p3P1/2PPPP2/2N5/PP6/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.d5  f5!  and now Black has ideas of ...Qa5,  as well as ...Rf7. It seems a shame to unrestrict Black's pieces with  11.gxf6!?  , but this does open lines and White doesn't appear to have anything clear after  11.Qc2  fxe4  .  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqnrk1/pp2p1bp/3p1Pp1/2pP4/2P1PP2/2N5/PP6/R1BQKBNR b KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.gxf6!?  Nxf6  12.Nh3  the knight is bound for a strong post on g5,  Black dare not weaken further his light squares with a trade on h3,  and there are also ideas of f4-f5.  In short, White has decent compensation and 6.h5!? very much looks like an idea we may soon see more of. }
6... e5 7. d5
{ Pushing past in approved fashion, although curiously  7.dxe5?!  dxe5  8.Qxd8  Rxd8  was preferred in no less a clash than Vachier-Lagrave-Carlsen @@StartBracket@@note the colours!@@EndBracket@@, Magnus Carlsen Invitational 2020, played near the start of those sub-optimal lockdown days.  At this juncture Black often plays @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2pbp/3p1np1/3Pp3/2P1P2P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...h5  , obstructing Harry, but also allowing White a very pleasant game after  8.Nf3  and Ng5,  emphasising the light-square weaknesses in the black camp, as we saw back in Line 2A. }
7... Na6
{ The knight heads for c5 to pressure e4. It can also come via d7 and, indeed,  7...Nbd7  8.h5  Nc5  would transpose.  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2pbp/3p1np1/3Pp3/2P1P2P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...a5  8.h5  Na6  9.h6  @@StartBracket@@9.g4!? is also possible, but this cramping advance is rather tempting and preferable to exchanging on g6,  as White did in Eltigani-Murzin, Internet  (blitz)  2020@@EndBracket@@  9...Bh8  10.Bg5  .  Black will be able to get out of the pin, but remains under the cosh with g2-g4 @@StartBracket@@and f2-f3 if required@@EndBracket@@ on the way. White will continue with Qd2 and O-O-O,  ready to meet any future ...f5 with a file-opening gxf5. }
8. h5 { And, of course, there's no reason not to make our favourite advance. }
8... Nc5 9. h6
{ Again, we opt for a restrictive further advance. Baadur Jobava has preferred  9.Bg5  , but there's no reason not to cramp the black kingside.  White's advantage probably isn't as large as the '+1.5' or so displayed by the engines, but it is a very nice one since Black is again going to find himself a little low on counterplay. }
9... Bh8 10. Bg5 { Only now do we pin with ...h6 taken off the table. } 10...
a5 11. f3
{ White calmly covers e4 and g4, while preparing to continue with Qd2 and g2-g4. }
11... Bd7 12. Qd2 Qb8 13. g4
{ This seems preferable to the also pretty decent  13.Nh3  of Jacobson-Siva, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2021. Black is clearly going to struggle to break with ...f5,  but can he obtain some play on the other flank? }
13... c6 14. Nh3
{ Simply ignoring Black as the knight sets off for f2 then d3 to challenge Black's best piece. Meanwhile ...b5 will always run into dxc6, so Black is likely to resolve the central tension: }
14... cxd5 15. Nxd5
{ White sidesteps  15.cxd5  b5  and increases his control of the position, with Nf2-d3 still very much on the agenda. }
15... Nxd5 16. cxd5
{ White already enjoys a clear advantage. Black may be able to prevent him castling queenside, but the king will be quite safe on e1 or even f1. Meanwhile Black's bishop on h8 is far from happy and any ...f5 @@StartBracket@@or ...f6; Be3 f5@@EndBracket@@; gxf5 gxf5 exchange is surely just going to lead to trouble down the g-file. }
