9... Bh8 10. Bg5 { Only now do we pin with ...h6 taken off the table. } 10...
c6
{ 10...Qe8  11.f3  Shoring up e4 is much stronger than the  11.Bxf6?!  Bxf6  12.Bg4?  Bxg4  13.Qxg4  Nd3+  of Boruchovsky-Saveljev, Internet  (blitz)  2022. And after @@StartFEN@@r1b1qrkb/ppp2p1p/3p1npP/2nPp1B1/2P1P3/2N5/PP2BPP1/R2QK1NR w KQ - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11.f3  :  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1qrkb/ppp2p1p/3p1npP/2nPp1B1/2P1P3/2N2P2/PP2B1P1/R2QK1NR b KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nh5!?  12.g4!  Nf4  13.Nh3  White is challenging the knight without delay, although seizing further space with  13.b4!?  Na6  14.a3  must also be a good policy.  After @@StartFEN@@r1b1qrkb/ppp2p1p/3p2pP/2nPp1B1/2P1PnP1/2N2P2/PP2B3/R2QK1NR w KQ - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Nh3  play might continue  13...f6!?  14.Bxf4  exf4  15.Nxf4  . Such pawn sacrifices are known in the King's Indian and here too Black does obtain an unopposed dark-squared bishop in return. However, White is a pawn up and doing well, since the knight on f4 is a pretty good piece too and Black's king can't sidestep to h8:   15...f5  16.gxf5  is the problem for Black. Rg1+ will come with check and if he doesn't recapture, that knight is going to sink into e6. White's king is admittedly vulnerable to a check via ...Be5 and ...Bg3+,  but it should be able to find perfectly reasonable sanctuary after Kd2 and Kc2.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1qrkb/ppp2p1p/3p1npP/2nPp1B1/2P1P3/2N2P2/PP2B1P1/R2QK1NR b KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nh5!?  12.g4!  f6  13.Be3  Nf4  14.Bxc5!  dxc5  15.Qd2  White has the much better structure and should be doing quite well, as he'll have time to whisk his king to b1 before Black's bishop gets out to g5.  Once again, ...f5 will be met by gxf5 and the other simple plan is to improve White's pieces while challenging the best black one with Bd3 and Nge2. }
