[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. King's Indian Style (...Bg7 + ...d6)"]
[Black "4B | KID Style with 5...O-O | Gambit Alternative 6.h5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 O-O
{ Black's main move, housing his king without delay and continuing to play all the normal King's Indian moves. }
6. h5
{ This is a tempting alternative here and a much better gambit played now that Black has castled than on move four. Indeed, Gawain Jones admitted that he was 'a bit scared by 6.h5', so let's take a quick look: }
6... Nxh5 7. g4
{ Kicking the knight back and beginning to seize space so simply must be better than  7.Rxh5?!  gxh5  8.Qxh5  f5!  , even though this was seen in the fairly high-profile online rapid game Yoo-Liang, 2021. }
7... Nf6 8. g5
{ Now  8...Nh5?  would be quickly cleaned up by  9.Be2  , so the knight must retreat to d7 or e8,  after which White can even continue to expand: }
8... Ne8 9. f4
{ Not only seizing more space, but also clearing the second rank and so a stronger continuation than the 9.Be3 of Zakaryan-Etingof, Sochi 2021. White already threatens the crude but strong Qd2-h2, so the engines feel that Black must react with a double-central advance: }
9... c5
{ This is possible as  10.Qd2  Bxd4  11.Qh2  h5!  keeps lines relatively closed. }
10. d5 f5 { Now Black has ideas of ...Qa5, as well as ...Rf7. } 11. gxf6
{ It seems a shame to unrestrict Black's pieces with  11.gxf6!?  , but this does open lines and White doesn't appear to have anything clear after  11.Qc2  fxe4  . }
11... Nxf6 12. Nh3
{ The knight is bound for a strong post on g5, Black dare not weaken further his light squares with a trade on h3, and there are also ideas of f4-f5.  In short, White has decent compensation and 6.h5!? very much looks like an idea we may soon see more of. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. King's Indian Style (...Bg7 + ...d6)"]
[Black "4B | Rameshbabu Praggnanandhaa – Carissa Yip | Chess24 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@R. Praggnanandhaa – C. Yip@@HeaderEnd@@Gelfand Challenge on Chess24 @@StartBracket@@Rapid@@EndBracket@@, 2021 }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
{ The Indian wunderkind is happy to allow a Grünfeld, but  3.h4  Bg7  4.Nc3  d6  5.e4  O-O  6.Be2  would, of course, be our move order. }
3... Bg7 4. e4 O-O 5. Be2 d6 6. h4 { Finally involving Harry... } 6... e5 7. d5
c6 8. h5 { ...who is already playing quite a major role! } 8... cxd5 9. cxd5
Nbd7 10. Be3
{ A fine spot for the bishop.   10.g4!?  Nc5  11.h6  Bh8  12.f3  and only then Be3 would also leave Black looking a little cramped. }
10... Nc5 11. h6 { AlphaZero style restriction of the black kingside. } 11...
Bh8 12. Bxc5
{ And now a big and well-judged exchange from Praggnanandhaa. Black will be able to get her bishop out of the corner, but not obtain sufficient counterplay, in part due to her inferior structure and also because of White's upcoming knight manoeuvre. }
12... dxc5 13. Nf3 Ne8 14. Nd2
{ Preparing to challenge Black's blockading knight once it reaches d6, as well as applying a bit of pressure on e5 from c4. }
14... Bd7
{ 14...Nd6  15.Nc4  Bf6!?  wasn't ridiculous, but after  16.Nxd6  Qxd6  17.Qd2  White retains the upper hand and may even be ready to advance Delroy after Nb5. He just needs to avoid castling into a pawn storm, so  17...a6  @@StartBracket@@or  17...Bd7  18.Bb5!  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p3p1p/p2q1bpP/2pPp3/4P3/2N5/PP1QBPP1/R3K2R w KQ - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18.a4  would be wise, and if  18...Bd7  19.a5  when the king will be quite safe on g1,  after which White might arrange to break with b2-b4 or manoeuvre his knight round to c4 via a3 or e3. }
15. a4
{ Once again, keeping Black's counterplay under control is Praggnanandhaa's immediate aim. }
15... Qg5 16. g3
{ Continuing to restrict. Black's queen does make it hard for White to now castle kingside, but the king is happy enough in the centre and may even still go long. }
16... Rd8
{ Not the most active of moves, but  16...f5?  17.d6!  would have been strong followed by Bc4@@StartBracket@@+@@EndBracket@@ or  17...Bf6??  18.Nf3  Qg4  19.Nxe5  . }
17. Qb3 b6
{ Another move where one has the impression that it was played with a slightly defeatist air, but even after  17...Nd6  18.Nc4  Nxc4  19.Qxc4  White would have been in full control, in part because Black is badly struggling to successfully free her position with ...f5 and as Qb3 and Nb1-d2-c4 is a manoeuvre very much on the cards. }
18. O-O-O
{ Now that Black isn't really in a position to launch the queenside pawns, Praggnanandhaa appreciates that his king will be quite safe on b1. }
18... Nd6 19. Kb1 Qe7 20. Nc4
{ Thematic as White's light-squared grip on the position begins to become quite pronounced. }
20... Rb8 21. Nxd6 Qxd6 22. Bb5
{ Improving the bishop while angling to be left with a knight against a not especially amazing dark-squared bishop. }
22... Bg4 23. Rd3 Bf6 24. Qc4
{ A short move and a strong one. White simply wants to go Bc6 without Black having ...a6 in response. }
24... Rfd8 25. Bc6 Qf8 { Prudently trying to get out of the way of Nb5. } 26.
f3 Bc8 27. Rhd1
{ 27.Nb5!  immediately was on, and if  27...a6  28.Na7  , which rather highlights Black's lack of activity and coordination. }
27... Be7 28. Nb5 Ba6
{ Yip hopes that there might be some salvation with opposite-coloured bishops the only minor pieces left, but White's huge advantage will persist even after an exchange on b5. }
29. Qc1
{ A powerful retreat, ruling out any ...Bg5 activation, while preparing to unpin with Ra3. }
29... Bxb5 30. axb5 Rd6
{ The a-pawn quickly drops off after this, but even  30...Bd6  31.Qg5  f6  32.Qh4  would have left Black under the cosh with White all set to increase the pressure with f3-f4. Never lose sight of the long-term danger to the black king posed by having Harry wedged in its throat on h6! }
31. Ra3 Qd8 32. Rxa7 Bg5
{ Regaining the pawn, but only at the huge cost of seeing White beginning to start a pawn juggernaut. }
33. f4
{ Note how Praggnanandhaa only now opens lines, content that he has matters under control and isn't opening lines to help Black's dark-squared-moving pieces. }
33... Bxh6 34. Qc3 Bg7
{ Of course,  34...exf4?  35.e5  Bg7  36.gxf4  would but have been completely crushing. }
35. fxe5 Qg5 36. Qf3
{ Praggnanandhaa has seen the deeper into the position and the game is up for Yip. }
36... Qxe5 37. Qxf7+ Kh8 38. Qxg7+
{ Classy and crushing play. White's central connected passed pawns will now sweep all before them. }
38... Qxg7 39. Rxg7 Kxg7 40. e5
{ White might only have a pawn for the exchange, but already Black could resign, so powerful is the white central juggernaut. }
40... Rdd8 41. d6 Kf7 42. Bd5+ Kg7 43. Bc4
{ As we all know, two pawns on the sixth can defeat a rook and here White can also play against the slightly exposed black monarch. }
43... Re8 44. e6 Rbd8 45. Kc2 Kf6 46. e7 Rd7 47. Rf1+
{ And this should really have led to Black throwing in the towel without delay. }
47... Kg5 48. Rf8 Rexe7 49. dxe7 Rxe7 50. Rb8 Re3 51. Rxb6 Rxg3 52. Rc6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. King's Indian Style Main Line (6...c5)"]
[Black "Chapter Five: KID Style Main Line (6...c5)"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Chapter Five: KID Style Main Line@@HeaderEnd@@ } 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 O-O 6. Be2 c5
{ Black's most popular and best response, angling for counterplay down the long, dark-square diagonal. This has been played and recommended by a number of grandmasters, so should probably be thought of as the main line. }
7. d5
{ In standard fashion we push past and maintain a space advantage. Now there are two important lines:  5A@@EndBracket@@  7...b5   5B@@EndBracket@@  7...e6   Somewhat behind, albeit in third place in the popularity stakes is  7...h5  when we saw that White should be happy to eye the weakened g5-square after  8.Nf3  back in Line 2A.  At lower levels, Black might not be aware of the need to try and obtain some counterplay pronto, and White should be happy to see any fairly slow moves here.  @@HeaderStart@@Slower Moves@@HeaderEnd@@Black Plays 7...a6  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2pP4/2P1P2P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...a6  8.a4!  clamping down on Black's counterplay without delay and so cutting out all Benko options.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1p2ppbp/p2p1np1/2pP4/P1P1P2P/2N5/1P2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nbd7?!  9.h5  and White already enjoys a largely free hand, as Black lacks counterplay and also suffers from something of a problematic light-squared bishop.  9...Ne5  10.h6!?  . Our favourite long-term, kingside squeezing-up move appears even better here than the 10.Nf3 of Artemiev-Bodnaruk, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2021.   10...Bh8  11.f4  Neg4  12.Ra3!?  is by no means the only good move, but one we quite like. If Black is careless the rook might manage to swing across to g3 and win material. Now Nh3-g5 is on the agenda, exploiting White's significant space advantage and there may also be ideas of a timely e4-e5 or f4-f5 and if ...Ne5; g2-g4.  Finally, do note why  12.Rh4  isn't quite as good:  12...e5!  and White is unable to take twice on g4 in view of the check on h4.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1p2ppbp/p2p1np1/2pP4/P1P1P2P/2N5/1P2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e6  9.h5!  Black might have correctly countered in the centre, but the inclusion of ...a6 and a4 reduces his options on the queenside.  Meanwhile, as usual, White has options with h5-h6 and hxg6,  and we'll see him winning in brutal fashion in a clash between your two authors, Williams-Palliser.  Black Plays 7...Nbd7  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2pP4/2P1P2P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nbd7?!  8.h5  Re8  9.h6!  is consistent and preferable to the  9.hxg6  hxg6  10.Bf4  of Cruz Lledo-Esteban Moreno, Sueca 2019, when Black might have hit back with  10...e6!  .  After @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/pp1nppbp/3p1np1/2pP3P/2P1P3/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR w KQ - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.h6!  Bh8  10.Nf3  the knight is bound for its favourite square and Black is somewhat hampered, in part because ...e6 or ...e5 will run into a strong capture.  Black Plays 7...Na6  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2pP4/2P1P2P/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Na6?!  8.h5  Nc7  9.Bf4!?  is a tempting alternative to 9.h6 with Black's play quite slow. White dissuades ...e6 and may now go in for a route one approach:  9...a6  10.a4  Nd7  11.Qd2  and already White enjoyed a pretty strong attack with Bh6 imminent in Ruckschloss-Mace, Parthenay 2000. }
