[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. King's Indian Style Main Line (6...c5)"]
[Black "5 | Slower 7th Moves | Black plays 7...a6, 8...Nbd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 O-O 6. Be2 c5
{ Black's most popular and best response, angling for counterplay down the long, dark-square diagonal. This has been played and recommended by a number of grandmasters, so should probably be thought of as the main line. }
7. d5 { In standard fashion we push past and maintain a space advantage. } 7...
a6 8. a4
{ Clamping down on Black's counterplay without delay and so cutting out all Benko options. }
8... Nbd7 9. h5
{ White already enjoys a largely free hand, as Black lacks counterplay and also suffers from something of a problematic light-squared bishop. }
9... Ne5 10. h6
{ Our favourite long-term, kingside squeezing-up move appears even better here than the  10.Nf3  of Artemiev-Bodnaruk, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2021. }
10... Bh8 11. f4 Neg4 12. Ra3
{ By no means the only good move, but one we quite like. If Black is careless the rook might manage to swing across to g3 and win material.  Now Nh3-g5 is on the agenda, exploiting White's significant space advantage and there may also be ideas of a timely e4-e5 or f4-f5 and if ...Ne5; g2-g4.  Finally, do note why  12.Rh4  isn't quite as good:  12...e5!  and White is unable to take twice on g4 in view of the check on h4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. King's Indian Style Main Line (6...c5)"]
[Black "5 | Slower 7th Moves | Black plays 7...a6, 8...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 O-O 6. Be2 c5
{ Black's most popular and best response, angling for counterplay down the long, dark-square diagonal. This has been played and recommended by a number of grandmasters, so should probably be thought of as the main line. }
7. d5 { In standard fashion we push past and maintain a space advantage. } 7...
a6 8. a4
{ Clamping down on Black's counterplay without delay and so cutting out all Benko options. }
8... e6 9. h5
{ Black might have correctly countered in the centre, but the inclusion of ...a6 and a4 reduces his options on the queenside.  Meanwhile, as usual, White has options with h5-h6 and hxg6, and we'll see him winning in brutal fashion in a clash between your two authors, Williams-Palliser. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. King's Indian Style Main Line (6...c5)"]
[Black "5 | Slower 7th Moves | Black plays 7...Nbd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 O-O 6. Be2 c5
{ Black's most popular and best response, angling for counterplay down the long, dark-square diagonal. This has been played and recommended by a number of grandmasters, so should probably be thought of as the main line. }
7. d5 { In standard fashion we push past and maintain a space advantage. } 7...
Nbd7 8. h5 Re8 9. h6
{ Consistent and preferable to the  9.hxg6  hxg6  10.Bf4  of Cruz Lledo-Esteban Moreno, Sueca 2019, when Black might have hit back with  10...e6!  . }
9... Bh8 10. Nf3
{ The knight is bound for its favourite square and Black is somewhat hampered, in part because ...e6 or ...e5 will run into a strong capture. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. King's Indian Style Main Line (6...c5)"]
[Black "5 | Slower 7th Moves | Black plays 7...Na6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 O-O 6. Be2 c5
{ Black's most popular and best response, angling for counterplay down the long, dark-square diagonal. This has been played and recommended by a number of grandmasters, so should probably be thought of as the main line. }
7. d5 { In standard fashion we push past and maintain a space advantage. } 7...
Na6 8. h5 Nc7 9. Bf4
{ A tempting alternative to  9.h6  with Black's play quite slow. White dissuades ...e6 and may now go in for a route one approach: }
9... a6 10. a4 Nd7 11. Qd2
{ Already White enjoyed a pretty strong attack with Bh6 imminent in Ruckschloss-Mace, Parthenay 2000. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. King's Indian Style Main Line (6...c5)"]
[Black "5A | KID with 6...c5 + 7...b5 | Black plays 9...Qa5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 O-O 6. Be2 c5 7. d5 b5
{ Black sacrifices a pawn and heads for Benko Gambit-like waters. } 8. cxb5
{ With e4 under threat, White should swipe the proffered pawn. } 8... a6
{ Invariably played. We dare say  8...Qa5  is also possible, but after  9.Bd2  play is likely to transpose with  9...a6  10.a4  . }
9. a4
{ A key advance, clamping down on the b5-square and so denying Black smooth development with  9.bxa6  Bxa6  . }
9... Qa5
{ 9...Nbd7  10.Nf3  . Simple development, although 10.h5!? must also be an option.  10...Qa5  11.Bd2  is a straightforward alternative to the also promising  11.O-O  axb5  12.Bxb5  of Badelka-Injac, Women's World Blitz Championship, Warsaw 2021.  Continuing the line @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/3nppbp/p2p1np1/qPpP4/P3P2P/2N2N2/1P2BPP1/R1BQK2R w KQ - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bd2  Qb4  12.Qc2  . Once again, White is just doing very well, as we saw in the notes to Black's 9th move in Vachier-Lagrave-Svidler. }
10. Bd2
{ This immediate pin-breaker is almost always a good response to the arrival of the black queen on a5. }
10... Qb4 11. Qc2
{ Covering e4 and in a much less weakening way than 11.f3 would. White is now ready to go 12.h5 or simply 12.Nf3 and we saw that  11...Nbd7  12.Nf3  is quite promising for him in the notes to Vachier-Lagrave-Svidler. As such, Black might do better to force the pace on the queenside: }
11... axb5 12. Bxb5
{ Clearly, this recapture was the whole point of White's play and now  12...--  13.h5  is still on the cards, with the idea of  13...Nxh5?  14.Nd1  . White is also all set to simply complete development with Nf3 and O-O. }
12... Ba6 13. f3
{ Only now do we weaken us slightly so as to be able to meet  13...Bxb5  with  14.Nxb5  when Black would have to ditch the queen for insufficient compensation. }
13... c4 14. Nge2
{ Completing development while still being ready to go  14...Bxb5  15.Nxb5  . }
14... Qc5 15. Qc1
{ Black doesn't have enough for a pawn here, with White set to go Be3 followed by O-O and, yes, a timely h4-h5 is still on the cards too. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. King's Indian Style Main Line (6...c5)"]
[Black "5A | KID with 6...c5 + 7...b5 | Black plays 9...axb5, 11...Qc8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 O-O 6. Be2 c5 7. d5 b5
{ Black sacrifices a pawn and heads for Benko Gambit-like waters. } 8. cxb5
{ With e4 under threat, White should swipe the proffered pawn. } 8... a6
{ Invariably played. We dare say  8...Qa5  is also possible, but after  9.Bd2  play is likely to transpose with  9...a6  10.a4  . }
9. a4
{ A key advance, clamping down on the b5-square and so denying Black smooth development with  9.bxa6  Bxa6  . }
9... axb5
{ 9...Nbd7  10.Nf3  . Simple development, although 10.h5!? must also be an option.  10...Qa5  11.Bd2  is a straightforward alternative to the also promising  11.O-O  axb5  12.Bxb5  of Badelka-Injac, Women's World Blitz Championship, Warsaw 2021.  Continuing the line @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/3nppbp/p2p1np1/qPpP4/P3P2P/2N2N2/1P2BPP1/R1BQK2R w KQ - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bd2  Qb4  12.Qc2  . Once again, White is just doing very well, as we saw in the notes to Black's 9th move in Vachier-Lagrave-Svidler. }
10. Bxb5 { Needless to say, White wants to remain a pawn ahead. } 10... Ba6
{ Consistent and very Benkoesque, although on the odd occasion Black prefers something else when White should just continue to develop:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/4ppbp/3p1np1/1BpP4/P3P2P/2N5/1P3PP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bd7  11.Bd2  is likely to transpose to our main line after  11...Bxb5  12.axb5  . If Black declines to exchange, the white bishop will be happy to tuck back in on c4: @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/3bppbp/3p1np1/1BpP4/P3P2P/2N5/1P1B1PP1/R2QK1NR b KQ - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qb6  12.Bc4!  Qxb2?  13.Rb1  and Black is losing material.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/4ppbp/3p1np1/1BpP4/P3P2P/2N5/1P3PP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Na6  11.Nf3  Nc7  12.Bc4  . White avoids an annoying exchange and maintains control, being all set to castle.  12...Ba6  13.Bxa6  . This straightforward approach seems even better than 13.Nd2.  13...Rxa6  14.O-O  .  Black shouldn't have enough for his pawn and White may now find Rb1 a useful move, overprotecting b2 and also enabling him to consider defensive ideas of b2-b3 or even of fighting back on the queenside, if allowed, with b2-b4.  Meanwhile Re1 will support the key pawn break, e4-e5,  and if the black knight leaves f6,  of course, h4-h5 may well get in on the show. }
11. Bd2
{ A strong and simple little move, dissuading ...Qa5 ideas while enabling White to recapture on b5 with the a-pawn. }
11... Qc8 12. f3
{ This nudge feels a decent response to Black's creative queen move, as was seen in Dragnev-Hillarp Persson, European Team Championship, Batumi 2019. White sidesteps  12.Nf3  Qg4  and will now complete development with Nge2 or even Nh3-f2. }
12... Bxb5 13. Nxb5
{ Not our normal response, but here  13.axb5  is fairly well met by  13...Rxa1  14.Qxa1  Qb7  followed by ...Nbd7 and ...Ra8 when it's Black who will enjoy the use of the open file.  Instead, we recapture with the knight, keeping lines relatively closed while also facilitating useful ideas of both Bc3 and Ne2-c3. }
