10. Bxb5 { Needless to say, White wants to remain a pawn ahead. } 10... Ba6
{ Consistent and very Benkoesque, although on the odd occasion Black prefers something else when White should just continue to develop:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/4ppbp/3p1np1/1BpP4/P3P2P/2N5/1P3PP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bd7  11.Bd2  is likely to transpose to our main line after  11...Bxb5  12.axb5  . If Black declines to exchange, the white bishop will be happy to tuck back in on c4: @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/3bppbp/3p1np1/1BpP4/P3P2P/2N5/1P1B1PP1/R2QK1NR b KQ - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qb6  12.Bc4!  Qxb2?  13.Rb1  and Black is losing material.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/4ppbp/3p1np1/1BpP4/P3P2P/2N5/1P3PP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Na6  11.Nf3  Nc7  12.Bc4  . White avoids an annoying exchange and maintains control, being all set to castle.  12...Ba6  13.Bxa6  . This straightforward approach seems even better than 13.Nd2.  13...Rxa6  14.O-O  .  Black shouldn't have enough for his pawn and White may now find Rb1 a useful move, overprotecting b2 and also enabling him to consider defensive ideas of b2-b3 or even of fighting back on the queenside, if allowed, with b2-b4.  Meanwhile Re1 will support the key pawn break, e4-e5,  and if the black knight leaves f6,  of course, h4-h5 may well get in on the show. }
11. Bd2
{ A strong and simple little move, dissuading ...Qa5 ideas while enabling White to recapture on b5 with the a-pawn. }
11... Bxb5 12. axb5
{ Our ideal recapture and also the only way here not to drop the e4-pawn. }
12... Nbd7 13. Nf3
{ Simple development. White wants to castle and only then begin to consider any possible invasions down the a-file. }
13... Rxa1
{ 13...Ne8?!  14.O-O  Nc7  15.Qe2  . White enjoys an even more pleasant advantage than with 15.Ra3!? supplied in Ruckschloss-Dobrowolski, Warsaw 2010.  The extra pawn is secure on b5,  the rooks connected, h4-h5 imminent and White can very much play for e4-e5,  possibly in conjunction with a disruptive b5-b6 advance. }
14. Qxa1 Qb6
{ 14...Nb6  15.O-O  Qd7  16.Qb1!  Having first completed development, White now gets off the a-file before the black rook lands on it. The queen will find a nice square on d3,  although immediately b2-b4 is something of a positional threat.  Now  16...Nc4  17.Qd3!  is much stronger than  17.b4?  Nxd2  18.Nxd2  Nh5!  . After @@StartFEN@@5rk1/3qppbp/3p1np1/1PpP4/2n1P2P/2N2N2/1P1B1PP1/1Q3RK1 w - - 5 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Qd3!  play might continue  17...Nxd2  18.Nxd2  Rb8?!  19.Nc4  .  Black might have an unopposed bishop, but White was clearly better in Urazayev-Aitbayev, Nur-Sultan 2021, with control over the position and the extra pawn secure. Already a breakthrough with e4-e5 looms and White also has a strong idea in Na5-c6. }
15. O-O
{ Calmly completing development and now Black should really involve his remaining piece in the game. }
15... Ne8 16. Qa8
{ A powerful invasion. White vacates a1 for the rook and simply threatens Qc6, all the while being temporarily happy to sacrifice a pawn: }
16... Bxc3 17. Bxc3 Qxb5 18. Qd8
{ The point and now:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@3Qnrk1/3npp1p/3p2p1/1qpP4/4P2P/2B2N2/1P3PP1/5RK1 b - - 1 18@@EndFEN@@  18...e6?  19.dxe6  fxe6  20.Ng5  would just leave Black with too many weaknesses. As such, White will regain his pawn with a large advantage.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@3Qnrk1/3npp1p/3p2p1/1qpP4/4P2P/2B2N2/1P3PP1/5RK1 b - - 1 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Nef6  19.Qxe7  Re8  20.Qxd6  Nxe4  21.Qc7!  Nxc3  22.bxc3  . This largely forcing line followed by h4-h5 and or c3-c4 saw White smoothly proceed to victory in both Ruckschloss-Balogh, Slovakian League 2018, and Zarubitski-Volianuk, Minsk 2021. }
