{ 14...Nb6  15.O-O  Qd7  16.Qb1!  Having first completed development, White now gets off the a-file before the black rook lands on it. The queen will find a nice square on d3,  although immediately b2-b4 is something of a positional threat.  Now  16...Nc4  17.Qd3!  is much stronger than  17.b4?  Nxd2  18.Nxd2  Nh5!  . After @@StartFEN@@5rk1/3qppbp/3p1np1/1PpP4/2n1P2P/2N2N2/1P1B1PP1/1Q3RK1 w - - 5 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Qd3!  play might continue  17...Nxd2  18.Nxd2  Rb8?!  19.Nc4  .  Black might have an unopposed bishop, but White was clearly better in Urazayev-Aitbayev, Nur-Sultan 2021, with control over the position and the extra pawn secure. Already a breakthrough with e4-e5 looms and White also has a strong idea in Na5-c6. }
15. O-O
{ Calmly completing development and now Black should really involve his remaining piece in the game. }
15... Rb8 16. Qa6
{ Beginning to invade with Ra1 next up and Black unable to exchange queens on a6 due to the resulting monster passed pawn there. We saw how White exploited his edge and later made fine use of Harry in Vachier-Lagrave-Svidler, Saint Louis 2021. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. King's Indian Style Main Line (6...c5)"]
[Black "5B | KID with 6...c5 + 7...e6 | Black plays 9...a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 O-O 6. Be2 c5 7. d5 e6
{ Black's most critical continuation, challenging in the centre without delay. }
8. h5
{ The one thing that Black's last move didn't do is prevent our favourite advance, so on marches Harry. }
8... exd5
{ The typical Modern Benoni follow-up and invariably played. Otherwise, White should simply continue with h6 Bh8; Bg5,  cramping Black, and we'll see  8...a6  9.a4  by transposition in Williams-Palliser. }
9. exd5
{ Maintaining full control by retaining a symmetrical structure and so denying Black the easier counterplay both  9.hxg6  fxg6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3pbp/3p1np1/2pp3P/2P1P3/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR w KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.cxd5  Re8  allow him.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3pbp/3p1np1/2pp3P/2P1P3/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR w KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.exd5!  White is ready to increase the pressure with Bg5 and h5-h6. Another useful move is likely to be Qd2 and even Kf1 may prove useful if White wishes to step off the e-file. }
9... a6 10. a4
{ Ruling out any notion of ...b5,  although White can also begin with  10.h6  if you prefer. }
10... Nbd7 11. h6
{ Cramping and preferable to the overly-ambitious  11.g4?!  of Ruckschloss-Treybal, Slovakian League 2006, when  11...Ne5  would have offered Black decent counterplay. }
11... Bh8 12. Bg5
{ The most active square for the bishop and a choice consistent with our play in the main line, although  12.Nf3  , possibly looking to go Ng5,  must also be a decent option.  After  12.Bg5  White is all set to go 13.Nf3 and 14.O-O,  so Black pretty much must head forwards with his knight: }
12... Ne5 13. Kf1
{ Keeping pieces on, unlike  13.Nf3  Nxf3+  14.Bxf3  Re8+   After @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rkb/1p3p1p/p2p1npP/2pPn1B1/P1P5/2N5/1P2BPP1/R2QK1NR w KQ - 3 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Kf1!?  White has the simple idea of g2-g3 and Kg2 to untangle his position, may go f2-f3 to keep Black out of g4 @@StartBracket@@the king's knight can always emerge via h3@@EndBracket@@, and Rh4 is another idea to very much bear in mind, introducing ideas of Rf4.  In short, White's game-plan is to deny Black counterplay and only then begin to head forwards. }
13... Qb6 14. Ra3
{ An important response to Black's queen move. White can now maintain control of the queenside with Rb3 and, of course, snatching on b2 would see Black losing the queen. }
