12... Bf5 13. Rc1
{ White wisely steps off the long diagonal and away from the gaze of Black's two raking bishops. }
13... Nbd7
{ 13...Ne4!?  might be a better try, but here too White can retain sufficient control:  14.Nxe4  Rxe4  15.Rh4!?  --  exchanging off Black's most active piece while intending  16.Rxe4  Bxe4  17.f3  Bf5  18.g4  to turn the black light-squared bishop back into a problem piece, and the check need not be feared:  @@StartFEN@@rn4kb/pp3p1p/1q1p2pP/2pP1bB1/2P1r2R/1P6/P3BPP1/2RQK1N1 b - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Qa5+?!  16.Qd2  Qxd2+  17.Kxd2  Rxh4  18.Bxh4  when Black's lack of counterplay, backwards d-pawn and potentially cramped pieces mean that White will be clearly for choice as he expands with f2-f4 and g2-g4. }
14. Kf1 { Unpinning and so threatening g2-g4. } 14... Ne5 15. Rh4
{ This kept Black out of g4 and so left White in control in Stefanova-Kamalidenova, FIDE Women's Grand Swiss, Riga 2021.  Next up will be g2-g3 and Kg2, as White gradually builds towards a timely f2-f4 or g3-g4, quite content to slowly exploit the extra space and the fine, long-term cramping effect exerted by Harry. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. King's Indian Style Main Line (6...c5)"]
[Black "5B | KID with 6...c5 + 7...e6 | Black plays 9...Re8, 12...Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 O-O 6. Be2 c5 7. d5 e6
{ Black's most critical continuation, challenging in the centre without delay. }
8. h5
{ The one thing that Black's last move didn't do is prevent our favourite advance, so on marches Harry. }
8... exd5
{ The typical Modern Benoni follow-up and invariably played. Otherwise, White should simply continue with h6 Bh8; Bg5,  cramping Black, and we'll see  8...a6  9.a4  by transposition in Williams-Palliser. }
9. exd5
{ Maintaining full control by retaining a symmetrical structure and so denying Black the easier counterplay both  9.hxg6  fxg6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3pbp/3p1np1/2pp3P/2P1P3/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR w KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.cxd5  Re8  allow him.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3pbp/3p1np1/2pp3P/2P1P3/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR w KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.exd5!  White is ready to increase the pressure with Bg5 and h5-h6. Another useful move is likely to be Qd2 and even Kf1 may prove useful if White wishes to step off the e-file. }
9... Re8
{ Black's main move by quite some margin, pinning and so threatening ...Nxh5. It has also been the choice of David Vigorito and Gawain Jones in their respective King's Indian repertoires.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3pbp/3p1np1/2pP3P/2P5/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qb6?!  10.h6  Bh8  11.g4!  when Black is already running out of good moves, with f2-f3 set to keep him out of g4 and do note that problem bishop on c8. Meanwhile White might go Qc2 and Bg5 or Bf4,  or untangle his kingside pieces with Nh3-g5 followed by O-O or Kf1.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3pbp/3p1np1/2pP3P/2P5/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qe7?!  10.h6!  White has often preferred 10.Kf1 and 10.hxg6 here, but why not cramp à la AlphaZero and then pin?  10...Bh8  11.Bg5  Pinning and, of course, ...Qe5 can just be met by Nf3.   11...Re8  12.Nf3  . White simply intends O-O followed by Re1 with a pleasant space advantage right across the board, although we should admit that  12.Rh4!?  Qf8  13.Kf1  is also quite tempting and strong. }
10. h6
{ Grischuk's and Giri's choice, clamping down on Black in AlphaZero style once again.  White's most popular choice has actually been  10.hxg6  , but after  10...fxg6  11.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@  11.Bh6?!  Bxh6  12.Rxh6  Nbd7  doesn't lead anywhere for White@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp4bp/3p1np1/2pP4/2P5/2N2N2/PP2BPP1/R1BQK2R b KQ - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nbd7  Black should have enough counterplay with ...Ne5 and/or ...Qe7 on their way.  Likewise, @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp3pbp/3p1np1/2pP3P/2P5/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQK1NR w KQ - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Kf1  Ne4!  11.Nxe4  Rxe4  12.Nf3  Bg4  should be OK for Black. }
10... Bh8
{ 10...Bf8?!  11.Bg5  Be7  12.Qd2  only leaves Black a little cramped and low on counterplay while White can go Nf3,  O-O @@StartBracket@@or even O-O-O@@EndBracket@@, and Rae1 to maintain control.  12...Nbd7!?  13.O-O-O!  @@StartBracket@@here  13...Ng4?  would lose a piece, whereas @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/pp1nbp1p/3p1npP/2pP2B1/2P5/2N5/PP1QBPP1/R3K1NR w KQ - 5 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Nf3  Ng4  isn't so clear@@EndBracket@@ and now:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/pp1nbp1p/3p1npP/2pP2B1/2P5/2N5/PP1QBPP1/2KR2NR b - - 6 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nxd5?  14.Bxe7  Nxe7  15.Qxd6  . Black might have deployed a tactic, but finds himself badly suffering, being pinned down the d-file and rather vulnerable on the dark squares.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/pp1nbp1p/3p1npP/2pP2B1/2P5/2N5/PP1QBPP1/2KR2NR b - - 6 13@@EndFEN@@  13...a6  14.Re1!?  . White simply prepares to land his bishop with some force on b5 and in the event of a break and exchanges there, will now continue with Nf3 and Qf4 if unpestered, while continuing to provoke a certain tactic:  14...Nxd5  15.Bxe7  Nxe7  16.Qxd6  .  Now Black surely doesn't have anything better than forcing the queen backwards:  16...Nf5  17.Qf4!  Nd4  18.Nf3  wasting no time challenging Black's control of d4. White is simply doing pretty well, with his queen still in touch with the kingside, where Black's king is a definite target, and it can easily slip back to d2 or g3 if needed. }
11. Bg5
{ Consistent and best, pinning Black, although Giri did once prefer  11.Kf1  in a blitz game. Now  11...Qa5  fails to inconvenience White after  12.Qd2  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1kb/pp3p1p/3p1npP/2pP4/2P5/2N5/PP2BPP1/R1BQ1KNR b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...a6  12.a4  Qb6  can be met by  13.b3  , as per our main line, or even  13.Ra2!?  , which neatly makes use of the a-pawn's advance to retain control and may be followed by a4-a5. }
11... Qb6
{ Gawain Jones's recommendation, unpinning.   11...b5  12.cxb5  a6  13.a4!  is, of course, our standard method of dealing with any Benko-type play and was seen in Urazayev-Schmakel, Internet  (blitz)  2021:   13...Qa5  14.Bd2  unpinning and preparing to recapture with the knight on b5,  after which Bc3,  as well as Nf3 and O-O may well follow. }
12. b3
{ A brave choice, as it weakens the dark squares, but also a better one than  12.Qd2  Ne4!  . It transpires that White is able to maintain control, with Rc1 next up and Bd2 if needed. }
12... Bg4 13. Kf1
{ Calmly breaking the pin and a less risky choice than  13.f3  Bd7  when Black will follow up with ...Nh5. }
13... Bxe2+ 14. Ngxe2 Nbd7 15. f3
{ White keeps Black out of e4 and so retains an edge.  White's immediate plan is to expand with Qd2, g2-g4 and Qf4, with Re1 possibly thrown in too. Black should then find his position more than a little cramped, while the white king will be quite safe on g2 or even f2.  Another idea after Re1 or Rc1 is to simply go Ng3 and Nge4, beginning to press on d6. }
