{ @@HeaderStart@@Simon Williams – Richard Palliser@@HeaderEnd@@Ron Banwell Memorial, London 2000 }
1. c4
{ Simon was still a regular English exponent at the turn of the century and hadn't yet progressed to our  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.h4!?  when  3...Bg7  4.Nc3  O-O  5.e4  d6  6.Be2  c5  7.d5  would transpose to the game. }
1... g6 2. Nc3 Bg7 3. e4 d6 4. d4 { Abandoning Iron English waters... } 4...
Nf6 5. Be2 O-O 6. h4 { ...and this is why: Harry is deployed! } 6... c5 7. d5
a6
{ This is just too slow, or at least leaves Black with an inferior version of Line 5B. }
8. a4
{ Ever an important reaction to ...a6 in such positions, clamping down on b5 and Black's counterplay. }
8... e6 9. h5 exd5 10. hxg6
{ Simon rolls the dice, but objectively, by analogy with Line 5B, White should prefer  10.exd5!  , thereby continuing to restrict Black's counterplay. Bg5 and h5-h6 may well follow. }
10... d4
{ Richard can still just about remember that he was keen to try and deny Simon the initiative, but this is too ambitious, whereas matters would just have been pretty unclear after  10...fxg6!  followed by ...Nbd7 or  11.e5!?  dxe5  12.cxd5  e4  . }
11. gxh7+ Kh8
{ Essential or at least it's hard to believe Black would have survived on the kingside after  11...Nxh7?  12.Nd5  . }
12. Nd5 Nxe4 13. Nf3
{ The knight can't come to g5 here, but has another role in mind. } 13... Bg4
{ 13...Nd7  would have been a tougher defence, intending  14.Nh4  Ne5  . } 14.
Nh4 { Suddenly White has the rather crude idea of Nf4 and mate on g6. } 14...
Re8
{ The only real try,  14...Bxe2?  losing to  15.Kxe2!  Re8  16.Kf1  followed by Qf3 or Qg4 and Nf5. }
15. Nf4 { With a certain threat. } 15... Qf6
{ It would have taken a braver man than Richard to play  15...Kxh7  and after  16.f3  Ng3  17.Nf5+!  Nxh1  18.fxg4  it's very hard to believe that Black would have survived. }
16. f3 { Coolly dealing with Black's threats. } 16... Ng3 17. fxg4 Nxh1
{ 17...Rxe2+!?  18.Nxe2  Nxh1  is proposed by the modern-day engines and would have been a reasonable try, although after  19.Nf5  Nc6  20.Ra3!  White remains clearly for choice. }
18. g5 Qd8
{ 18...Qxg5!  19.Nfg6+  Qxg6  20.Nxg6+  fxg6  was well worth a try, although Black would probably have eventually come up short after  21.Ra3!  . }
19. Qd3 { Threatening mate in five via checks on g6 and e7. } 19... Be5
{ Even here  19...Qxg5  20.Nfg6+  Qxg6!  21.Nxg6+  fxg6  22.Qxg6  Nd7  should have been tried, since White is not exactly well coordinated, winning gradually with care though he should be after  23.Bf4!  Ne5  24.Bxe5  Rxe5  25.Kd2  Nf2  26.Bf3  . }
20. Nhg6+
{ Simon was never going to miss such a blow and subsequent follow-up. } 20...
fxg6 21. Nxg6+ Kg7 22. Qh3
{ The point. The black king is going to be hunted down to its doom. } 22...
Bg3+
{ Alternatively,  22...Kxg6  23.Qh6+  Kf7  24.g6+  Ke7  25.Bg5+  Bf6  26.Bxf6+  Kxf6  27.g7+  , and @@StartFEN@@rn1qr3/1p4kP/p2p2N1/2p1b1P1/P1Pp4/7Q/1P2B1P1/R1B1K2n b Q - 2 22@@EndFEN@@  22...Qa5+!?  23.Bd2!  Bg3+  24.Kf1  Qxd2  25.h8=Q+!  Rxh8  26.Qxh8+  Kxg6  27.Qf6+  Kh7  28.g6+  Kh6  29.g7+  Kh7  30.Qf8!  Qf4+  31.Bf3  win by force, as pointed out by Angus Dunnington in BCM at the time. }
23. Kf1 Kxg6
{ White doesn't capture after  23...Rf8+  , but simply wins with  24.Kg1  . }
24. Qh6+ Kf5 25. Bg4+ Ke5 { Or if  25...Kxg4  26.Qh3  . } 26. Qg7+ Ke4 27. Qg6+
Ke5 28. Qf5# { A lovely attack by Simon, even if it pains Richard to say so! }
