{ @@HeaderStart@@Afterword: ...h4 Against the Modern@@HeaderEnd@@ } 1. d4 g6
{ Likewise,  1...d6  2.c4  and now:  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e5  isn't the choice of a Modern player, but does throw a spanner in White's h4 works. That said, after  3.Nf3  e4  4.Ng5  f5  5.Nc3  White might very well use Harry to help clamp down and exploit his space advantage, as with  5...Nf6  6.h4!?  .  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...g6  3.h4!?  is very much possible. }
2. c4 Bg7 3. h4
{ A rare choice here, but it can hardly be a bad one of course.   3.Nc3  d6  4.h4!?  would also be a perfectly valid move order. }
3... h5
{ Trying to block.  A@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppppppbp/6p1/8/2PP3P/8/PP2PPP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  would, of course, simply transpose to our main course here.  B@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppppppbp/6p1/8/2PP3P/8/PP2PPP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.d5  might well transpose too, while after  4...d6  White can avoid any potential ...Bxc3+ exchange by beginning with  5.h5!  .  C@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppppppbp/6p1/8/2PP3P/8/PP2PPP1/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6  4.h5  already looks like a pleasant early initiative for White, with 5.h6 quite possibly already a positional threat. }
4. e4
{ And why not advance so before Nc3 with Black's king's knight still at home? }
4... d6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ 5...Nf6  6.Be2  would take play back into Line 2A.  So might @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1ppb1/3p2p1/7p/2PPP2P/2N5/PP3PP1/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  6.d5  in the event of  6...Nf6  . Note too that now ...h5 has been played, White need not worry about  6...Bxc3+  7.bxc3  , since his knight should be able to take up a strong role in typical fashion on g5. }
6. d5 Nd4 7. Nge2
{ This position is known without the inclusion of the h-pawns and here White should have an especially decent version.  If Black defends the knight with a pawn,  8.Be3  will follow and at some point soon that dark-squared bishop may well find itself taking up a nice role on g5 where it can't be kicked away by ...h6. }
